{'count': 20, 'next': None, 'previous': None, 'results': [{'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203134, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': "<p>A company runs a production environment in an Amazon VPC configured with the CIDR block 175.10.0.0/16. The company runs large batch computing workloads within the VPC and has nearly depleted the IP address space.</p><p>The company must extend the VPC by allocating an additional block of addresses. Which CIDR blocks meet the company's requirements? (Select TWO.)</p>", 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The company has used up their address space and must add a secondary CIDR block to an existing VPC. This is allowed but with some restrictions. The following restrictions discount three of the available answers:</p><p>· If the primary CIDR block is publicly routable (non-RFC 1918) you cannot associate a secondary CIDR from the RFC 1918 ranges.</p><p>· The CIDR block must not overlap with any existing CIDR block that\'s associated with the VPC.</p><p>The following table provides an overview of permitted and restricted CIDR block associations, which depend on the IPv4 address range in which your VPC\'s primary CIDR block resides.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_13-53-08-4d05fdb430d203ad02d86ca59d547ab3.jpg"><p>From the table above we know that we cannot add any RFC 1918 address ranges as the secondary CIDR block because the primary CIDR block is non-RFC 1918. Therefore, the 172.16.0.0/20 and 10.11.0.0/16 CIDR blocks would be restricted.</p><p>The 175.11.0.0/8 address ranges overlaps with the existing 175.10.0.0/16 address range.</p><p>The 175.11.0.0/16 and 196.15.0.0/20 CIDR blocks are both non-RFC 1918 and do not overlap with the existing primary CIDR block and are therefore permitted associations.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"175.11.0.0/16" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"196.15.0.0/20" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "172.16.0.0/20" is incorrect.</p><p>This is an RFC 1918 address range and is not a permitted association when the primary CIDR block is a non-RFC 1918 address range.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "175.11.0.0/8" is incorrect.</p><p>This is a non-RFC 1918 address range (permitted), but it overlaps with the existing 175.10.0.0/16 address range.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "10.11.0.0/16" is incorrect.</p><p>This is an RFC 1918 address range and is not a permitted association when the primary CIDR block is a non-RFC 1918 address range.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>175.11.0.0/16</p>', '<p>172.16.0.0/20</p>', '<p>196.15.0.0/20</p>', '<p>175.11.0.0/8</p>', '<p>10.11.0.0/16</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': "A company runs a production environment in an Amazon VPC configured with the CIDR block 175.10.0.0/16. The company runs large batch computing workloads within the VPC and has nearly depleted the IP address space.The company must extend the VPC by allocating an additional block of addresses. Which CIDR blocks meet the company's requirements? (Select TWO.)", 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203136, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is designing a domain name resolution solution for a client. The company plans to migrate all DNS records to Amazon Route 53. The company’s public website uses the domain name “example.com” and the company plans to use “internal.example.com” for private services running in an Amazon VPC.</p><p>Which steps should the network engineer take to configure split-view DNS for the client?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You can use Route 53 to configure split-view DNS, also known as split-horizon DNS. In split-view DNS, you use the same domain name (example.com) for internal uses (internal.example.com) and external uses, such as your public website (www.example.com).</p><p>To configure split-view DNS, you perform the following steps:</p><ol><li><p>Create public and private hosted zones that have the same name. (Split-view DNS still works if you\'re using another DNS service for the public hosted zone.)</p></li><li><p>Associate one or more Amazon VPCs with the private hosted zone. Route 53 Resolver uses the private hosted zone to route DNS queries in the specified VPCs.</p></li><li><p>Create records in each hosted zone. Records in the public hosted zone control how internet traffic is routed, and records in the private hosted zone control how traffic is routed in your Amazon VPCs.</p></li></ol><p>If you have private and public hosted zones that have overlapping namespaces, such as example.com and internal.example.com, Resolver routes traffic based on the most specific match. When users are logged into an EC2 instance in an Amazon VPC that you have associated with the private hosted zone, here\'s how Route 53 Resolver handles DNS queries:</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and a private hosted zone for internal.example.com. Associate the Amazon VPC with the private hosted zone" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and internal.example.com. Associate the Amazon VPC with the public hosted zone for internal.example.com" is incorrect.</p><p>The internal.example.com hosted zone should be a private hosted zone.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and internal.example.com. Add NS records for the subdomain to the zone file for the parent domain" is incorrect.</p><p>The internal.example.com hosted zone should be a private hosted zone and the VPC should be associated with the private hosted zone as domain delegation using NS records is not necessary.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and a private hosted zone for internal.example.com. Add NS records for the subdomain to the zone file for the parent domain" is incorrect.</p><p>domain delegation using NS records is not necessary; instead, the VPC can be associated with the private hosted zone.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/hosted-zone-private-considerations.html#hosted-zone-private-considerations-split-view-dns">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/hosted-zone-private-considerations.html#hosted-zone-private-considerations-split-view-dns</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and internal.example.com. Associate the Amazon VPC with the public hosted zone for internal.example.com.</p>', '<p>Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and internal.example.com. Add NS records for the subdomain to the zone file for the parent domain.</p>', '<p>Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and a private hosted zone for internal.example.com. Associate the Amazon VPC with the private hosted zone.</p>', '<p>Create a Route 53 public hosted zone for example.com and a private hosted zone for internal.example.com. Add NS records for the subdomain to the zone file for the parent domain.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is designing a domain name resolution solution for a client. The company plans to migrate all DNS records to Amazon Route 53. The company’s public website uses the domain name “example.com” and the company plans to use “internal.example.com” for private services running in an Amazon VPC.Which steps should the network engineer take to configure split-view DNS for the client?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203138, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A security incident occurred whereby Amazon EC2 instances within a VPC made unauthorized connection attempts to a specific public IP address. The security team updated the Network ACL for the subnets to block access to the IP address. The team would like to be notified if any additional connection attempts are initiated to the malicious IP address.</p><p>What is the MOST cost-effective solution that meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Using VPC flow logs with a CloudWatch metric filter is more cost-effective than using AWS GuardDuty.</p><p>There are three costs associated with this solution:</p><p>1. Data ingestion and archival charges for vended logs apply when you publish flow logs to CloudWatch Logs or to Amazon S3.</p><p>2. CloudWatch Logs - Collect (Data Ingestion).</p><p>3. CloudWatch Logs - Analyze (Logs Insights queries).</p><p>To ensure the lowest cost it is important to set the VPC flow log to log only reject events as this will mean less data for the CloudWatch metric filter to analyze.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a VPC flow log for the VPC and log rejected traffic. Set the destination to Amazon CloudWatch and create a CloudWatch metric filter for all events that sends a notification to the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a VPC flow log for the VPC and log all traffic. Set the destination to Amazon CloudWatch and create a CloudWatch metric filter for reject events that sends a notification to the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged" is incorrect.</p><p>If all traffic is logged, then it will increase the cost of analyzing the data using CloudWatch Logs metric filters. It is better to reduce the volume of data to be analyzed by only logging rejected traffic.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable Amazon GuardDuty on the account and upload a threat list that includes the malicious IP. Create a VPC flow log for the VPC and log all traffic. Configure GuardDuty to monitor the VPC flow log and use Amazon EventBridge to notify the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged" is incorrect.</p><p>GuardDuty is more expensive than using the solution with VPC flow logs and CloudWatch metric filters.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable Amazon GuardDuty on the account and upload a threat list that includes the malicious IP. Configure AWS CloudTrail Event Logs as the data source for GuardDuty and use Amazon EventBridge to notify the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged" is incorrect.</p><p>AWS CloudTrail will not log any information relating to connections to the malicious IP address. CloudTrail only logs API actions.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/flow-logs-cwl.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/flow-logs-cwl.html</a></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/cloudwatch/pricing/">https://aws.amazon.com/cloudwatch/pricing/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a VPC flow log for the VPC and log all traffic. Set the destination to Amazon CloudWatch and create a CloudWatch metric filter for reject events that sends a notification to the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged.</p>', '<p>Create a VPC flow log for the VPC and log rejected traffic. Set the destination to Amazon CloudWatch and create a CloudWatch metric filter for all events that sends a notification to the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged.</p>', '<p>Enable Amazon GuardDuty on the account and upload a threat list that includes the malicious IP. Create a VPC flow log for the VPC and log all traffic. Configure GuardDuty to monitor the VPC flow log and use Amazon EventBridge to notify the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged.</p>', '<p>Enable Amazon GuardDuty on the account and upload a threat list that includes the malicious IP. Configure AWS CloudTrail Event Logs as the data source for GuardDuty and use Amazon EventBridge to notify the security team if rejected connection attempts to the malicious IP are logged.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A security incident occurred whereby Amazon EC2 instances within a VPC made unauthorized connection attempts to a specific public IP address. The security team updated the Network ACL for the subnets to block access to the IP address. The team would like to be notified if any additional connection attempts are initiated to the malicious IP address.What is the MOST cost-effective solution that meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203140, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer has enabled VPC Flow Logs to troubleshoot a connectivity issue between an EC2 application instance and an EC2 database instance in another subnet. The VPC flow logs recorded ACCEPT records for the connection from the client to the EC2 database instance and REJECT records for the response from the EC2 database instance to the EC2 application instance.</p><p>What is the MOST likely reason for the failed connection response?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Network Access Control Lists (Network ACLs) are stateless firewalls that operate at the subnet level. With a Network ACL you must allow both the connection from client to server and the response traffic from server to client.</p><p>In this case the most likely cause of the issue is that the EC2 database instance’s network ACL is denying the outbound response traffic. This would be logged in the VPC flow logs as a REJECT.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"The EC2 database instance’s network ACL is denying outbound connections" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The EC2 database instance’s security group is denying inbound connections" is incorrect.</p><p>An ACCEPT was logged for the inbound connection so this is not the cause of the issue.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The EC2 application instance’s security group is denying inbound connections" is incorrect.</p><p>Security groups are stateful so the response traffic coming back to the EC2 application instance would be allowed as it is related to the outbound connection made from the instance.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The EC2 application instance’s security group is denying outbound connections" is incorrect.</p><p>In this case the packet would be rejected and the ACCEPT record would not have been logged so this is not the cause of the issue.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>The EC2 database instance’s security group is denying inbound connections.</p>', '<p>The EC2 application instance’s security group is denying inbound connections.</p>', '<p>The EC2 database instance’s network ACL is denying outbound connections.</p>', '<p>The EC2 application instance’s security group is denying outbound connections.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer has enabled VPC Flow Logs to troubleshoot a connectivity issue between an EC2 application instance and an EC2 database instance in another subnet. The VPC flow logs recorded ACCEPT records for the connection from the client to the EC2 database instance and REJECT records for the response from the EC2 database instance to the EC2 application instance.What is the MOST likely reason for the failed connection response?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203142, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A security team is responsible for monitoring a group of AWS accounts. The security team does not have direct access to all of the AWS accounts but must be able to monitor for malicious or unauthorized behavior.</p><p>Which of the following solutions will enable the security team to monitor the resources across all AWS accounts with the LEAST administrative overhead?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To manage multiple accounts in Amazon GuardDuty, you must choose a single AWS account to be the administrator account for GuardDuty. You can then associate other AWS accounts with the administrator account as member accounts.</p><p>There are two ways to associate accounts with a GuardDuty administrator account: either through an AWS Organizations organization that both accounts are members of, or by sending an invitation through GuardDuty.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create an Amazon GuardDuty administrator account within an AWS account the security team has access to. Add the monitored accounts as member accounts in Amazon GuardDuty" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure Amazon GuardDuty in each AWS account. Create a role within each monitored AWS account with permissions to GuardDuty. Instruct the security team to assume the role in each monitored account" is incorrect.</p><p>This would require much more administrative overhead compared to the correct answer.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a third-party threat detection service in an AWS account the security team has access to. Configure the route tables in each monitored AWS account to route all traffic through the third-party threat detection appliances" is incorrect.</p><p>This solution is incomplete and would only ever work for packet inspection. GuardDuty offers a threat detection service that monitors AWS accounts and workloads for malicious activity and delivers detailed security findings for visibility and remediation.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable Amazon Macie within each AWS account and configure centralized reporting in the account the security team has access to" is incorrect.</p><p>Amazon Macie is a fully managed data security and data privacy service that uses machine learning and pattern matching to discover and protect your sensitive data in AWS. Macie does not detect malicious or unauthorized behavior.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_accounts.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_accounts.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure Amazon GuardDuty in each AWS account. Create a role within each monitored AWS account with permissions to GuardDuty. Instruct the security team to assume the role in each monitored account.</p>', '<p>Create an Amazon GuardDuty administrator account within an AWS account the security team has access to. Add the monitored accounts as member accounts in Amazon GuardDuty.</p>', '<p>Deploy a third-party threat detection service in an AWS account the security team has access to. Configure the route tables in each monitored AWS account to route all traffic through the third-party threat detection appliances.</p>', '<p>Enable Amazon Macie within each AWS account and configure centralized reporting in the account the security team has access to.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A security team is responsible for monitoring a group of AWS accounts. The security team does not have direct access to all of the AWS accounts but must be able to monitor for malicious or unauthorized behavior.Which of the following solutions will enable the security team to monitor the resources across all AWS accounts with the LEAST administrative overhead?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203144, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is unable to connect to an Amazon EC2 instance which keeps returning a “request timed out” error message. The engineer is connecting from the public IP address of 200.10.11.12 and the instance’s private IP address is 172.31.16.25.</p><p>A VPC flow log has captured the following information:</p><p>2 0123456789992 eni-12345c7b2012345678 200.10.11.12 172.31.16.25 0 0 1 4 232 1357101112 1357101182 ACCEPT OK</p><p>2 0123456789992 eni-12345c7b2012345678 172.31.16.25 200.10.11.12 0 0 1 4 232 1357101112 1357101182 REJECT OK</p><p>What is the most likely cause of the problem?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The information captured in the flow log shows that the inbound data was accepted but the outbound response data was rejected. The most likely cause of this issue is that a Network ACL is not configured correctly to allow the response traffic going outbound.</p><p>Network ACLs are not stateful and therefore require that a rule is configured for both inbound and outbound traffic, even if the outbound traffic is response traffic to a connection that was accepted inbound.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Network ACL outbound rules" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Network ACL inbound rules" is incorrect.</p><p>The inbound traffic was accepted so this is not the issue.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Security group inbound rules" is incorrect.</p><p>The inbound rules for the target instance must be configured to allow the traffic as we can see an ACCEPT. The source instance is receiving response traffic and security groups are stateful, so the inbound rules are not relevant.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Security group outbound rules" is incorrect.</p><p>The outbound rules for the source instance security group must be correct as the packet was delivered with an ACCEPT. The outbound rules for the target instance would not be relevant as response traffic for an accepted connection would be allowed.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Security group inbound rules.</p>', '<p>Security group outbound rules.</p>', '<p>Network ACL inbound rules.</p>', '<p>Network ACL outbound rules.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is unable to connect to an Amazon EC2 instance which keeps returning a “request timed out” error message. The engineer is connecting from the public IP address of 200.10.11.12 and the instance’s private IP address is 172.31.16.25.A VPC flow log has captured the following information:2 0123456789992 eni-12345c7b2012345678 200.10.11.12 172.31.16.25 0 0 1 4 232 1357101112 1357101182 ACCEPT OK2 0123456789992 eni-12345c7b2012345678 172.31.16.25 200.10.11.12 0 0 1 4 232 1357101112 1357101182 REJECT OKWhat is the most likely cause of the problem?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203146, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An Amazon VPC has been created with the 172.31.0.0/16 CIDR block. Within this VPC, which of the following addresses are provided by Amazon for DNS resolution using the Route 53 Resolver?</p><p>(Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>When you create a VPC, the Route 53 Resolver that is created by default, maps to a DNS server that runs on a reserved IP address for the VPC network range, plus 2. For example, the DNS Server on a 10.0.0.0/16 network is located at 10.0.0.2.</p><p>Route 53 Resolver is also available at 169.254.169.253.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"172.31.0.2" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"169.254.169.253" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "10.0.0.53" is incorrect. This is not an address used by Route 53 Resolver.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "172.31.0.1" is incorrect. The .2 address is used, not the .1 address in the CIDR.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "169.254.169.254" is incorrect. This address is used for instance metadata, not the Route 53 Resolver service.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resolver.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resolver.html</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-dns.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-dns.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>10.0.0.53</p>', '<p>172.31.0.2</p>', '<p>172.31.0.1</p>', '<p>169.254.169.253</p>', '<p>169.254.169.254</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'd'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'An Amazon VPC has been created with the 172.31.0.0/16 CIDR block. Within this VPC, which of the following addresses are provided by Amazon for DNS resolution using the Route 53 Resolver?(Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203148, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has deployed redundant AWS Direct Connect connections to an Amazon VPC. The VPC is configured using BGP metrics so that one Direct Connect connection is used as the primary traffic path and the other is the failover traffic path. The company wants the primary Direct Connect connection to fail to the secondary in less than one second.</p><p>What should be done to meet this requirement?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>BFD is a detection protocol that provides fast forwarding path failure detection times. These fast failure detection times facilitate faster routing reconvergence times.</p><p>It\'s a best practice to enable BFD for fast failure detection and failover when connecting to AWS services over Direct Connect connections or VPNs. Enabling BFD for your Direct Connect connection allows the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) neighbor relationship to be quickly torn down. Otherwise, by default, BGP waits for three keep-alives to fail at a hold-down time of 90 seconds.</p><p>Asynchronous BFD is automatically enabled for Direct Connect virtual interfaces on the AWS side. However, you must configure your router to enable asynchronous BFD for your connection. The default AWS BFD liveness detection minimum interval is 300 ms. The default BFD liveness detection multiplier is three.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Enable Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) on the company\'s router with a detection minimum interval of 300 ms and a BFD liveness detection multiplier of 3" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) on the virtual private gateway with a detection minimum interval of 300 ms and a DPD liveliness detection multiplier of 3" is incorrect.</p><p>As explained above, asynchronous BDF is enabled for Direct Connect virtual interfaces on the AWS side but you must configure it on the customer router.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure BGP on the company\'s router with a keep-alive to 300 ms and the BGP hold timer to 900 ms" is incorrect.</p><p>BFD must be configured to improve the convergence times rather than BGP.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable Dead Peer Detection (DPD) on the company\'s router with a detection minimum interval of 300 ms and a DPD liveliness detection multiplier of 3" is incorrect.</p><p>Dead Peer Detection enables the VPN devices to rapidly identify when a network condition prevents delivery of packets across the internet. This is relevant to dynamically routed IPSec VPN connections and not to a DX connection.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/enable-bfd-direct-connect/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/enable-bfd-direct-connect/</a></p>', 'answers': ["<p>Configure BGP on the company's router with a keep-alive to 300 ms and the BGP hold timer to 900 ms.</p>", "<p>Enable Dead Peer Detection (DPD) on the company's router with a detection minimum interval of 300 ms and a DPD liveliness detection multiplier of 3.</p>", "<p>Enable Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) on the company's router with a detection minimum interval of 300 ms and a BFD liveness detection multiplier of 3.</p>", '<p>Enable Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) on the virtual private gateway with a detection minimum interval of 300 ms and a DPD liveliness detection multiplier of 3.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has deployed redundant AWS Direct Connect connections to an Amazon VPC. The VPC is configured using BGP metrics so that one Direct Connect connection is used as the primary traffic path and the other is the failover traffic path. The company wants the primary Direct Connect connection to fail to the secondary in less than one second.What should be done to meet this requirement?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203150, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company stores application logs in an Amazon S3 bucket in the us-west-1 Region. The company has established an AWS Direct Connect connection to the us-east-1 Region.</p><p>How can the company access the application log bucket over the Direct Connect connection?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To access public resources in a remote Region, you must set up a public virtual interface and establish a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) session. After you have created a public virtual interface and established a BGP session to it, your router learns the routes of the other public AWS Regions.</p><p>Using a public VIF you can connect to Amazon S3 buckets in all AWS Regions. This solution will allow the applications to connect to the bucket in us-west-1 using the Direct Connect connection.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Set up a public virtual interface and establish a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) session" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Direct Connect gateway in the us-west-1 Region and connect over a private virtual interface" is incorrect.</p><p>A Direct Connect gateway is not required for this solution as a public VIF can be used to connect to public AWS resources in all Regions.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Set up a transit virtual interface and establish a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) session" is incorrect.</p><p>A transit virtual interface is used to connect to an AWS Transit Gateway which is not required or used in this solution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an AWS Managed VPN across the Direct Connect connection that terminates at a virtual private gateway in the us-west-1 Region" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot terminate a VPN connection in a different Region when sending the connection across an AWS Direct Connect connection.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/remote_regions.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/remote_regions.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a Direct Connect gateway in the us-west-1 Region and connect over a private virtual interface.</p>', '<p>Set up a public virtual interface and establish a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) session.</p>', '<p>Set up a transit virtual interface and establish a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) session.</p>', '<p>Create an AWS Managed VPN across the Direct Connect connection that terminates at a virtual private gateway in the us-west-1 Region.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company stores application logs in an Amazon S3 bucket in the us-west-1 Region. The company has established an AWS Direct Connect connection to the us-east-1 Region.How can the company access the application log bucket over the Direct Connect connection?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203152, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A highly sensitive application runs on Amazon EC2 Linux instances in private subnets. An AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection is provisioned to the company data center and all traffic must traverse the DX connection including outbound internet traffic. The company enforces the use of a forward proxy server for all outbound traffic. The EC2 instances have established connectivity with on-premises servers but are unable to connect to web services on the internet.</p><p>What should a network engineer do to resolve the internet connectivity issues for the EC2 instances?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The company is only allowing traffic from the VPC to be routed to the on-premises network via the DX connection. This means that even internet traffic must be routed via the DX link and cannot be routed via an internet gateway.</p><p>The company also requires the use of a proxy server running on-premises for routing all outbound internet traffic. The EC2 instances in this case do not know about the proxy server and are routing all connections to the on-premises firewalls which will fail.</p><p>To resolve the connectivity issues the VPC route tables must be configured with an entry for the on-premises proxy server so that all internet bound traffic is routed to the proxy server and not the on-premises routers.</p><p>For example, in the route table below there is an entry for the on-premises IP range (192.168.0.0/16) via a virtual private gateway and an entry for all other traffic to go via the on-premises proxy server IP address</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_14-24-43-995f36fcc94165b5ba2643134cbf5547.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Update the VPC route table with entries for the on-premises proxy server" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Update the VPC route table with entries for the on-premises CIDR block" is incorrect.</p><p>The VPC route table must already have an entry for the on-premises CIDR block via the VGW or the instances would not have been able to establish connections with the on-premises servers.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure proxy server settings on the Amazon EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>The instances need a route to a proxy server for internet traffic and this can be configured using the VPC route tables.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a NAT gateway that forwards traffic to the on-premises proxy server" is incorrect.</p><p>A NAT gateway uses an internet gateway to forward traffic and cannot be configured to forward traffic via an on-premises proxy server.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/route-table-options.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/route-table-options.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure proxy server settings on the Amazon EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Create a NAT gateway that forwards traffic to the on-premises proxy server.</p>', '<p>Update the VPC route table with entries for the on-premises proxy server.</p>', '<p>Update the VPC route table with entries for the on-premises CIDR block.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A highly sensitive application runs on Amazon EC2 Linux instances in private subnets. An AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection is provisioned to the company data center and all traffic must traverse the DX connection including outbound internet traffic. The company enforces the use of a forward proxy server for all outbound traffic. The EC2 instances have established connectivity with on-premises servers but are unable to connect to web services on the internet.What should a network engineer do to resolve the internet connectivity issues for the EC2 instances?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203154, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company runs many microservices applications in an Amazon VPC with a CIDR block of 10.4.0.0/22. The microservices applications have become very popular and the IP address pool has been fully used up. A network engineer has been tasked with ensuring that new microservices can be launched without running into IP address issues.</p><p>How should the network engineer resolve this issue?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The current CIDR block is 10.4.0.0/22. This CIDR block provides addresses from 10.4.0.1 to 10.4.3.254. The CIDR block 10.5.0.0/22 is suitable for this scenario and provides addresses from 10.5.0.1 to 10.5.3.254. Therefore, the 10.5.0.0/22 CIDR address block would be ideal for providing an additional addresses space for launching the microservices.</p><p>Secondary CIDR blocks can be created in a VPC if you adhere to the rules around permitted associations (see link below). Once the secondary CIDR has been added subnets must be created that use the address space.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.5.0.0/22. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.4.0.0/21. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>This address block overlaps with the current address block which is not allowed.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.4.5.0/23. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>This address block overlaps with the current address block which is not allowed.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.4.4.0/16. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>A 16-bit subnet mask only masks the first 16 bits of the address block, which in this case is 10.4.0.0. Therefore, the range of addresses is from 10.4.0.0-10.4.255.255. This CIDR block overlaps with the existing CIDR block.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.4.3.0/22. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet.</p>', '<p>Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.5.0.0/22. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet.</p>', '<p>Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.4.0.0/21. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet.</p>', '<p>Add a second CIDR block to the VPC and use 10.4.4.0/16. Create a new subnet with a new CIDR block and configure microservices to launch in the new subnet.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company runs many microservices applications in an Amazon VPC with a CIDR block of 10.4.0.0/22. The microservices applications have become very popular and the IP address pool has been fully used up. A network engineer has been tasked with ensuring that new microservices can be launched without running into IP address issues.How should the network engineer resolve this issue?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203156, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has deployed several applications in an Amazon VPC which includes a virtual private gateway. The company has established an AWS Direct Connect connection and configured a private virtual interface (VIF). The company has also established a VPN connection to the on-premises data center.</p><p>For traffic originating in the VPC, what is the order of BGP path selection from MOST preferred to LEAST preferred?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>It is essential to understand the route selection behavior for the exam. The longest / most specific prefix is always preferred, regardless of how the route is learned.</p><p>Routes configured manually (static routes) take precedence over learned routes.</p><p>If the prefixes are the same a VGW prioritizes routes as follows (most to least preferred):</p><ul><li><p>BGP propagated routes from an AWS Direct Connect connection.</p></li><li><p>Manually added static routes for a Site-to-Site VPN connection.</p></li><li><p>BGP propagated routes from a Site-to-Site VPN connection.</p></li><li><p>For matching prefixes where each Site-to-Site VPN connection uses BGP, the AS PATH is compared and the prefix with the shortest AS PATH is preferred. Alternatively, you can prepend AS_PATH, so that the path is less preferred.</p></li><li><p>When the AS PATHs are the same length and if the first AS in the AS_SEQUENCE is the same across multiple paths, multi-exit discriminators (MEDs) are compared. The path with the lowest MED value is preferred.</p></li></ul><p>Therefore, the order of path selection will be longest prefix match followed by static routes followed by BGP paths via DX and lastly BGP paths via VPN.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Longest prefix match, static routes, Direct Connect BGP routes, VPN BGP routes" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Longest prefix match, static routes, VPN BGP routes, Direct Connect BGP routes" is incorrect.</p><p>The DX BGP paths will be preferred over the VPN BGP paths.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Static routes, longest prefix match, VPN BGP routes, Direct Connect BGP routes" is incorrect.</p><p>Longest prefix match is preferred over static routes and DX BGP paths will be preferred over the VPN BGP paths.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Static routes, longest prefix match, Direct Connect BGP routes, VPN BGP routes" is incorrect.</p><p>Longest prefix match is preferred over static routes.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/VPNRoutingTypes.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/VPNRoutingTypes.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Static routes, longest prefix match, VPN BGP routes, Direct Connect BGP routes.</p>', '<p>Static routes, longest prefix match, Direct Connect BGP routes, VPN BGP routes.</p>', '<p>Longest prefix match, static routes, Direct Connect BGP routes, VPN BGP routes.</p>', '<p>Longest prefix match, static routes, VPN BGP routes, Direct Connect BGP routes.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has deployed several applications in an Amazon VPC which includes a virtual private gateway. The company has established an AWS Direct Connect connection and configured a private virtual interface (VIF). The company has also established a VPN connection to the on-premises data center.For traffic originating in the VPC, what is the order of BGP path selection from MOST preferred to LEAST preferred?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203158, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is deploying an AWS Direct Connect connection. The engineer must create a public virtual interface and needs to only import routes that originated from the same Region as the Direct Connect location.</p><p>Which action will achieve this?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>For public virtual interfaces AWS Direct Connect supports scope BGP community tags and the NO_EXPORT BGP community tag to help control the scope (Regional or global) and route preference of traffic on public virtual interfaces.</p><p>You can apply BGP community tags on the public prefixes that you advertise to Amazon to indicate how far to propagate your prefixes in the Amazon network, for the local AWS Region only, all Regions within a continent, or all public Regions.</p><p>You can use the following BGP communities for your prefixes:</p><ul><li><p>7224:9100—Local AWS Region</p></li><li><p>7224:9200—All AWS Regions for a continent</p><ul><li><p>North America–wide</p></li><li><p>Asia Pacific</p></li><li><p>Europe, the Middle East and Africa</p></li></ul></li><li><p>7224:9300—Global (all public AWS Regions)</p></li></ul><p>The communities 7224:1 – 7224:65535 are reserved by AWS Direct Connect.</p><p>AWS Direct Connect applies the following BGP communities to its advertised routes:</p><ul><li><p>7224:8100—Routes that originate from the same AWS Region in which the AWS Direct Connect point of presence is associated.</p></li><li><p>7224:8200—Routes that originate from the same continent with which the AWS Direct Connect point of presence is associated.</p></li><li><p>No tag—Global (all public AWS Regions).</p></li></ul><p>Therefore, the correct answer is to use the BGP community tag 7224:8100 which will only import routes that originate from the same AWS Region in which the AWS Direct Connect point of presence is associated.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure a filter on the company\'s router to only import routes with the 7224: 8100 BGP community tag" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a filter on the company\'s router to only import routes with the NO_EXPORT BGP community tag" is incorrect.</p><p>The NO_EXPORT tells routers to keep the information within the AS boundary. All routes that AWS Direct Connect advertises to customers are tagged with the NO_EXPORT community tag.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a filter on the company\'s router to only import routes without a BGP community tag and a maximum path length of 3" is incorrect.</p><p>AWS Direct Connect advertises prefixes with a minimum path length of 3 so this would not be advisable.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a filter on the company\'s router to only import routes with the 7224: 9300 BGP community tag" is incorrect.</p><p>The 7224:9300 BGP community tag is used for controlling how far to advertise your prefixes in the AWS network – in this case: Global (all public AWS Regions). This is the reverse of the requirement which is to limit the scope of imported prefixes.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/routing-and-bgp.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/routing-and-bgp.html</a></p>', 'answers': ["<p>Configure a filter on the company's router to only import routes with the NO_EXPORT BGP community tag.</p>", "<p>Configure a filter on the company's router to only import routes with the 7224: 8100 BGP community tag.</p>", "<p>Configure a filter on the company's router to only import routes without a BGP community tag and a maximum path length of 3.</p>", "<p>Configure a filter on the company's router to only import routes with the 7224: 9300 BGP community tag.</p>"]}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is deploying an AWS Direct Connect connection. The engineer must create a public virtual interface and needs to only import routes that originated from the same Region as the Direct Connect location.Which action will achieve this?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203160, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A meteorology company receives real-time weather data from sensors. The data is received in a single data source VPC and the company must then perform unique analysis on the data using applications in several data analysis VPCs. The data must be distributed simultaneously from Amazon EC2 instances in the data source VPC to the data analysis VPCs.</p><p>Which set of configuration steps should the company take to meet these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Multicast is a communication protocol used for delivering a single stream of data to multiple receiving computers simultaneously. Transit Gateway supports routing multicast traffic between subnets of attached VPCs, and it serves as a multicast router for instances sending traffic destined for multiple receiving instances.</p><p>EC2 instances can be configured as a multicast sources or multicast members. With a multicast source the elastic network interface associated with the EC2 instance is statically configured to send multicast traffic. With a multicast member the elastic network interface associated with the EC2 instance receives multicast traffic.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure a transit gateway to serve as a multicast router. Attach the data source and data analysis VPCs. Add the ENIs of the EC2 instances in the data source VPC as multicast senders" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to capture streaming data from the data source VPC and load the data into Amazon S3. Configure the instances in the data analysis VPCs to download the data from Amazon S3 for processing" is incorrect.</p><p>Kinesis Data Firehose is a near real-time solution. In this case real-time (not near real-time) is required as the data must be delivered simultaneously to the various instances in the data analysis VPCs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a Direct Connect gateway to serve as a multicast router. Attach the data source and data analysis VPCs. Add the ENIs of the EC2 instances in the data source VPC as multicast senders" is incorrect.</p><p>Direct Connect gateway does not support IP multicast. You must use a Transit Gateway for this purpose.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure VPC peering between the data source VPC and the data analysis VPCs. Enable the Internet Group Management Protocol (IGMP) on all VPCs. Configure the EC2 instances in the data source VPC to send IP multicast traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>Amazon VPC does not support IGMP. You must use Transit Gateway for multicast routing.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/tgw-multicast-overview.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/tgw-multicast-overview.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure a Direct Connect gateway to serve as a multicast router. Attach the data source and data analysis VPCs. Add the ENIs of the EC2 instances in the data source VPC as multicast senders.</p>', '<p>Configure VPC peering between the data source VPC and the data analysis VPCs. Enable the Internet Group Management Protocol (IGMP) on all VPCs. Configure the EC2 instances in the data source VPC to send IP multicast traffic.</p>', '<p>Configure a transit gateway to serve as a multicast router. Attach the data source and data analysis VPCs. Add the ENIs of the EC2 instances in the data source VPC as multicast senders.</p>', '<p>Configure Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to capture streaming data from the data source VPC and load the data into Amazon S3. Configure the instances in the data analysis VPCs to download the data from Amazon S3 for processing.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A meteorology company receives real-time weather data from sensors. The data is received in a single data source VPC and the company must then perform unique analysis on the data using applications in several data analysis VPCs. The data must be distributed simultaneously from Amazon EC2 instances in the data source VPC to the data analysis VPCs.Which set of configuration steps should the company take to meet these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203162, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying an API using Amazon API Gateway that will be used by customers in several geographical locations. The company plans to deploy the API to multiple Regions and will use a custom DNS domain name.</p><p>What actions should a network engineer take to ensure customers can access the API with the LOWEST latency?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A <em>regional API endpoint</em> is intended for clients in the same region. When a client running on an EC2 instance calls an API in the same region, or when an API is intended to serve a small number of clients with high demands, a regional API reduces connection overhead.</p><p>API requests are targeted directly to the Region-specific API Gateway API without going through any CloudFront distribution. For in-Region requests, a Regional endpoint bypasses the unnecessary round trip to a CloudFront distribution.</p><p>In addition, you can apply latency-based routing on Regional endpoints to deploy an API to multiple Regions using the same Regional API endpoint configuration, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure latency-based DNS records in Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has the lowest latency.</p><p>The diagram below compares the three different types of endpoint:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_14-33-50-b7d8cb6dc62dcb2c1e8f5ab7caf3cf71.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure a regional API endpoint in each Region, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure latency-based DNS records in Amazon Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has the lowest latency" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an edge-optimized API endpoint in each Region, set a unique custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure latency-based DNS records in Amazon Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has the lowest latency" is incorrect.</p><p>An edge-optimized endpoint is better suited for global requests for a single API deployment. This uses the CloudFront network to reduce latency for global users.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure private API endpoint in each Region, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure an interface VPC endpoint in the VPCs of customers that connects them to the nearest endpoint" is incorrect.</p><p>A private API is best suited for use within a single Region where clients are using VPC interface endpoints to connect to the service using private IP addresses.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a regional API endpoint in each Region, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure weighted DNS records in Amazon Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has highest weight" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not the best way to configure a regional API endpoint (see reference link below). The configuration should use a unique custom domain name for each deployed API and latency-based routing rather than weighted routing.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/api-gateway-basic-concept.html#apigateway-definition-regional-api-endpoint">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/api-gateway-basic-concept.html#apigateway-definition-regional-api-endpoint</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure a regional API endpoint in each Region, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure latency-based DNS records in Amazon Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has the lowest latency.</p>', '<p>Configure an edge-optimized API endpoint in each Region, set a unique custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure latency-based DNS records in Amazon Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has the lowest latency.</p>', '<p>Configure private API endpoint in each Region, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure an interface VPC endpoint in the VPCs of customers that connects them to the nearest endpoint.</p>', '<p>Configure a regional API endpoint in each Region, set the same custom domain name for each deployed API, and configure weighted DNS records in Amazon Route 53 to route client requests to the Region that has highest weight.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying an API using Amazon API Gateway that will be used by customers in several geographical locations. The company plans to deploy the API to multiple Regions and will use a custom DNS domain name.What actions should a network engineer take to ensure customers can access the API with the LOWEST latency?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203164, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has four Amazon VPCs within an AWS Region. The company plans to connect an AWS Site-to-Site VPN between an on-premises data center and the AWS Cloud. The company requires full transitive routing between the data center network and all four Amazon VPCs.</p><p>Which solutions meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You can configure your transit gateway as a centralized router that connects all your VPCs, AWS Direct Connect, and Site-to-Site VPN connections. In this scenario, all attachments are associated with the transit gateway default route table and propagate to the transit gateway default route table. Therefore, all attachments can route packets to each other, with the transit gateway serving as a simple layer 3 IP router.</p><p>An example of this architecture is depicted in the diagram below:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_14-35-30-2012ef59ade1a2b86f36a3088329ce09.jpg"><p>The route tables in each of the VPCs above should be configured with a route to 0.0.0.0/0 that points to the transit gateway. This entry routes all traffic destined to addresses outside of the local CIDR range to the transit gateway.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a transit gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route to 0.0.0.0/0 that points to the transit gateway" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Direct Connect gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route to 0.0.0.0/0 that points to the Direct Connect gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>A Direct Connect gateway cannot be used with an S2S VPN and cannot be used for transitive routing between VPCs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a transit gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route for each VPC CIDR and the on-premises network that points to the transit gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>There should be a single route destined to 0.0.0.0/0 that goes via the transit gateway as explained above.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Direct Connect gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route for each VPC CIDR and the on-premises network that points to the Direct Connect gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>As explained previously Direct Connect is not suitable for this solution.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/transit-gateway-centralized-router.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/transit-gateway-centralized-router.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a transit gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route to 0.0.0.0/0 that points to the transit gateway.</p>', '<p>Create a Direct Connect gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route to 0.0.0.0/0 that points to the Direct Connect gateway.</p>', '<p>Create a transit gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route for each VPC CIDR and the on-premises network that points to the transit gateway.</p>', '<p>Create a Direct Connect gateway with three VPC attachments and one Site-to-Site VPN attachment. In each VPC route table create a route for each VPC CIDR and the on-premises network that points to the Direct Connect gateway.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has four Amazon VPCs within an AWS Region. The company plans to connect an AWS Site-to-Site VPN between an on-premises data center and the AWS Cloud. The company requires full transitive routing between the data center network and all four Amazon VPCs.Which solutions meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203166, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>Users connect to an online gaming application using the TCP and UDP protocols. Each protocol uses different ports on the same instances. Incoming connections must be distributed to a pool of Amazon EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones.</p><p>Which actions should a network engineer perform?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The network load balancer must be configured with two separate listeners as the protocols are unique for each protocol. Therefore, a TCP listener and a UDP listener should be created. Next, the network engineer will need to create target groups. As the instances are each listening on different ports for UDP and TCP traffic, two target groups should be created. This is because you can only specify one protocol and port number per target group.</p><p>As you can see in the image below, the target group can only be configured with one protocol / port combination:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_14-36-56-236f4c79fcadaaeccd571bce2a331580.jpg"><p>You can add instances to multiple target groups so the network engineer will be able to create a second target group for UDP and specify the port number to forward connections to.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a Network Load Balancer with TCP and UDP listeners. Create two target groups for the EC2 instances, select TCP for the protocol in one target group and UDP in the other and enter the port numbers" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Network Load Balancer with TCP and UDP listeners. Create a single target group for the EC2 instances, select TCP_UDP for the protocol and enter the port numbers" is incorrect.</p><p>There must be two target groups as the UDP and TCP port numbers are unique.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Network Load Balancer with a TCP_UDP listener. Create a single target group for the EC2 instances, select TCP_UDP for the protocol and enter the port numbers" is incorrect.</p><p>A TCP_UDP listener can only be used on the NLB if the port number for both protocols is the same. There must also be two target groups as mentioned above.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Network Load Balancer with a TCP_UDP listener. Create two target groups for the EC2 instances, select TCP for the protocol in one target group and UDP in the other and enter the port numbers" is incorrect.</p><p>As per the explanation for the previous incorrect answer, a separate listener must be created for the TCP and UDP protocols.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/network/load-balancer-target-groups.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/network/load-balancer-target-groups.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a Network Load Balancer with a TCP_UDP listener. Create a single target group for the EC2 instances, select TCP_UDP for the protocol and enter the port numbers.</p>', '<p>Create a Network Load Balancer with a TCP_UDP listener. Create two target groups for the EC2 instances, select TCP for the protocol in one target group and UDP in the other and enter the port numbers.</p>', '<p>Create a Network Load Balancer with TCP and UDP listeners. Create a single target group for the EC2 instances, select TCP_UDP for the protocol and enter the port numbers.</p>', '<p>Create a Network Load Balancer with TCP and UDP listeners. Create two target groups for the EC2 instances, select TCP for the protocol in one target group and UDP in the other and enter the port numbers.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'Users connect to an online gaming application using the TCP and UDP protocols. Each protocol uses different ports on the same instances. Incoming connections must be distributed to a pool of Amazon EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones.Which actions should a network engineer perform?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203168, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application is deployed on AWS Elastic Beanstalk using a single EC2 instance. The application was recently updated to add a second instance and an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Customers connecting to the application are often asked to re-authenticate when they connect. Normally they would only authenticate once and then be able to reconnect without re-authenticating for several hours.</p><p>How can this issue be resolved?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Sticky sessions are a mechanism to route requests to the same target in a target group. This is useful for servers that maintain state information in order to provide a continuous experience to clients. To use sticky sessions, the clients must support cookies.</p><p>In this case, it is likely that the clients authenticate to the back-end instance and when they are reconnecting without sticky sessions enabled they may be load balanced to a different instance and need to authenticate again.</p><p>The most obvious first step in troubleshooting this issue is to enable sticky sessions on the target group. The following image shows this setting:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_14-38-11-b060d3a730aeb3d727d364997bb25c8c.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Enable Sticky Sessions on the target group" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable proxy protocol for the ALB" is incorrect.</p><p>Proxy protocol does not work with the ALB and is not relevant to this situation anyway. This feature works with the NLB and records information about the IP addresses of clients.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add a new TLS/SSL certificate to the ALBs listener" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no need to add a listener, and this would not assist with this issue.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add the x-forwarded-for request header" is incorrect.</p><p>The x-forwarded-for header is added automatically and helps you identify the IP address of a client when you use an HTTP or HTTPS load balancer.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-target-groups.html#sticky-sessions">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-target-groups.html#sticky-sessions</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Enable proxy protocol for the ALB.</p>', '<p>Add a new TLS/SSL certificate to the ALBs listener.</p>', '<p>Add the x-forwarded-for request header.</p>', '<p>Enable Sticky Sessions on the target group.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'An application is deployed on AWS Elastic Beanstalk using a single EC2 instance. The application was recently updated to add a second instance and an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Customers connecting to the application are often asked to re-authenticate when they connect. Normally they would only authenticate once and then be able to reconnect without re-authenticating for several hours.How can this issue be resolved?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203170, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company uses a Network Time Protocol (NTP) server to maintain time synchronization across Windows and Linux instances running in a VPC. The NTP server has been replaced and now uses a different IP address.</p><p><br></p><p>Which action should be taken to update the NTP addresses?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) provides a standard for passing configuration information to hosts on a TCP/IP network. The options field of a DHCP message contains configuration parameters, including the domain name, domain name server, and the netbios-node-type. Additional options such as the NTP server can also be added.</p><p>After you create a set of DHCP options, you can\'t modify them. If you need your VPC to use a different set of DHCP options, you must create it and then associate it with your VPC. Alternatively, you can specify that your VPC should use no DHCP options.</p><p>You can have multiple sets of DHCP options, but you can associate only one set of DHCP options with a VPC at a time. If you delete a VPC, the DHCP options set that is associated with the VPC is disassociated from the VPC.</p><p>After you associate a new set of DHCP options with a VPC, any existing instances and all new instances that you launch in the VPC use the new options. You don\'t need to restart or relaunch your instances. Instances automatically pick up the changes within a few hours, depending on how frequently they renew their DHCP leases. If you prefer, you can explicitly renew the lease using the operating system on the instance.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Associate a new DHCP Options Set" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Update the subnet route table" is incorrect.</p><p>NTP server IP addresses are provided to instances using the DHCP protocol. There isn’t any configuration in the route table.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Update the instance user data" is incorrect.</p><p>Instance user data is used to pass commands to the instance to run at system launch.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Update the instance metadata" is incorrect.</p><p>Instance metadata records information about the configuration of the instance but is not used to directly configure the instance.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_DHCP_Options.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_DHCP_Options.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Update the instance user data.</p>', '<p>Update the subnet route table.</p>', '<p>Update the instance metadata.</p>', '<p>Associate a new DHCP Options Set.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company uses a Network Time Protocol (NTP) server to maintain time synchronization across Windows and Linux instances running in a VPC. The NTP server has been replaced and now uses a different IP address.Which action should be taken to update the NTP addresses?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203172, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>Many Amazon EC2 instances run in an Amazon VPC. Security groups and network ACLs have been configured according to best practices. A network engineer needs to validate the configuration by logging information about traffic flows within the VPC. The information should log ACCEPT and REJECT data and indicate the protocol affected. The solution should be cost-effective.</p><p>Which logging solution should the network engineer configure to centrally collect this information?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>VPC Flow Logs is a feature that enables you to capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in your VPC. Flow log data can be published to Amazon CloudWatch Logs or Amazon S3. After you create a flow log, you can retrieve and view its data in the chosen destination.</p><p>Flow logs can be created at the network interface, subnet, or VPC level. In this case the flow log should be created at the VPC level to capture all traffic flows within the VPC. Information captured includes whether the connection was accepted or rejected, and which protocol was used.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"VPC flow log configured at the VPC level" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "VPC traffic mirroring for elastic network interfaces" is incorrect.</p><p>This is less cost-effective as the mirror target is an ENI or Network Load Balancer and you must pay an hourly fee for each mirror source.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Packet sniffing at the EC2 instance level" is incorrect.</p><p>This requires 3rd party software or utilities and a method of aggregating the data. It is better to use VPC flow logs to collect the information centrally.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Amazon CloudWatch Logs for EC2 interfaces" is incorrect.</p><p>CloudWatch would not log information about the packets being sent across the VPC network.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/flow-logs.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/flow-logs.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Packet sniffing at the EC2 instance level.</p>', '<p>VPC traffic mirroring for elastic network interfaces.</p>', '<p>VPC flow log configured at the VPC level.</p>', '<p>Amazon CloudWatch Logs for EC2 interfaces.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'Many Amazon EC2 instances run in an Amazon VPC. Security groups and network ACLs have been configured according to best practices. A network engineer needs to validate the configuration by logging information about traffic flows within the VPC. The information should log ACCEPT and REJECT data and indicate the protocol affected. The solution should be cost-effective.Which logging solution should the network engineer configure to centrally collect this information?', 'related_lectures': []}]}
