{'count': 20, 'next': None, 'previous': None, 'results': [{'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472294, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has deployed thin client devices in a remote office and will use Amazon Workspaces to host virtual desktops. A network engineer has configured the Amazon Workspaces security groups according to AWS best practices.</p><p>Which of the following steps should the network engineer complete to configure the remote office firewalls to support streaming of the Workspace desktop?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>When using a client application to connect such as a thin client device you must open ports 443 (TCP) and 4172 and 4195 (UDP and TCP). The image below shows the ports and targets:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_14-52-10-c85a142b102dbd5170cf075ee1642885.jpg"><p>Port 443 is used for client application updates, registration, and authentication.</p><p>Ports 4172 and 4195 are used for streaming the WorkSpace desktop and health checks. These ports must be open to the PCoIP Gateway and WorkSpaces Streaming Protocol (WSP) Gateway IP address ranges, and to the health check servers in the Region that the WorkSpace is in.</p><p>If your firewall uses stateful filtering, ephemeral ports (also known as dynamic ports) are automatically opened to allow return communication. If your firewall uses stateless filtering, you must open ephemeral ports explicitly to allow return communication.</p><p>Therefore, the network engineer should allow outbound access on ports 4172 and 4195 (UDP and TCP) and ensure return communication is allowed by opening ephemeral ports inbound.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Allow outbound access on ports 4172 and 4195 (UDP and TCP) and open inbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Allow inbound access on ports 4172 and 4195 (UDP and TCP) and open outbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication" is incorrect.</p><p>The direction of traffic is reversed in this answer compared to the correct answer and is therefore incorrect.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Allow outbound access on ports 80 and 443 (UDP and TCP) and open inbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication" is incorrect.</p><p>Ports 80 and 443 are not required for streaming the workspaces desktop to a thin client device.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Allow inbound access on ports 80 and 443 (UDP and TCP) and open outbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no reason to allow inbound access on ports 80 and 443 to the remote office thin clients.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/workspaces/latest/adminguide/workspaces-port-requirements.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/workspaces/latest/adminguide/workspaces-port-requirements.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Allow outbound access on ports 4172 and 4195 (UDP and TCP) and open inbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication.</p>', '<p>Allow inbound access on ports 4172 and 4195 (UDP and TCP) and open outbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication.</p>', '<p>Allow outbound access on ports 80 and 443 (UDP and TCP) and open inbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication.</p>', '<p>Allow inbound access on ports 80 and 443 (UDP and TCP) and open outbound ephemeral ports to allow return communication.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company has deployed thin client devices in a remote office and will use Amazon Workspaces to host virtual desktops. A network engineer has configured the Amazon Workspaces security groups according to AWS best practices.Which of the following steps should the network engineer complete to configure the remote office firewalls to support streaming of the Workspace desktop?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472296, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An organization has deployed a web application in an Amazon VPC that will be used by many customers. The customers will connect to the web application from VPCs within the same Region and all connections must use private addresses and should not use the internet.</p><p>What is the best way to meet these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The organization can deploy the web application in a service provider model using AWS PrivateLink. This will ensure that all traffic between the customer’s VPCs and the web application does not leave the Amazon network. An Internet gateway, NAT device, public IP address, or VPN connection is therefore not needed to communicate with the service.</p><p>The solution can be deployed by creating a network load balancer in front of the web application. Customers can then create an interface VPC endpoint to connect to the service using private addresses.</p><p>The image below depicts this scenario with a single customer connection:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-08-53-8cf57abab27377bef035b9222d984fdc.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy the web application behind an internal Network Load Balancer. Connect to the service using an interface VPC endpoint" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create VPC peering connections between the web application VPC and all customer VPCs" is incorrect.</p><p>This is a more complex solution and there are limits on the scalability of VPC peering connections.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy the web application behind an internal Application Load Balancer. Connect to the service using a Gateway VPC endpoint" is incorrect.</p><p>A network load balancer should be used for deployment and an interface VPC endpoint should be used for connecting to the service.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution and control access using Network ACL rules" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not a workable solution and does not offer an option for customers to connect using private addresses.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/privatelink/">https://aws.amazon.com/privatelink/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Deploy the web application behind an internal Network Load Balancer. Connect to the service using an interface VPC endpoint.</p>', '<p>Create VPC peering connections between the web application VPC and all customer VPCs.</p>', '<p>Deploy the web application behind an internal Application Load Balancer. Connect to the service using a Gateway VPC endpoint.</p>', '<p>Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution and control access using Network ACL rules.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'An organization has deployed a web application in an Amazon VPC that will be used by many customers. The customers will connect to the web application from VPCs within the same Region and all connections must use private addresses and should not use the internet.What is the best way to meet these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472298, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is working with a network provider to provision a circuit between a company’s on-premises data center and an AWS Direct Connect location. The network provider has provisioned the circuit and needs information to cross-connect.</p><p>How can the network engineer obtain the information required by the network provider for ordering the cross connect?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>When you have your own equipment in an AWS Direct Connect location you must then cross connect between your customer router and the AWS router. The information needed to make this cross connect includes rack, patch panel, port numbers, and connector types. This information is supplied in a Letter of Authorization - Connecting Facility Assignment (LOA-CFA).</p><p>To get access to the LOA-CFA you must create a new AWS Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console. Once AWS has processed the request you will then be able to download the LOA-CFA. The network engineer in this scenario would then be able to forward the LOA-CFA to the network provider who can arrange the connection.</p><p>Here is an example of an (rather old) LOA-CFA:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-10-35-42c0181a3b0159ec8bbfa353eb99df2a.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console. After AWS has processed the request the network engineer can download the LOA-CFA and forward it to the network provider" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a private virtual interface (VIF) in the AWS Management Console. After AWS has processed the request the network engineer can download the LOA-CFA and forward it to the network provider" is incorrect.</p><p>VIFs are created later. First you must create the AWS Direct Connect connection to obtain the LOA-CFA document.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Contact an AWS Technical Account Manager (TAM) and request an LOA-CFA document that details the cross connect connection information and forward it to the network provider" is incorrect.</p><p>An AWS TAM is only available for customers on an Enterprise Support Plan and is also not the right person to approach for obtaining an LOA-CFA. The procedure detailed in the explanation above should be followed instead.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Instruct the network provider to contact AWS through the AWS Partner Network and gain authorization for the cross-connect. AWS will then organize deployment of the cross connect" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not the correct procedure. Please refer to the explanation above.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/create-connection.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/create-connection.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Contact an AWS Technical Account Manager (TAM) and request an LOA-CFA document that details the cross connect connection information and forward it to the network provider.</p>', '<p>Instruct the network provider to contact AWS through the AWS Partner Network and gain authorization for the cross-connect. AWS will then organize deployment of the cross connect.</p>', '<p>Create a Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console. After AWS has processed the request the network engineer can download the LOA-CFA and forward it to the network provider.</p>', '<p>Create a private virtual interface (VIF) in the AWS Management Console. After AWS has processed the request the network engineer can download the LOA-CFA and forward it to the network provider.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is working with a network provider to provision a circuit between a company’s on-premises data center and an AWS Direct Connect location. The network provider has provisioned the circuit and needs information to cross-connect.How can the network engineer obtain the information required by the network provider for ordering the cross connect?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472300, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances behind an Auto Scaling group. The application publishes custom metrics to Amazon CloudWatch in the same AWS Region. The metric data includes sensitive information that must remain private. All connectivity must use private IP addresses and cannot use the AWS public endpoints.</p><p>How can the network engineer configure the solution to meet the security requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>If you use Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) to host your AWS resources, you can establish a private connection between your VPC and CloudWatch Logs. You can use this connection to send logs to CloudWatch Logs without sending them through the internet.</p><p>This meets the security requirements as the connection between the EC2 instances and Amazon CloudWatch will use private IP addresses and will not use the AWS public endpoints.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use an interface VPC endpoint to connect to CloudWatch" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a NAT gateway with an elastic IP address" is incorrect.</p><p>A NAT gateway is used for outbound internet access for EC2 instances in private subnets. This does not assist with this solution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a gateway VPC endpoint to connect to CloudWatch" is incorrect.</p><p>A gateway VPC endpoint can be used with Amazon S3 and Amazon DynamoDB but cannot be used with Amazon CloudWatch.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy the CloudWatch agent and encrypt the sensitive data" is incorrect.</p><p>The CloudWatch agent and encrypting data does not ensure that the connections will be made of private IP addresses. An interface VPC endpoint is needed.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/cloudwatch-logs-and-interface-VPC.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/cloudwatch-logs-and-interface-VPC.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use an interface VPC endpoint to connect to CloudWatch.</p>', '<p>Deploy a NAT gateway with an elastic IP address.</p>', '<p>Use a gateway VPC endpoint to connect to CloudWatch.</p>', '<p>Deploy the CloudWatch agent and encrypt the sensitive data.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'An application runs on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances behind an Auto Scaling group. The application publishes custom metrics to Amazon CloudWatch in the same AWS Region. The metric data includes sensitive information that must remain private. All connectivity must use private IP addresses and cannot use the AWS public endpoints.How can the network engineer configure the solution to meet the security requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472302, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company deploys Amazon VPCs using AWS CloudFormation. Each VPC uses a similar configuration but has a different VPC CIDR block and varying number of subnets. Which attribute should be used in a CloudFormation template to automatically return an array of CIDR address blocks for selection?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The intrinsic function Fn::Cidr returns an array of CIDR address blocks. The number of CIDR blocks returned is dependent on the count parameter. You can think of this function as a subnet calculator that returns a list of CIDR blocks based on the base CIDR specified and number of CIDRs that need to be generated.</p><p>The parameters are:</p><p>· <strong>ipBlock - </strong>The user-specified CIDR address block to be split into smaller CIDR blocks.</p><p>· <strong>Count - </strong>The number of CIDRs to generate. Valid range is between 1 and 256.</p><p>· <strong>cidrBits - </strong>The number of subnet bits for the CIDR. For example, specifying a value "8" for this parameter will create a CIDR with a mask of "/24".</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use the Fn::Cidr intrinsic function" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the cfn-init and cfn-signals helper scripts" is incorrect.</p><p>The cfn-init helper script reads template metadata from the AWS::CloudFormation::Init key. The cfn-signal helper script signals CloudFormation to indicate whether Amazon EC2 instances have been successfully created or updated.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the Fn::Select intrinsic function" is incorrect.</p><p>The intrinsic function Fn::Select returns a single object from a list of objects by index.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the Fn::GetAtt intrinsic function" is incorrect.</p><p>The Fn::GetAtt intrinsic function returns the value of an attribute from a resource in the template.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/intrinsic-function-reference-cidr.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/intrinsic-function-reference-cidr.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use the Fn::Cidr intrinsic function.</p>', '<p>Use the cfn-init and cfn-signals helper scripts.</p>', '<p>Use the Fn::Select intrinsic function.</p>', '<p>Use the Fn::GetAtt intrinsic function.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company deploys Amazon VPCs using AWS CloudFormation. Each VPC uses a similar configuration but has a different VPC CIDR block and varying number of subnets. Which attribute should be used in a CloudFormation template to automatically return an array of CIDR address blocks for selection?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472304, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A consultant is creating an architecture for a web application that includes an Elastic Load Balancer. For compliance purposes the server access logs should record the source IP address of all connections to the application.</p><p>With default settings, what IP address will be recorded in the EC2 instance server access logs as the source of incoming connections? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>With an application load balancer, the server access logs will show the source IP address of connections as the IP addresses of the load balancer nodes that forwarded the connection. To see the IP address of the client, use the X-Forwarded-For request header.</p><p>With network load balancers the IP that is recorded in the server access logs depends on how the targets are specified:</p><p>· By instance ID – the source IP is the IP address of the client.</p><p>· By IP address – the source IP is the IP address of the load balancer node.</p><p>For Network Load Balancers when you can register only IP addresses as targets, enable proxy protocol version 2 on the load balancer.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-13-56-615db174280e4399b29d04eb2220286f.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>With a Network Load Balancer the source IP of the client will be recorded if the instance is specified by instance ID" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"With an Application Load Balancer the source IP address of the load balancer nodes will be recorded" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "With an Application Load Balancer the source IP address of the client will be recorded" is incorrect.</p><p>This not true with default settings. It is possible to configure server access logs to record the information captured in the x-forwarded-for header which would provide the client IP.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "With a Network Load Balancer the source IP of the client will be recorded if the instance is specified by IP address" is incorrect.</p><p>This is only true when the instance is specified by instance ID.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "With a Network Load Balancer the source IP of the application server will be recorded" is incorrect.</p><p>The source IP of the incoming connection will never be the application server itself.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/elb-capture-client-ip-addresses/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/elb-capture-client-ip-addresses/</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/x-forwarded-headers.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/x-forwarded-headers.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>With an Application Load Balancer, the source IP address of the client will be recorded.</p>', '<p>With a Network Load Balancer, the source IP of the client will be recorded if the instance is specified by instance ID.</p>', '<p>With a Network Load Balancer, the source IP of the client will be recorded if the instance is specified by IP address.</p>', '<p>With an Application Load Balancer, the source IP address of the load balancer nodes will be recorded.</p>', '<p>With a Network Load Balancer, the source IP of the application server will be recorded.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'd'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A consultant is creating an architecture for a web application that includes an Elastic Load Balancer. For compliance purposes the server access logs should record the source IP address of all connections to the application.With default settings, what IP address will be recorded in the EC2 instance server access logs as the source of incoming connections? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472306, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is migrating to the AWS Cloud and needs to migrate 100 virtual machines (VMs) using the AWS Server Migration Service (SMS). The migration must take place during non-peak hours to avoid saturating the existing internet connection. The migration must complete within 14 days. The average VM size is 10 GB, and the company has a 2 Gbps internet connection.</p><p>What should the company do to ensure the migration completes on schedule?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Server Migration Service (SMS) is an agentless service which makes it easier and faster for you to migrate thousands of on-premises workloads to AWS. AWS SMS allows you to automate, schedule, and track incremental replications of live server volumes, making it easier for you to coordinate large-scale server migrations.</p><p>The total volume of data is 100 (VMs) x 10 GB (average VM size) = 1000 GB. At 1 Gbps this works out to be around 2 hours of transfer time. Even if we assume the link is already 50% utilized there is still plenty of time to migrate the VMs.</p><p>For this scenario the migration can therefore be scheduled to run outside of business hours using the existing internet connection and should easily complete within the timeframe specified.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use the existing internet connection and schedule the transfer outside of business hours" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Order an AWS Direct Connect connection and avoid using the existing internet connection" is incorrect.</p><p>Direct Connect is unnecessary for this scenario and would take several weeks to provision.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an IPSec VPN connection between the data center and AWS and use Transfer Acceleration to improve upload times" is incorrect.</p><p>An IPSec VPN may add security (though the SMS transfer is already encrypted) but does not improve transfer times. The Transfer Acceleration service is associated with Amazon S3 uploads, not SMS transfers.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Implement an AWS Storage Gateway in cached volume mode and schedule the transfer outside of business hours" is incorrect.</p><p>Storage Gateway is used to store on-premises files in cloud storage, it does not work with AWS SMS to migrate VMs or improve transfer times for VM migrations.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/server-migration-service/">https://aws.amazon.com/server-migration-service/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create an IPSec VPN connection between the data center and AWS and use Transfer Acceleration to improve upload times.</p>', '<p>Implement an AWS Storage Gateway in cached volume mode and schedule the transfer outside of business hours.</p>', '<p>Order an AWS Direct Connect connection and avoid using the existing internet connection.</p>', '<p>Use the existing internet connection and schedule the transfer outside of business hours.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is migrating to the AWS Cloud and needs to migrate 100 virtual machines (VMs) using the AWS Server Migration Service (SMS). The migration must take place during non-peak hours to avoid saturating the existing internet connection. The migration must complete within 14 days. The average VM size is 10 GB, and the company has a 2 Gbps internet connection.What should the company do to ensure the migration completes on schedule?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472308, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is planning an Amazon Workspaces deployment of up to 1000 desktops. The architecture should support a Multi-AZ AWS Directory Services construct and allow for future growth.</p><p>Which architecture is suitable for this deployment?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Each AWS Directory Service construct requires a pair of subnets that provides a highly available directory service split between Amazon AZs. WorkSpaces deployments are tied to a directory construct and reside in the same VPC subnets as your chosen AWS Directory Service.</p><p>AWS recommend using private subnets for your Workspaces deployments. Therefore, we need two private subnets and need to determine the subnet mask that provides enough IP addresses for the Workspaces and room for future growth.</p><p>The following subnet masks were included in answers:</p><p>· /21 – this provides 2048 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>· /22 – this provides 1024 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>· /23 – this provides 512 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>· /24 – this provides 256 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>We can therefore determine that to deploy 1000 Workspaces and allow for future growth we should choose a /22 subnet mask. This is the best of the available answers.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Two private subnets with a /22 subnet mask" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "One public subnet with a /21 subnet mask" is incorrect.</p><p>This will provide enough IP addresses but only provides one subnet and we need two subnets to support a multi-AZ AWS Directory Services construct and according to AWS best practices for Workspaces deployments.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Two private subnets with a /24 subnet mask" is incorrect.</p><p>This will allow a maximum of 512 IP addresses (minus the reserved addresses) which is not sufficient for this deployment.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Two public subnets with a /23 subnet mask" is incorrect.</p><p>This will allow a maximum of 1024 IP addresses (minus the reserved addresses) which does not provide much room for growth.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://d1.awsstatic.com/whitepapers/workspaces/Best_Practices_for_Deploying_Amazon_WorkSpaces.pdf">https://d1.awsstatic.com/whitepapers/workspaces/Best_Practices_for_Deploying_Amazon_WorkSpaces.pdf</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/workspaces/latest/adminguide/amazon-workspaces-vpc.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/workspaces/latest/adminguide/amazon-workspaces-vpc.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Two private subnets with a /22 subnet mask.</p>', '<p>One public subnet with a /21 subnet mask.</p>', '<p>Two private subnets with a /24 subnet mask.</p>', '<p>Two public subnets with a /23 subnet mask.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is planning an Amazon Workspaces deployment of up to 1000 desktops. The architecture should support a Multi-AZ AWS Directory Services construct and allow for future growth.Which architecture is suitable for this deployment?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472310, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': "<p>A microservices application is being designed that will run on Amazon ECS. The application consists of separate microservices accessed through different paths and running behind a single Elastic Load Balancer. The application requires the customer's source IP addresses.</p><p>Which of the following actions should a network engineer take? (Select TWO.)</p>", 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>There are two key requirements here that determine which answers to choose.</p><p><strong>The first requirement </strong>is that the solution must support path-based routing. This determines the choice of load balancer. Only the application load balancer supports path-based routing which means the incoming connections can be distributed based on the path in the request to different target groups containing specific microservices components of the application.</p><p>For example, if the request is for example.com/my-account the connection can be routed to a different target group (containing the ECS tasks) than if the request is for example.com/orders.</p><p><strong>The second requirement</strong> is to capture the customer’s source IP address. As we are using an ALB we must use the x-forwarded-for header as proxy protocol is not supported on layer 7 load balancer.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>" Use an Application Load Balancer with path-based routing " is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Capture client IP addresses by using the X-Forwarded-For header" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a Network Load Balancer with path-based routing" is incorrect.</p><p>The NLB does not support path-based routing.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Capture client IP addresses by using the proxy protocol" is incorrect.</p><p>The proxy protocol is not supported on layer 7 load balancers like the ALB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a Gateway Load Balancer with host-based routing" is incorrect.</p><p>A gateway load balancer is used for routing traffic to content inspection appliances like intrusion detection systems (IDS) and intrusion prevention systems (IPS).</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/x-forwarded-headers.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/x-forwarded-headers.html</a></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/elb-achieve-path-based-routing-alb/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/elb-achieve-path-based-routing-alb/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use a Network Load Balancer with path-based routing.</p>', '<p>Capture client IP addresses by using the X-Forwarded-For header.</p>', '<p>Use a Gateway Load Balancer with host-based routing.</p>', '<p>Capture client IP addresses by using the proxy protocol.</p>', '<p>Use an Application Load Balancer with path-based routing.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'e'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': "A microservices application is being designed that will run on Amazon ECS. The application consists of separate microservices accessed through different paths and running behind a single Elastic Load Balancer. The application requires the customer's source IP addresses.Which of the following actions should a network engineer take? (Select TWO.)", 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472312, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer has established VPN connections from multiple company data centers to a virtual private gateway (vgw-xxxx) attached to VPC. The data centers use the following CIDR blocks:</p><p><strong>Location IPv4 CIDR</strong></p><p>Data Center A 172.31.0.0/20</p><p>Data Center B 172.31.16.0/20</p><p>The VPC also has an internet gateway (igw-xxxx). Which VPC route table entry will correctly route traffic destined to the on-premises networks via the virtual private gateway?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A single entry can be created in the route table that includes all on-premises destinations. This rule will direct all traffic via the virtual private gateway which will know which VPN connection to direct the traffic to based on the specific destination IP address.</p><p>The 172.31.0.0/19 CIDR block includes IP addresses from 172.31.0.1 through to 172.31.31.254 which includes all IP addresses in the data center locations.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Destination: 172.31.0.0/19 Target: vgw-xxxx" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Destination: 172.31.0.0/20 Target: vgw-xxxx" is incorrect.</p><p>The 172.31.0.0/20 CIDR block only includes addresses from 172.31.0.1 to 172.31.15.254. This entry will not route connections for data center B via the VGW.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Destination: 172.31.0.0/32 Target: igw-xxxx" is incorrect.</p><p>A /32 CIDR block means a single IP address, in this case 172.31.0.0 which is not even valid for assigning to servers. The connection should also route via the VGW, not the IGW.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Destination: 172.31.0.0/24 Target: igw-xxxx" is incorrect.</p><p>The /24 address block would only include addresses from 172.31.0.1 to 172.31.0.254. The target is also incorrect as per the previous explanation.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/WorkWithRouteTables.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/WorkWithRouteTables.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Destination: 172.31.0.0/19 Target: vgw-xxxx</p>', '<p>Destination: 172.31.0.0/20 Target: vgw-xxxx</p>', '<p>Destination: 172.31.0.0/32 Target: igw-xxxx</p>', '<p>Destination: 172.31.0.0/24 Target: igw-xxxx</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer has established VPN connections from multiple company data centers to a virtual private gateway (vgw-xxxx) attached to VPC. The data centers use the following CIDR blocks:Location IPv4 CIDRData Center A 172.31.0.0/20Data Center B 172.31.16.0/20The VPC also has an internet gateway (igw-xxxx). Which VPC route table entry will correctly route traffic destined to the on-premises networks via the virtual private gateway?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472314, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A three-tier internet-facing application is being deployed on AWS. The web tier and application tier will run on Amazon EC2 instances in a VPC. The database tier consists of an Amazon DynamoDB table.</p><p>Which architecture will minimize public exposure of the EC2 instances?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The requirement is to minimize the public exposure of the EC2 instances. There is no mention of a load balancer so the web tier must reside in public subnets. Name resolution may be via DNS (e.g. Route 53). The application tier can be placed in private subnets and then connect to DynamoDB via a Gateway VPC endpoint. This solution minimizes public exposure.</p><p>Note that if you introduced an Elastic Load Balancer such as an ALB you could then further secure the solution by moving the web tier into private subnets. In this configuration the ALB must be configured with public subnets in the same AZs as the private subnets in which the web tier instances are running. Watch out for variations of this pattern in the exam!</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"A VPC with public subnets for the web tier, private subnets for the application tier, and a VPC endpoint for DynamoDB" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "A VPC with public subnets for the web tier, public subnets for the application tier, and private subnets for DynamoDB" is incorrect.</p><p>DynamoDB is a public service and does not run within a VPC and cannot therefore be placed in private subnets.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "A VPC with private subnets for the web tier, private subnets for the application tier, and private subnets for DynamoDB" is incorrect.</p><p>If the web tier runs in a private subnet there must be a way for internet clients to connect to them such as an Elastic Load Balancer, but the question does not mention an ELB. As per the previous explanation DynamoDB does not run in a VPC.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "A VPC with private subnets for the web tier, private subnets for the application tier, and a VPC endpoint for DynamoDB" is incorrect.</p><p>As above, the web tier must be public.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Scenario2.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Scenario2.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>A VPC with public subnets for the web tier, public subnets for the application tier, and private subnets for DynamoDB.</p>', '<p>A VPC with private subnets for the web tier, private subnets for the application tier, and private subnets for DynamoDB.</p>', '<p>A VPC with public subnets for the web tier, private subnets for the application tier, and a VPC endpoint for DynamoDB.</p>', '<p>A VPC with private subnets for the web tier, private subnets for the application tier, and a VPC endpoint for DynamoDB.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A three-tier internet-facing application is being deployed on AWS. The web tier and application tier will run on Amazon EC2 instances in a VPC. The database tier consists of an Amazon DynamoDB table.Which architecture will minimize public exposure of the EC2 instances?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472316, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company runs a critical application in an Amazon VPC which will be accessed by application servers running in an on-premises data center via a Direct Connect connection. An SLA of 99.9% uptime is required for the Direct Connect connection. The company has an AWS Enterprise Support plan.</p><p>What is the MOST cost-effective way to meet this SLA requirement?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To achieve 99.9% uptime SLA for Direct Connect you must create virtual interfaces on Dedicated Connections at a minimum of 2 Direct Connect locations, and at least one of those Direct Connect locations uses the Associated AWS Region in which your workload is located.</p><p>The solution to the requirements is to establish another Direct Connect connection to a different cross-connect location. A new private VIF can then be provisioned to the existing VPC and BGP can be used for load balancing connections in active/active mode.</p><p>Additional requirements are:</p><p>· Each virtual interface provisioned on the Included Resource must be configured for full, independent access to your workload.</p><p>· You must have the Enterprise Support plan in place.</p><p>· For private endpoints, your workload must be deployed to two or more Availability Zones.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Order an additional Direct Connect connection from AWS in a different cross-connect location terminated in the associated Region. Provision a new virtual interface (VIF) to the existing VPC and use BGP for load balancing" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Order an additional Direct Connect connection from AWS in the same cross-connect location. Provision a new virtual interface (VIF) to the existing VPC and use BGP for load balancing" is incorrect.</p><p>The 99.9% uptime SLA requirements specify that you must have an additional DX connection in a separate cross-connect location.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a second virtual interface (VIF) on the existing Direct Connect connection and terminate it in the existing VPC. Use BGP for load balancing between the VIFs in active/active mode" is incorrect.</p><p>This configuration does not meet the requirements for the 99.9% uptime SLA. Please see previous explanations and the link below.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Update the solution to include 4 Dedicated Connections across a minimum of 2 Direct Connect locations. Create a virtual interface for each connection and use BGP for load balancing between the VIFs in active/active mode" is incorrect.</p><p>This configuration would meet the requirements for the 99.99% uptime SLA and would be more expensive. As the goal is 99.9% and the solution must be cost-effective, this is an incorrect choice.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/directconnect/sla/">https://aws.amazon.com/directconnect/sla/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Order an additional Direct Connect connection from AWS in a different cross-connect location terminated in the associated Region. Provision a new virtual interface (VIF) to the existing VPC and use BGP for load balancing.</p>', '<p>Create a second virtual interface (VIF) on the existing Direct Connect connection and terminate it in the existing VPC. Use BGP for load balancing between the VIFs in active/active mode.</p>', '<p>Order an additional Direct Connect connection from AWS in the same cross-connect location. Provision a new virtual interface (VIF) to the existing VPC and use BGP for load balancing.</p>', '<p>Update the solution to include 4 Dedicated Connections across a minimum of 2 Direct Connect locations. Create a virtual interface for each connection and use BGP for load balancing between the VIFs in active/active mode.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company runs a critical application in an Amazon VPC which will be accessed by application servers running in an on-premises data center via a Direct Connect connection. An SLA of 99.9% uptime is required for the Direct Connect connection. The company has an AWS Enterprise Support plan.What is the MOST cost-effective way to meet this SLA requirement?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472318, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A new application has been deployed in an Amazon VPC on Amazon EC2 instances. The application must communicate with on-premises servers. Network traffic for the first few months is expected to be low volume but will increase to more than 10 Gbps within the first year. The company needs to connect the applications as quickly as possible.</p><p>The network engineer has been asked to design a hybrid IT connectivity solution.</p><p>What should be done to meet these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Direct Connect is the ideal solution for this scenario as the application is expected to require significant bandwidth soon. However, DX connections take several weeks to setup, so the company needs an initial solution to get up and running.</p><p>The best solution is to setup an AWS VPN initially and submit the connection request for the DX connection. That way the communication channel can be opened straight away and then the network traffic can be migrated across to the DX connection when it is provisioned.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN between the VPC and the data center. Submit a connection request for an AWS Direct Connect connection later" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Submit a connection request for a 1 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection. Increase the bandwidth later, as needed" is incorrect.</p><p>DX connections can take several weeks to months to setup so this would not meet the requirement of establishing a communication channel immediately.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach Elastic IP addresses to the EC2 instances and provision a software VPN between the EC2 instances and the company router" is incorrect.</p><p>This does not work as having separate software-based VPNs from each instance would be unmanageable. Also, there is no path to establishing a high bandwidth solution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Setup an Enterprise Support Plan and then submit a connection request for a 10 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection" is incorrect.</p><p>An Enterprise Support Plan will not help to meet the timelines as there it does not expedite the setup process for the DX connection.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/create-connection.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/create-connection.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Submit a connection request for a 1 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection. Increase the bandwidth later, as needed.</p>', '<p>Attach Elastic IP addresses to the EC2 instances and provision a software VPN between the EC2 instances and the company router.</p>', '<p>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN between the VPC and the data center. Submit a connection request for an AWS Direct Connect connection later.</p>', '<p>Setup an Enterprise Support Plan and then submit a connection request for a 10 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A new application has been deployed in an Amazon VPC on Amazon EC2 instances. The application must communicate with on-premises servers. Network traffic for the first few months is expected to be low volume but will increase to more than 10 Gbps within the first year. The company needs to connect the applications as quickly as possible.The network engineer has been asked to design a hybrid IT connectivity solution.What should be done to meet these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472320, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Users upload files through the application which are then stored in an Amazon S3 bucket. For large file uploads users have experienced timeout errors.</p><p>A network engineer investigated the issue and determined that the backend connections are being closed for long running requests.</p><p>How can the network engineer prevent timeouts from occurring and maintain connection reuse between the ALB and the backend nodes? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>For each request that a client makes through a load balancer, the load balancer maintains two connections. The front-end connection is between a client and the load balancer. The backend connection is between the load balancer and a target. The load balancer has a configured idle timeout period that applies to its connections. If no data has been sent or received by the time that the idle timeout period elapses, the load balancer closes the connection.</p><p>To ensure that lengthy operations such as file uploads have time to complete, send at least 1 byte of data before each idle timeout period elapses, and increase the length of the idle timeout period as needed.</p><p>For backend connections, AWS recommends that you enable the HTTP keep-alive option for your EC2 instances. You can enable HTTP keep-alive in the web server settings for your EC2 instances. If you enable HTTP keep-alive, the load balancer can reuse backend connections until the keep-alive timeout expires. We also recommend that you configure the idle timeout of your application to be larger than the idle timeout configured for the load balancer.</p><p>Therefore, to prevent idle timeout and to reuse backend connections the network engineer should increase the length of the idle timeout period on the ALB and enable HTTP keep-alive in the web server settings of the EC2 instances.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Increase the length of the idle timeout period on the ALB" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Enable HTTP keep-alive in the EC2 instance’s web server settings" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable HTTP keep-alive on the ALB" is incorrect.</p><p>This setting must be enabled on the EC2 instances in the web server settings. It is not enabled on the ALB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable the proxy protocol on the ALB" is incorrect.</p><p>Proxy protocol capture information about the source IP address of clients and works with the CLB and NLB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure cross-zone load balancing on the ALB" is incorrect.</p><p>Cross-zone load balancing is used to evenly distribute load across availability zones and does not assist with meeting these requirements.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/application-load-balancers.html#connection-idle-timeout">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/application-load-balancers.html#connection-idle-timeout</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Increase the length of the idle timeout period on the ALB.</p>', '<p>Enable the proxy protocol on the ALB.</p>', '<p>Enable HTTP keep-alive in the EC2 instance’s web server settings.</p>', '<p>Configure cross-zone load balancing on the ALB.</p>', '<p>Enable HTTP keep-alive on the ALB.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Users upload files through the application which are then stored in an Amazon S3 bucket. For large file uploads users have experienced timeout errors.A network engineer investigated the issue and determined that the backend connections are being closed for long running requests.How can the network engineer prevent timeouts from occurring and maintain connection reuse between the ALB and the backend nodes? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472322, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is configuring an Amazon CloudFront distribution for a website running on example.com. For several countries the website uses country-specific subdomains such as us.example.com and uk.example.com. The network engineer has configured the distribution to cache based on the CloudFront-Viewer-Country header and must configure a redirect for requests to example.com to the relevant subdomain.</p><p>Which actions should the network engineer take?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Lambda@Edge runs your code closer to the viewer. There are several points at which you can run your function code:</p><p>• After CloudFront receives a request from a viewer (viewer request)</p><p>• Before CloudFront forwards the request to the origin (origin request)</p><p>• After CloudFront receives the response from the origin (origin response)</p><p>• Before CloudFront forwards the response to the viewer (viewer response)</p><p>The following diagram depicts where the code can be executed:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-28-59-80b9e9ff204f23c3c7baaf55c99c67e6.jpg"><p>Using a CloudFront origin request with a Lambda@Edge function you can configure an HTTP redirect response with a country-specific URL and return the response to the viewer.</p><p>This is useful when you want to provide country-specific responses. For example, if you have country-specific subdomains, such as us.example.com and uk.example.com, you can generate a redirect response when a viewer requests example.com.</p><p>For this to work you must first configure the distribution to cache based on the CloudFront-Viewer-Country header. This was already done so the network engineer only needs to create the origin request function.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a Lambda@Edge origin request function that generates a redirect response when a viewer requests example.com" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Lambda@Edge viewer response function that generates a redirect response when a viewer requests example.com" is incorrect.</p><p>The viewer response is the wrong place to run this code. The code should be executed at the origin request.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure the CloudFront distribution behavior to conditionally forward requests based on a path pattern" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use a path pattern to conditionally redirect based on the subdomain host name. Path patterns redirect based on the path in the request, e.g. /images/*.jpg or *.gif.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure the viewer protocol policy to redirect HTTP to HTTPS and specify separate origins for each subdomain" is incorrect.</p><p>The viewer protocol policy determines how to handle requests using specific protocols such as HTTP or HTTPS. You can, for example, redirect all HTTP requests to HTTPS. However, you cannot use the viewer protocol policy to specify different origins for each subdomain.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/lambda-examples.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/lambda-examples.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a Lambda@Edge origin request function that generates a redirect response when a viewer requests example.com.</p>', '<p>Configure the CloudFront distribution behavior to conditionally forward requests based on a path pattern.</p>', '<p>Create a Lambda@Edge viewer response function that generates a redirect response when a viewer requests example.com.</p>', '<p>Configure the viewer protocol policy to redirect HTTP to HTTPS and specify separate origins for each subdomain.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is configuring an Amazon CloudFront distribution for a website running on example.com. For several countries the website uses country-specific subdomains such as us.example.com and uk.example.com. The network engineer has configured the distribution to cache based on the CloudFront-Viewer-Country header and must configure a redirect for requests to example.com to the relevant subdomain.Which actions should the network engineer take?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472324, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network administrator needs to capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in a VPC and then run SQL queries against the captured data.</p><p>Which solutions meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Amazon Virtual Private Cloud flow logs capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in a VPC. Use the logs to investigate network traffic patterns and identify threats and risks across your VPC network. You can use Amazon Athena to query log files stored in Amazon S3 using SQL statements.</p><p>The following diagram provides more information on VPC flow logs:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-30-20-2f8ddaaa2f21eb540db445665b863579.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a VPC flow log that captures the data to an Amazon S3 bucket. Use Amazon Athena to query the log files using SQL statements" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a VPC flow log that captures the data to Amazon CloudWatch Logs. Create a metric filter to query the log files using SQL statements" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enabled detailed monitoring for the Amazon EC2 instances. Use CloudWatch Contributor Insights to run SQL statements" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Capture the information using Wireshark on EC2 instances. Export the results to Amazon S3 and use S3 select to query the log files using SQL statements" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/athena/latest/ug/vpc-flow-logs.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/athena/latest/ug/vpc-flow-logs.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Enabled detailed monitoring for the Amazon EC2 instances. Use CloudWatch Contributor Insights to run SQL statements.</p>', '<p>Create a VPC flow log that captures the data to Amazon CloudWatch Logs. Create a metric filter to query the log files using SQL statements.</p>', '<p>Capture the information using Wireshark on EC2 instances. Export the results to Amazon S3 and use S3 select to query the log files using SQL statements.</p>', '<p>Create a VPC flow log that captures the data to an Amazon S3 bucket. Use Amazon Athena to query the log files using SQL statements.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A network administrator needs to capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in a VPC and then run SQL queries against the captured data.Which solutions meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472326, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer has created an Amazon VPC with the CIDR block 172.16.0.0/16. The engineer must create several subnets and each subnet must support up to 1000 assignable IP addresses.</p><p>Which subnet mask will make MOST efficient use of the VPC CIDR block?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To determine the usable IP addresses per subnet you can perform a simple two-step calculation.</p><p>1) Take the number 32 and subtract the number of bits assigned to the subnet mask.</p><p>For example, take 32 and subtract 22, leaving 10 (32 - 22 = 10).</p><p>2) Take the value from the previous calculation and raise it to the power of 2.</p><p>In our example we take 10 and raise it to the power of 2.</p><p>2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 = 1024.</p><p>The result (1024) is the number of IP addresses available. Remember that we must always deduct 5 addresses from this number for VPC subnets as AWS reserve the first 4 and last IP address. The actual assignable addresses are therefore 1019 (1024 – 5 = 1019) which is sufficient for this use case.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"255.255.252.0 (/22)" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "255.255.255.0 (/24)" is incorrect.</p><p>A 24-bit subnet mask allows 256 hosts per network.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "255.255.254.0 (/23)" is incorrect.</p><p>A 23-bit subnet mask allows 512 hosts per network.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "255.255.240.0 (/20)" is incorrect.</p><p>A 20-bit subnet mask allows 4096 hosts per network. This is a less efficient use of the VPC CIDR block.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://network00.com/NetworkTools/IPv4SubnetCalculator/">https://network00.com/NetworkTools/IPv4SubnetCalculator/</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>255.255.255.0 (/24)</p>', '<p>255.255.252.0 (/22)</p>', '<p>255.255.254.0 (/23)</p>', '<p>255.255.240.0 (/20)</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer has created an Amazon VPC with the CIDR block 172.16.0.0/16. The engineer must create several subnets and each subnet must support up to 1000 assignable IP addresses.Which subnet mask will make MOST efficient use of the VPC CIDR block?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472328, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company uses an Amazon RDS MySQL database instance to store customer order data. The security team have requested that SSL/TLS encryption in transit must be used for encrypting connections to the database from application servers. The data in the database is currently encrypted at rest using an AWS KMS key.</p><p>How can a network engineer enable encryption in transit?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Amazon RDS creates an SSL certificate and installs the certificate on the DB instance when Amazon RDS provisions the instance. These certificates are signed by a certificate authority. The SSL certificate includes the DB instance endpoint as the Common Name (CN) for the SSL certificate to guard against spoofing attacks.</p><p>You can download a root certificate from AWS that works for all Regions, or you can download Region-specific intermediate certificates.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Download the AWS-provided root certificates. Use the certificates when connecting to the RDS DB instance" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Take a snapshot of the RDS instance. Restore the snapshot to a new instance with encryption in transit enabled" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no need to do this as a certificate is created when the DB instance is launched.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable encryption in transit using the RDS Management console and obtain a key using AWS KMS" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot enable/disable encryption in transit using the RDS management console or use a KMS key.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add a self-signed certificate to the RDS DB instance. Use the certificates in all connections to the RDS DB instance" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use self-signed certificates with RDS.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/UsingWithRDS.SSL.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/UsingWithRDS.SSL.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Enable encryption in transit using the RDS Management console and obtain a key using AWS KMS.</p>', '<p>Add a self-signed certificate to the RDS DB instance. Use the certificates in all connections to the RDS DB instance.</p>', '<p>Take a snapshot of the RDS instance. Restore the snapshot to a new instance with encryption in transit enabled.</p>', '<p>Download the AWS-provided root certificates. Use the certificates when connecting to the RDS DB instance.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A company uses an Amazon RDS MySQL database instance to store customer order data. The security team have requested that SSL/TLS encryption in transit must be used for encrypting connections to the database from application servers. The data in the database is currently encrypted at rest using an AWS KMS key.How can a network engineer enable encryption in transit?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472330, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is configuring a customer router to establish an AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection. A firewall must also be updated to allow the traffic required for the connection.</p><p>Which types of network traffic must be allowed? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You must have an internet-routable IP address to use as the endpoint for the IPsec tunnels that connect your customer gateway device to the virtual private gateway. If a firewall is in place between the internet and your gateway you must ensure the correct rules are added.</p><p>Firewall rules should allow UDP port 500 and IP protocol 50 (ESP). These rules enable the transmission of IKE packets and IPsec packets that contain the encrypted network traffic.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"UDP port 50" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"IP Protocol 50" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "IP Protocol 5" is incorrect. The protocol number should be 50.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "UDP Port 53" is incorrect. This port is for DNS traffic and is not relevant.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "TCP Port 500" is incorrect. This should be UDP 500, not TCP 500.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/your-cgw.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/your-cgw.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>UDP port 500</p>', '<p>IP Protocol 5</p>', '<p>UDP Port 53</p>', '<p>TCP Port 500</p>', '<p>IP Protocol 50</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'e'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is configuring a customer router to establish an AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection. A firewall must also be updated to allow the traffic required for the connection.Which types of network traffic must be allowed? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 59472332, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A retail website will run on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The website must be accessible on example.com and www.example.com.</p><p>A network engineer has created a public hosted zone in Amazon Route 53. Which records should be created to meet the requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Amazon Route 53 <em>alias records</em> provide a Route 53–specific extension to DNS functionality. Alias records let you route traffic to selected AWS resources, such as CloudFront distributions, Amazon S3 buckets, and Elastic Load Balancers. They also let you route traffic from one record in a hosted zone to another record.</p><p>Unlike a CNAME record, you can create an alias record at the top node of a DNS namespace, also known as the <em>zone apex</em>. For example, if you register the DNS name example.com, the zone apex is example.com. You can\'t create a CNAME record for example.com, but you can create an alias record for example.com that routes traffic to www.example.com (if www.example.com doesn\'t already have a CNAME record).</p><p>For this scenario an ALIAS record can be created for both the example.com and <a href="http://www.example.com/">www.example.com</a> domains. Each record will point to the ALB and will resolve to one or more IP addresses associated with the load balancer.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"An ALIAS record for example.com pointing to the ALB and an ALIAS record for <a href="http://www.example.com/">www.example.com</a> pointing to the ALB" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "A CNAME record for example.com pointing to the ALB and a CNAME record for <a href="http://www.example.com/">www.example.com</a> pointing to the ALB" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot create a CNAME at the zone apex as explained above.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "An ALIAS record for example.com pointing to the ALB and a CNAME record for <a href="http://www.example.com/">www.example.com</a> pointing to the ALIAS record for example.com" is incorrect.</p><p>Both records should be ALIAS records. Route 53 charges for CNAME queries so this would be a more expensive option.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "An A record for example.com pointing to the IP addresses of the ALB and a CNAME record for <a href="http://www.example.com/">www.example.com</a> pointing to the A record for example.com" is incorrect.</p><p>An A record is unsuitable as load balancer node IP addresses changes frequently and it would therefore become out of date and cause failed connections.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resource-record-sets-choosing-alias-non-alias.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resource-record-sets-choosing-alias-non-alias.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>An ALIAS record for example.com pointing to the ALB and an ALIAS record for www.example.com pointing to the ALB.</p>', '<p>A CNAME record for example.com pointing to the ALB and a CNAME record for www.example.com pointing to the ALB.</p>', '<p>An ALIAS record for example.com pointing to the ALB and a CNAME record for www.example.com pointing to the ALIAS record for example.com.</p>', '<p>An A record for example.com pointing to the IP addresses of the ALB and a CNAME record for www.example.com pointing to the A record for example.com.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A retail website will run on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The website must be accessible on example.com and www.example.com.A network engineer has created a public hosted zone in Amazon Route 53. Which records should be created to meet the requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}]}
