{'count': 20, 'next': None, 'previous': None, 'results': [{'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203888, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has an AWS Direct Connect connection between its on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC. The company runs an on-premises application that must communicate with an application running on an Amazon EC2 instance. The communication path must ensure consistent performance and data encryption in-transit.</p><p>How can the network engineer meet these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The communication path must support both consistent performance and data encryption. For consistent performance the communication must go across the Direct Connect connection as using the internet would be unreliable.</p><p>It is not possible to enable encryption using Direct Connect (DX) but you can add an encrypted AWS Site-to-Site VPN over the top of the DX connection. In this case you must create a public VIF as the virtual private gateway (AWS side of the VPN connection) is a public endpoint.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-45-07-7846f7d19c569592ac2b74d307fb432a.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create virtual private gateway in the Amazon VPC and configure a public virtual interface (VIF) on the Direct Connect connection. Establish a site-to-site VPN over the public VIF" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create virtual private gateway in the Amazon VPC and configure a private virtual interface (VIF) on the Direct Connect connection. Establish a site-to-site VPN over the public VIF" is incorrect.</p><p>A public VIF should be used as the virtual private gateway uses a public endpoint.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable encryption in-transit for the existing AWS Direct Connect connection using a private virtual interface (VIF) and an AWS KMS data encryption key" is incorrect.</p><p>It is not possible to encrypt DX connections directly.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an internet gateway in the VPC. Establish a software VPN between the EC2 instance and the on-premises application server via the internet gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>A software VPN cannot be used via a NAT gateway as this communication would be directed across the internet which would not meet the requirement of ensuring consistent performance.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-vpc-connectivity-options/aws-direct-connect-vpn.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-vpc-connectivity-options/aws-direct-connect-vpn.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create virtual private gateway in the Amazon VPC and configure a private virtual interface (VIF) on the Direct Connect connection. Establish a site-to-site VPN over the public VIF.</p>', '<p>Enable encryption in-transit for the existing AWS Direct Connect connection using a private virtual interface (VIF) and an AWS KMS data encryption key.</p>', '<p>Create virtual private gateway in the Amazon VPC and configure a public virtual interface (VIF) on the Direct Connect connection. Establish a site-to-site VPN over the public VIF.</p>', '<p>Configure an internet gateway in the VPC. Establish a software VPN between the EC2 instance and the on-premises application server via the internet gateway.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has an AWS Direct Connect connection between its on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC. The company runs an on-premises application that must communicate with an application running on an Amazon EC2 instance. The communication path must ensure consistent performance and data encryption in-transit.How can the network engineer meet these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203890, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A critical web application recently became unavailable due to changes made to the configuration of an Application Load Balancer. To avoid a repeat of this situation, management has requested that permissions are locked down and auditing is enabled with automated alerting.</p><p>What actions should accomplish this?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The best solution is to use IAM policies to lock down permissions for specific groups of users. The involves creating IAM user policies and applying them to IAM groups and adding authorized users to the group. This is in line with IAM best practices.</p><p>API auditing can be achieved using AWS CloudTrail. AWS Config can be used to monitor the configuration status of resources and can trigger SNS notifications is a resource configuration is modified.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use IAM policies to lock down permissions for specific groups of users. Enable API auditing using AWS CloudTrail. Configure AWS Config to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SNS" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an IAM role with permissions to make changes. Configure permissions to allow all users to assume the role. Configure AWS Config to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SNS" is incorrect.</p><p>A role is more complex as users must first assume the role. In this case all users have been allowed to assume the role which is a security issue.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use IAM policies to lock down permissions for specific groups of users. Enable API auditing using AWS CloudWatch. Configure Amazon Inspector to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SES" is incorrect.</p><p>CloudTrail offers API auditing; CloudWatch offers performance monitoring. AWS Config should be used for configuration monitoring and SNS should be used for sending notifications.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an IAM role with permissions to make changes. Configure permissions to allow specific users to assume the role. Configure AWS GuardDuty to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SES" is incorrect.</p><p>AWS Config should be used for configuration monitoring and SNS should be used for sending notifications.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/notifications-for-AWS-Config.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/notifications-for-AWS-Config.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use IAM policies to lock down permissions for specific groups of users. Enable API auditing using AWS CloudWatch. Configure Amazon Inspector to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SES.</p>', '<p>Create an IAM role with permissions to make changes. Configure permissions to allow all users to assume the role. Configure AWS Config to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SNS.</p>', '<p>Create an IAM role with permissions to make changes. Configure permissions to allow specific users to assume the role. Configure AWS GuardDuty to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SES.</p>', '<p>Use IAM policies to lock down permissions for specific groups of users. Enable API auditing using AWS CloudTrail. Configure AWS Config to audit configuration changes and setup notification using Amazon SNS.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'A critical web application recently became unavailable due to changes made to the configuration of an Application Load Balancer. To avoid a repeat of this situation, management has requested that permissions are locked down and auditing is enabled with automated alerting.What actions should accomplish this?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203892, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A financial application running in a New York data center requires single-digit millisecond latency to databases running on Amazon EC2 within the us-east-1 Region. Currently, latency is unacceptable, and the company must determine a solution to bring latency down to acceptable levels. The company prefers not to use dedicated private network links.</p><p>Which solutions meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Local Zones are a type of AWS infrastructure deployment that place compute, storage, database, and other select services closer to large population, industry, and IT centers, enabling you to deliver applications that require single-digit millisecond latency to end-users.</p><p>To use Local Zones the company must enable the Local Zone of their choice, extend the Amazon VPC to span Availability Zones and Local Zones, and then create subnets that use the Local Zone. The EC2 instances running the databases can then be redeployed in the AWS Local Zone.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Enable an AWS Local Zone in New York. Run the database instances in subnets associated with the AWS Local Zone" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable an AWS Local Zone in New York. Use Amazon CloudFront to cache database content in the AWS Local Zone" is incorrect.</p><p>Amazon CloudFront cannot be used to cache content from a database running on EC2.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an AWS Direct Connect connection with a public VIF to us-east-1. Use compression to reduce latency" is incorrect.</p><p>AWS Direct Connect uses private dedicated lines and the company has specified that this is not desired. Compression will also not result in reduced latency.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an AWS Direct Connect connection with a public VIF to us-east-1. Use Amazon RDS to reduce latency" is incorrect.</p><p>Amazon RDS cannot be used to reduce latency over a network; it is a managed hosting service for running your database.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/localzones/features/">https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/localzones/features/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Enable an AWS Local Zone in New York. Run the database instances in subnets associated with the AWS Local Zone.</p>', '<p>Create an AWS Direct Connect connection with a public VIF to us-east-1. Use compression to reduce latency.</p>', '<p>Enable an AWS Local Zone in New York. Use Amazon CloudFront to cache database content in the AWS Local Zone.</p>', '<p>Create an AWS Direct Connect connection with a public VIF to us-east-1. Use Amazon RDS to reduce latency.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A financial application running in a New York data center requires single-digit millisecond latency to databases running on Amazon EC2 within the us-east-1 Region. Currently, latency is unacceptable, and the company must determine a solution to bring latency down to acceptable levels. The company prefers not to use dedicated private network links.Which solutions meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203894, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company uses several Amazon VPCs within an AWS Region for different application services. Each application service uses Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets and public subnets. The instances in private subnets must make API calls to a service on the internet and use NAT gateways for outbound connections.</p><p>The company has recently deployed AWS Transit Gateway with full transitive interconnectivity between VPCs. The company are looking to reduce the cost of the NAT gateways across the VPCs whilst maintaining redundancy for the internet connection.</p><p>What is the best solution to reduce the costs associated with the NAT gateways?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Using AWS Transit Gateway, you can configure a single VPC with multiple NAT gateways to consolidate outbound traffic for numerous VPCs. At the same time, you can use multiple route tables within the transit gateway to maintain VPC-to-VPC isolation. This hub-and-spoke design enables you to manage all your outbound internet communication securely from one place.</p><p>The number of NAT gateways in this architecture reduces from two per-VPC to two in total. The following diagram depicts a similar solution:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-50-44-81843feca8eaeb34b41c93ad0f0e8d16.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy NAT gateways in an egress VPC across multiple availability zones. Configure the transit gateway to send outbound internet traffic through the centralized NAT gateways" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy NAT gateways in an egress VPC across multiple availability zones. Create an interface VPC endpoint to the centralized NAT gateways within each application VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>An interface VPC endpoint is not required. The transit gateway can handle all interconnectivity between the VPCs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy NAT gateways in an egress VPC across multiple availability zones. Configure VPC peering to send outbound internet traffic through the centralized NAT gateways" is incorrect.</p><p>VPC peering is not required as transit gateway is being used.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a single large NAT gateway in a public subnet within each VPC. Update the route tables to point to the NAT gateway for outbound internet traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no sizing available for NAT gateways, they scale seamlessly up to the maximum throughput. This solution is also not redundant.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/networking-and-content-delivery/creating-a-single-internet-exit-point-from-multiple-vpcs-using-aws-transit-gateway/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/networking-and-content-delivery/creating-a-single-internet-exit-point-from-multiple-vpcs-using-aws-transit-gateway/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Deploy NAT gateways in an egress VPC across multiple availability zones. Create an interface VPC endpoint to the centralized NAT gateways within each application VPC.</p>', '<p>Deploy NAT gateways in an egress VPC across multiple availability zones. Configure VPC peering to send outbound internet traffic through the centralized NAT gateways.</p>', '<p>Deploy a single large NAT gateway in a public subnet within each VPC. Update the route tables to point to the NAT gateway for outbound internet traffic.</p>', '<p>Deploy NAT gateways in an egress VPC across multiple availability zones. Configure the transit gateway to send outbound internet traffic through the centralized NAT gateways.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company uses several Amazon VPCs within an AWS Region for different application services. Each application service uses Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets and public subnets. The instances in private subnets must make API calls to a service on the internet and use NAT gateways for outbound connections.The company has recently deployed AWS Transit Gateway with full transitive interconnectivity between VPCs. The company are looking to reduce the cost of the NAT gateways across the VPCs whilst maintaining redundancy for the internet connection.What is the best solution to reduce the costs associated with the NAT gateways?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203896, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has deployed an AWS Site-to-Site VPN as a backup to their AWS Direct Connect connection. The virtual private gateway uses path selection to determine how to route traffic. The same prefixes are being advertised across each connection.</p><p>Which routes will be preferred by the virtual private gateway?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>When using a VPN as a backup for a DX connection you use the same virtual private gateway for both Direct Connect and the VPN connection to the VPC. If the same prefixes are being advertised across each connection, then the virtual private gateway makes routing decisions as follows (most preferred to least preferred):</p><ul><li><p>BGP propagated routes from an AWS Direct Connect connection.</p></li><li><p>Manually added static routes for a Site-to-Site VPN connection.</p></li><li><p>BGP propagated routes from a Site-to-Site VPN connection.</p></li><li><p>For matching prefixes where each Site-to-Site VPN connection uses BGP, the AS PATH is compared and the prefix with the shortest AS PATH is preferred.</p></li><li><p>When the AS PATHs are the same length and if the first AS in the AS_SEQUENCE is the same across multiple paths, multi-exit discriminators (MEDs) are compared. The path with the lowest MED value is preferred.</p></li></ul><p>Therefore, the correct answer is that the BDP propagated routes from the DX connection will be preferred.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"BGP propagated routes from the AWS Direct Connect connection" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Manually added static routes for the Site-to-Site VPN connection" is incorrect (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "BGP propagated routes from the Site-to-Site VPN connection" is incorrect (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The prefix with the shortest AS Path will be preferred" is incorrect (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/VPNRoutingTypes.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/VPNRoutingTypes.html</a></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/configure-vpn-backup-dx/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/configure-vpn-backup-dx/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>BGP propagated routes from the AWS Direct Connect connection.</p>', '<p>Manually added static routes for the Site-to-Site VPN connection.</p>', '<p>BGP propagated routes from the Site-to-Site VPN connection.</p>', '<p>The prefix with the shortest AS Path will be preferred.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has deployed an AWS Site-to-Site VPN as a backup to their AWS Direct Connect connection. The virtual private gateway uses path selection to determine how to route traffic. The same prefixes are being advertised across each connection.Which routes will be preferred by the virtual private gateway?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203898, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>Company A has recently formed a partnership with Company B and plans to offer access to a web application running on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Elastic Load Balancer. The application runs on a custom TCP port and will be accessed over the internet. Company B requires a short list of static public IP addresses to whitelist in their firewalls.</p><p>How should the solution be deployed?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Company B must configure their firewall to allow outbound connections on a custom TCP port. To implement the firewall updates, they will need the IP addresses of the load balancer nodes that connections will be directed to.</p><p>With a Network Load Balancer, it is possible to configure an Elastic IP address in each subnet the load balancer has targets in. These static addresses can be used by Company B to update their firewall rules.</p><p>The diagram below depicts an NLB with Elastic IP addresses across multiple subnets:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-52-35-400fa13c50f6b7844751f0bbaabfd01a.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use a Network Load Balancer with a TCP listener and configure Elastic IP addresses for each subnet that contains target EC2 instances" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an Application Load Balancer with an HTTPS listener and configure Elastic IP addresses for each subnet that contains target EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>It is not possible to use an ALB as it does not support custom TCP ports (HTTP/HTTPS listeners only) and you cannot assign Elastic IP addresses to ALB nodes.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a Network Load Balancer with a TCP listener and use Elastic IP addresses for the EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>The connections from Company B will be to the NLB nodes so the Elastic IP addresses should be assigned to the NLB nodes, not to the EC2 instances.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an Application Load Balancer with a TCP listener and configure Elastic IP addresses for each subnet that contains target EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot configure a TCP listener with an ALB.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/elb-attach-elastic-ip-to-public-nlb/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/elb-attach-elastic-ip-to-public-nlb/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use an Application Load Balancer with an HTTPS listener and configure Elastic IP addresses for each subnet that contains target EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use a Network Load Balancer with a TCP listener and configure Elastic IP addresses for each subnet that contains target EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use a Network Load Balancer with a TCP listener and use Elastic IP addresses for the EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use an Application Load Balancer with a TCP listener and configure Elastic IP addresses for each subnet that contains target EC2 instances.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'Company A has recently formed a partnership with Company B and plans to offer access to a web application running on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Elastic Load Balancer. The application runs on a custom TCP port and will be accessed over the internet. Company B requires a short list of static public IP addresses to whitelist in their firewalls.How should the solution be deployed?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203900, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances in multiple subnets within a VPC. All instances communicate using private IP addresses. An administrator created a DHCP options set with a custom root domain name however the domain name must be changed to a sub-domain.</p><p>How can the administrator modify the domain name that is received by DHCP?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) provides a standard for passing configuration information to hosts on a TCP/IP network. The options field of a DHCP message contains configuration parameters, including the domain name, domain name server, and the netbios-node-type.</p><p>When you create a VPC, AWS automatically creates a set of DHCP options and associates them with the VPC. You can configure your own DHCP options set for your VPC if you need to use custom settings.</p><p>After you create a set of DHCP options, you can\'t modify them. If you need your VPC to use a different set of DHCP options, you must create it and then associate it with your VPC. Alternatively, you can specify that your VPC should use no DHCP options.</p><p>In this case the administrator will need to create a new DHCP option set with the new domain name and then associate the DHCP option set with the VPC.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a new DHCP option set with the new domain name and associate it with the VPC" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Modify the existing DHCP option set and specify the new domain name" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot modify an existing DHCP option set, a new one must be created.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a new VPC and a new DHCP option set and redeploy the EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no need to create a new VPC, just a new DHCP option set.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a private hosted zone in Route 53 with the new domain name" is incorrect.</p><p>This does not assist with modifying DHCP option set configuration options.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_DHCP_Options.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_DHCP_Options.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a new DHCP option set with the new domain name and associate it with the VPC.</p>', '<p>Modify the existing DHCP option set and specify the new domain name.</p>', '<p>Create a new VPC and a new DHCP option set and redeploy the EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Create a private hosted zone in Route 53 with the new domain name.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances in multiple subnets within a VPC. All instances communicate using private IP addresses. An administrator created a DHCP options set with a custom root domain name however the domain name must be changed to a sub-domain.How can the administrator modify the domain name that is received by DHCP?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203902, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company manages applications for customers in isolated VPCs. Each VPC must be created automatically and must adhere to the company’s network and security standards. The VPCs must use unique CIDR ranges. A network engineer needs to automate the creation of the VPCs to reduce the manual effort associated with onboarding new customers.</p><p>Which solution meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>In a CloudFormation template, you use the AWS::CloudFormation::CustomResource or Custom::<em>String</em> resource type to specify custom resources. Custom resources provide a way for you to write custom provisioning logic in CloudFormation template and have CloudFormation run it during a stack operation, such as when you create, update or delete a stack.</p><p>In this case the custom resource can be used to obtain a unique CIDR block from an external IP address management (IPAM) service. This will ensure that each VPC has a unique CIDR block and allows for central management of CIDR block ranges.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use AWS CloudFormation to deploy the VPCs and use a custom resource to request a CIDR range from an external IP address management (IPAM) service" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use AWS CloudFormation to deploy the VPCs and use the intrinsic function Fn::Cidr to obtain the CIDR blocks from an external IP address management (IPAM) service" is incorrect.</p><p>The intrinsic function Fn::Cidr returns an array of CIDR address blocks. You can think of it as a calculator for creating CIDR address blocks. This intrinsic function cannot be used to obtain addresses from an external IPAM service.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the AWS Management Console to create the VPCs and manually enter unique CIDR address blocks for each VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not an automated method of deploying the VPCs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create the VPCs using the AWS CLI and use the dry-run flag to validate if the current CIDR range is in use" is incorrect.</p><p>The dry-run flag checks whether you have the required permissions for the action, without making the request, and provides an error response. It does not help with checking if a CIDR address block is in use.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-resource-cfn-customresource.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-resource-cfn-customresource.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use AWS CloudFormation to deploy the VPCs and use the intrinsic function Fn::Cidr to obtain the CIDR blocks from an external IP address management (IPAM) service.</p>', '<p>Use AWS CloudFormation to deploy the VPCs and use a custom resource to request a CIDR range from an external IP address management (IPAM) service.</p>', '<p>Use the AWS Management Console to create the VPCs and manually enter unique CIDR address blocks for each VPC.</p>', '<p>Create the VPCs using the AWS CLI and use the dry-run flag to validate if the current CIDR range is in use.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company manages applications for customers in isolated VPCs. Each VPC must be created automatically and must adhere to the company’s network and security standards. The VPCs must use unique CIDR ranges. A network engineer needs to automate the creation of the VPCs to reduce the manual effort associated with onboarding new customers.Which solution meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203904, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A web application runs across several groups of Amazon EC2 instances. Each group of instances should be accessed via a different domain name. For example, requests to api.example.com must be routed to a different set of instances than mobile.example.com.</p><p>What is the most cost-effective solution for load balancing requests to the separate groups of instances?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To answer this question correctly you must determine which load balancer to use and how to configure it correctly to forward the requests to the correct groups of instances. With both load balancers you create target groups and put your instances into the target groups.</p><p>In this case we need to route incoming requests based on the domain name specified. For this we must use information in the host header. For example, api.example.com should be directed to one target group and mobile.example.com should be directed to another.</p><p>Only the Application Load Balancer supports this type of routing which is known as host-based routing. To deploy this solution correctly a single HTTP listener can be created and a forwarding rule that routes incoming requests to the correct target group based on the host header information (domain name specified in the URL).</p><p>To complete the solution an Amazon Route 53 Alias record should be created for each domain name that maps to the ALB.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_20-56-52-ff6a23262d68647de47df4eb1e82b85e.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a single Application Load Balancer. Configure an HTTP listener and use Amazon Route 53 to create Alias records for each domain name. Create a forwarding rule that routes requests to the correct target group based on the host header" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Network Load Balancer for each group of instances. Configure a TCP listener for port 80 and use Amazon Route 53 to create an Alias record for the corresponding domain name" is incorrect.</p><p>This would not be cost-effective as you would end up with several load balancers which will cost more. It is better to use host-based routing with an ALB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a single Network Load Balancer. Configure a TCP listener for port 80 use Amazon Route 53 to create Alias records for each domain name. Create a forwarding rule that routes requests to the correct target group based on the host header" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot forward requests to different target groups based on the host header with an NLB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a single Application Load Balancer. Configure an HTTP listener and use Amazon Route 53 to create Alias records for each domain name. Create a forwarding rule that routes requests to the correct target group based on the URL path" is incorrect.</p><p>Path based routing is where you use information in the URL path rather than the host header. For example, you could route requests for example.com/orders differently to example.com/my-account. In this case host-based routing is required.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/new-host-based-routing-support-for-aws-application-load-balancers/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/new-host-based-routing-support-for-aws-application-load-balancers/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a Network Load Balancer for each group of instances. Configure a TCP listener for port 80 and use Amazon Route 53 to create an Alias record for the corresponding domain name.</p>', '<p>Create a single Application Load Balancer. Configure an HTTP listener and use Amazon Route 53 to create Alias records for each domain name. Create a forwarding rule that routes requests to the correct target group based on the host header.</p>', '<p>Create a single Network Load Balancer. Configure a TCP listener for port 80 use Amazon Route 53 to create Alias records for each domain name. Create a forwarding rule that routes requests to the correct target group based on the host header.</p>', '<p>Create a single Application Load Balancer. Configure an HTTP listener and use Amazon Route 53 to create Alias records for each domain name. Create a forwarding rule that routes requests to the correct target group based on the URL path.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A web application runs across several groups of Amazon EC2 instances. Each group of instances should be accessed via a different domain name. For example, requests to api.example.com must be routed to a different set of instances than mobile.example.com.What is the most cost-effective solution for load balancing requests to the separate groups of instances?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203906, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network manager needs to determine which DNS record types are queried most frequently for an Amazon Route 53 public hosted zone.</p><p>Which actions should a network engineer take to capture this information?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You can configure Amazon Route 53 to log information about the public DNS queries that Route 53 receives, such as the following:</p><ul><li><p>Domain or subdomain that was requested</p></li><li><p>Date and time of the request</p></li><li><p>DNS record type (such as A or AAAA)</p></li><li><p>Route 53 edge location that responded to the DNS query</p></li><li><p>DNS response code, such as NoError or ServFail</p></li></ul><p>Amazon Route 53 sends query logs directly to CloudWatch Logs; the logs are never accessible through Route 53. Instead, you use CloudWatch Logs to view logs in near real-time, search and filter data, and export logs to Amazon S3.</p><p>Note that when logging for a public hosted zone you cannot directly send the logs to Amazon S3. As noted above you can export to S3 but the data is first logged in CloudWatch. This is a key difference compared to Route 53 Resolver query logs which can be sent to several destinations including S3 and Kinesis Data Firehose. Watch out for variations of this scenario!</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Enable Amazon Route 53 query logging and choose the CloudWatch Logs log group to publish logs to" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable Amazon Route 53 query logging and select an Amazon S3 bucket to publish logs to" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot publish directly to S3 with query logging for a public hosted zone (only a Resolver query log).</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable CloudTrail Data Events and select the Amazon S3 bucket that Amazon Route 53 publishes logs to" is incorrect.</p><p>Data events capture actions that take place on Amazon S3 but have nothing to do with Route 53.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable detailed monitoring for Amazon Route 53 and view the metrics for the AWS/Route53 namespace" is incorrect.</p><p>There’s no such thing as detailed monitoring for Route 53. The AWS/Route53 namespace can be used to find information such as the total number of queries but not per record type.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/query-logs.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/query-logs.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Enable Amazon Route 53 query logging and select an Amazon S3 bucket to publish logs to.</p>', '<p>Enable CloudTrail Data Events and select the Amazon S3 bucket that Amazon Route 53 publishes logs to.</p>', '<p>Enable Amazon Route 53 query logging and choose the CloudWatch Logs log group to publish logs to.</p>', '<p>Enable detailed monitoring for Amazon Route 53 and view the metrics for the AWS/Route53 namespace.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A network manager needs to determine which DNS record types are queried most frequently for an Amazon Route 53 public hosted zone.Which actions should a network engineer take to capture this information?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203908, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is establishing a hybrid cloud and has connected an AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection. The DX connection will be used to access multiple VPCs within a Region and to connect on-premises application servers to private Amazon S3 bucket. A network engineer must configure virtual interfaces (VIFs) for the DX connection.</p><p>Which of the following sets of actions will require the LEAST amount of configuration overhead on the customer router?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A Direct Connect gateway is a grouping of virtual private gateways (VGWs) and private virtual interfaces (VIFs). A Direct Connect gateway is a globally available resource. You can create the Direct Connect gateway in any Region and access it from all other Regions.</p><p>A Virtual Interface (VIF) is necessary to access AWS services and can be either public or private. A public virtual interface enables access to public services, such as Amazon S3. A private virtual interface enables access to your VPC.</p><p>For this scenario the network engineer can create a single private VIF to the DX gateway for accessing the VPCs. The DX gateway will then take care of routing connections to multiple VPCs. A single public VIF can be created for accessing Amazon S3. This represents the solutions with the least config required on the customer router.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure a private VIF to a Direct Connect gateway for the VPC resources and a public VIF for S3" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure private VIFs for the VPC resources and for S3" is incorrect.</p><p>You must use a public VIF for Amazon S3 as it has a public endpoint. An alternative is to use a private VIF and an interface VPC endpoint, but this was not mentioned.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure private VIFs for the VPC resources and a public VIF for S3" is incorrect.</p><p>This would require a separate VIF for each VPC which represents more configuration on the customer router.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a private VIF to a Direct Connect gateway for the VPC resources and for S3" is incorrect.</p><p>As mentioned above, S3 will require a public VIF.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithVirtualInterfaces.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithVirtualInterfaces.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure private VIFs for the VPC resources and for S3.</p>', '<p>Configure private VIFs for the VPC resources and a public VIF for S3.</p>', '<p>Configure a private VIF to a Direct Connect gateway for the VPC resources and for S3.</p>', '<p>Configure a private VIF to a Direct Connect gateway for the VPC resources and a public VIF for S3.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is establishing a hybrid cloud and has connected an AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection. The DX connection will be used to access multiple VPCs within a Region and to connect on-premises application servers to private Amazon S3 bucket. A network engineer must configure virtual interfaces (VIFs) for the DX connection.Which of the following sets of actions will require the LEAST amount of configuration overhead on the customer router?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203910, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An Amazon EC2 web server has been deployed into Subnet B within a VPC. An EC2 instance in Subnet A within the same VPC must be able to connect to the web service. A network administrator has created a security group and added both instances to it. Subnet A uses a default Network ACL. A custom Network ACL has been created and attached to Subnet B.</p><p>Which rules should be created to successfully connect to the web server? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A <em>security group</em> acts as a virtual firewall for your instance to control inbound and outbound traffic. When you launch an instance in a VPC, you can assign up to five security groups to the instance. Security groups act at the instance level, not the subnet level. Therefore, each instance in a subnet in your VPC can be assigned to a different set of security groups.</p><p>For each security group, you add <em>rules</em> that control the inbound traffic to instances, and a separate set of rules that control the outbound traffic.</p><p>A <em>network access control list (ACL)</em> is an optional layer of security for your VPC that acts as a firewall for controlling traffic in and out of one or more subnets. Network ACLs act at the subnet level, not the instance level.</p><p>A key difference between a security group and a network ACL is that security groups are stateful whereas network ACLs are stateless. With a network ACL you must therefore create a rule that allows the return traffic for a connection using the ephemeral port range (1024-65535).</p><p>Even though both instances are in the same security group you still must create the inbound rule for the web server and an outbound rule for the connection to it. With the network ACL you must create an inbound rule allowing TCP port 80 and an outbound rule allowing the return traffic on the ephemeral ports.</p><p>The table below describes some important differences between security groups and network ACLs:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-00-43-292f8fe1138555ad390e2278c609e13c.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Security group TCP port 80 inbound and TCP port 80 outbound" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Network ACL: TCP port 80 inbound and TCP ports 1024-65535 outbound" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Security group: TCP port 80 inbound and nothing outbound" is incorrect.</p><p>You must have an outbound rule otherwise the connection to the web server will not be possible.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Security group: TCP port 80 inbound and TCP ports 1024-65535 outbound" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no need to allow the ephemeral ports outbound as these will typically only be used in response traffic which is allowed due to the stateful nature of a security group. Only port 80 is required outbound.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Network ACL: TCP port 80 inbound and TCP port 80 outbound" is incorrect.</p><p>Port 80 outbound is not required in this security group as it is attached to the subnet the web server runs in and the web server will be receiving traffic on port 80 and returning responses using ephemeral ports.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_SecurityGroups.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_SecurityGroups.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Security group: TCP port 80 inbound and nothing outbound.</p>', '<p>Network ACL: TCP port 80 inbound and TCP ports 1024-65535 outbound.</p>', '<p>Security group TCP port 80 inbound and TCP port 80 outbound.</p>', '<p>Network ACL: TCP port 80 inbound and TCP port 80 outbound.</p>', '<p>Security group: TCP port 80 inbound and TCP ports 1024-65535 outbound.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'An Amazon EC2 web server has been deployed into Subnet B within a VPC. An EC2 instance in Subnet A within the same VPC must be able to connect to the web service. A network administrator has created a security group and added both instances to it. Subnet A uses a default Network ACL. A custom Network ACL has been created and attached to Subnet B.Which rules should be created to successfully connect to the web server? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203912, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A systems integration company regularly creates Amazon VPCs for their customers. The VPCs are created in separate accounts in the same Region but share CIDR blocks from the same set of ranges. Security groups and route tables are also configured with common rules.</p><p>The consultants use AWS CloudFormation to deploy the VPCs. Which procedures can assist with automating the deployments and reducing manual effort?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A prefix list is a set of one or more CIDR blocks. You can use prefix lists to make it easier to configure and maintain your security groups and route tables. You can create a prefix list from the IP addresses that you frequently use, and reference them as a set in security group rules and routes instead of referencing them individually.</p><p>To automate the process in separate accounts the owner of the prefix list can share the prefix list with organizations and accounts using AWS RAM. Consumers with whom a prefix list has been shared can view the prefix list and its entries, and they can reference the prefix list in their AWS resources.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create VPC prefix lists and reference them within AWS CloudFormation templates. Use AWS Resource Access Manager to share the prefix lists across accounts" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the AWS CLI and write a shell script to configure the VPCs, security groups, and route tables in each account" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not a very sophisticated way to automate the creation of the resources. It would be better to use CloudFormation for the creation of the resources and prefix lists to define the common configuration items.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use AWS CloudFormation to create change sets for each account and configure the CIDR blocks and rules within the template" is incorrect.</p><p>Change sets are used to submit changes to existing CloudFormation Stacks.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the AWS API with an AWS Lambda function to deploy standard configurations across accounts" is incorrect.</p><p>This is complex and unnecessary as CloudFormation is perfectly suited to deploying the infrastructure in an automated way.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/sharing-managed-prefix-lists.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/sharing-managed-prefix-lists.html</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/managed-prefix-lists.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/managed-prefix-lists.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create VPC prefix lists and reference them within AWS CloudFormation templates. Use AWS Resource Access Manager to share the prefix lists across accounts.</p>', '<p>Use the AWS CLI and write a shell script to configure the VPCs, security groups, and route tables in each account.</p>', '<p>Use AWS CloudFormation to create change sets for each account and configure the CIDR blocks and rules within the template.</p>', '<p>Use the AWS API with an AWS Lambda function to deploy standard configurations across accounts.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A systems integration company regularly creates Amazon VPCs for their customers. The VPCs are created in separate accounts in the same Region but share CIDR blocks from the same set of ranges. Security groups and route tables are also configured with common rules.The consultants use AWS CloudFormation to deploy the VPCs. Which procedures can assist with automating the deployments and reducing manual effort?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203914, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company runs an application on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The EC2 instances run across two Availability Zones. An engineer has deployed new EC2 instances into a third Availability Zone. The instances appear healthy in the target group, but traffic is not being routed to them.</p><p>What should the engineer do to resolve this issue?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You can enable or disable the Availability Zones for your load balancer at any time. After you enable an Availability Zone, the load balancer starts routing requests to the registered targets in that Availability Zone. Your load balancer is most effective if you ensure that each enabled Availability Zone has at least one registered target.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Enable the new Availability Zone on the Application Load Balancer" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enable the new Availability Zone on the target group" is incorrect.</p><p>Availability Zones must be enabled on the load balancer, not on the target group.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach Elastic Network Interfaces in all three Availability Zones" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot attach ENIs across AZs and this is not required anyway.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a new target group with the instances in three Availability Zones" is incorrect.</p><p>There’s no need to create a new target group and it won’t help if the engineer doesn’t enable the AZ on the ALB.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Enable the new Availability Zone on the Application Load Balancer.</p>', '<p>Attach Elastic Network Interfaces in all three Availability Zones.</p>', '<p>Enable the new Availability Zone on the target group.</p>', '<p>Create a new target group with the instances in three Availability Zones.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company runs an application on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The EC2 instances run across two Availability Zones. An engineer has deployed new EC2 instances into a third Availability Zone. The instances appear healthy in the target group, but traffic is not being routed to them.What should the engineer do to resolve this issue?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203916, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A high-performance computing (HPC) application is running in a cluster placement group. A network engineer needs to optimize network throughput by increasing the packet size and reducing network overhead.</p><p>What should the network engineer do to optimize network throughput?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The maximum transmission unit (MTU) of a network connection is the size, in bytes, of the largest permissible packet that can be passed over the connection. The larger the MTU of a connection, the more data that can be passed in a single packet. Ethernet packets consist of the frame, or the actual data you are sending, and the network overhead information that surrounds it.</p><p>The standard Ethernet v2 frame format supports 1500 MTU, which is the largest Ethernet packet size supported over most of the internet. The maximum supported MTU for an instance depends on its instance type. All Amazon EC2 instance types support 1500 MTU, and many current instance sizes support 9001 MTU, or jumbo frames.</p><p>Jumbo frames allow more than 1500 bytes of data by increasing the payload size per packet, and thus increasing the percentage of the packet that is not packet overhead. Fewer packets are needed to send the same amount of usable data. For instances that are collocated inside a cluster placement group, jumbo frames help to achieve the maximum network throughput possible, and they are recommended in this case.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Ensure the EC2 instances support jumbo frames and configure a maximum transmission unit (MTU) of 9001 bytes" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Set the maximum transmission unit (MTU) to 1500 bytes and set the Don’t Fragment flag in the IP header" is incorrect.</p><p>For the best throughput the MTU should be set to 9001 bytes (jumbo frames) as explained above.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Ensure the EC2 instances support jumbo frames and configure a maximum transmission unit (MTU) of 1500 bytes" is incorrect.</p><p>As per the previous explanation, jumbo frames should be used to achieve the highest network throughput.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Relaunch the instances in a partition placement group, install the ENA module and enable ENA support" is incorrect.</p><p>A partition placement group spreads instances across separate partitions of hardware to reduce the likelihood of correlated hardware failures for your application. A cluster placement group is more suitable for HPC applications and applications that require the lowest inter-instance latency and the highest network throughput.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/network_mtu.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/network_mtu.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Ensure the EC2 instances support jumbo frames and configure a maximum transmission unit (MTU) of 1500 bytes.</p>', '<p>Set the maximum transmission unit (MTU) to 1500 bytes and set the Don’t Fragment flag in the IP header.</p>', '<p>Relaunch the instances in a partition placement group, install the ENA module and enable ENA support.</p>', '<p>Ensure the EC2 instances support jumbo frames and configure a maximum transmission unit (MTU) of 9001 bytes.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A high-performance computing (HPC) application is running in a cluster placement group. A network engineer needs to optimize network throughput by increasing the packet size and reducing network overhead.What should the network engineer do to optimize network throughput?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203918, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer needs to deny outbound access from a VPC subnet to a specific IP CIDR block, all other addresses are allowed. The network engineer created a new network ACL and added an outbound rule denying all traffic to 175.12.3.0/24. Inbound rules are configured to allow all inbound traffic from any source.</p><p>After associating the network ACL with a VPC the network engineer noticed that no traffic is being allowed out from the VPC subnet.</p><p>What update is required to the network ACL to meet the requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A <em>network access control list (ACL)</em> is an optional layer of security for your VPC that acts as a firewall for controlling traffic in and out of one or more subnets. Network ACLs are stateless which means you must create rules for each direction of a connection. In this case the inbound rules are configured to allow all traffic. The network engineer needs to deny outbound connections to a specific CIDR block.</p><p>To achieve this a rule should be added that denies the IP CIDR block in question. This is shown as rule 100 in the network ACL example below. Rules are processed in order until an allow or deny is reached. In this case the traffic to the 175.12.3.0/24 range would be blocked.</p><p>However, there is a default deny rule at the end of every network ACL that blocks all traffic that hasn’t been allowed or denied in previous rules. In this case, as there was no other rule to allow traffic the default deny was reached.</p><p>The solution, as shown below, is to add an allow rule for all traffic. This rule should have a higher number than the deny rule to ensure the deny still takes effect as designed.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-12-17-ba8e6a3ed56802a8d6aef6fb5f78c680.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Add an allow rule for all traffic to 0.0.0.0/0 and specify a higher rule number" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add an allow rule for all traffic to 0.0.0.0/0 and specify a lower rule number" is incorrect.</p><p>If the allow rule has a lower number, it will allow everything and the deny rule will not be processed.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Remove the default deny rule from the end of the network ACL" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot modify the default deny rule.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Modify the default deny rule to allow all traffic to any destination" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot modify the default deny rule.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Add an allow rule for all traffic to 0.0.0.0/0 and specify a higher rule number.</p>', '<p>Add an allow rule for all traffic to 0.0.0.0/0 and specify a lower rule number.</p>', '<p>Remove the default deny rule from the end of the network ACL.</p>', '<p>Modify the default deny rule to allow all traffic to any destination.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer needs to deny outbound access from a VPC subnet to a specific IP CIDR block, all other addresses are allowed. The network engineer created a new network ACL and added an outbound rule denying all traffic to 175.12.3.0/24. Inbound rules are configured to allow all inbound traffic from any source.After associating the network ACL with a VPC the network engineer noticed that no traffic is being allowed out from the VPC subnet.What update is required to the network ACL to meet the requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203920, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer has created an Amazon VPC with the CIDR block 10.0.0.0/22. The engineer must create 10 subnets and each subnet must support up to 50 assignable IP addresses.</p><p>Which subnet mask will allow 10 subnets with at least 50 hosts per subnet?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To determine the usable IP addresses per subnet you can perform a simple two-step calculation.</p><p>1) Take the number 32 and subtract the number of bits assigned to the subnet mask.</p><p>For example, take 32 and subtract 26, leaving 6 (32 - 26 = 6).</p><p>2) Take the value from the previous calculation and raise it to the power of 2.</p><p>In our example we take 6 and raise it to the power of 2.</p><p>2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 = 64.</p><p>The result (64) is the number of IP addresses available. Remember that we must always deduct 5 addresses from this number for VPC subnets as AWS reserve the first 4 and last IP address. The actual assignable addresses are therefore 59 (64 – 5 = 59) which is sufficient for this use case.</p><p>To ensure we can create enough subnets for this requirement we can use the same process as above to calculate the total IP addresses within the CIDR block to ensure there are enough available for division into 10 subnets. This is a simple way to ensure you won’t run out of address space.</p><p>The calculation on a subnet mask of 22 returns 1024 hosts. This provides ample address space for 10 subnets of 64 hosts per subnet.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"255.255.255.192 (/26)" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "255.255.255.255 (/32)" is incorrect.</p><p>A 32-bit subnet mask is not possible for a subnet mask and AWS does not allow subnet masks greater than /28.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "255.255.254.0 (/23)" is incorrect.</p><p>A 23-bit subnet mask allows 512 hosts per network. There will not be room for 10 subnets of this size within the CIDR address space.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "255.255.255.224 (/27)" is incorrect.</p><p>A 27-bit subnet mask allows 32 hosts per network which is insufficient.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://network00.com/NetworkTools/IPv4SubnetCalculator/">https://network00.com/NetworkTools/IPv4SubnetCalculator/</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>255.255.255.192 (/26)</p>', '<p>255.255.255.255 (/32)</p>', '<p>255.255.254.0 (/23)</p>', '<p>255.255.255.224 (/27)</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer has created an Amazon VPC with the CIDR block 10.0.0.0/22. The engineer must create 10 subnets and each subnet must support up to 50 assignable IP addresses.Which subnet mask will allow 10 subnets with at least 50 hosts per subnet?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203922, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is designing a web application that runs on and Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones. The network engineer will add an Elastic Load Balancer to distribute incoming connections across the EC2 instances. Security requirements mandate that data in transit must be encrypted.</p><p>Which solution options meet the encryption requirement? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You can passthrough encrypted traffic with an NLB and terminate the SSL on the Amazon EC2 instances, so this is a valid answer.</p><p>You can also use an HTTPS listener with an ALB and install certificates on both the ALB and EC2 instances. This does not use passthrough, instead it will terminate the first SSL connection on the ALB and then re-encrypt the traffic and connect to the EC2 instances.</p><p>The diagram below depicts how you can implement end-to-end encryption (left) or two encrypted sessions (right). This example uses an NLB, it is not possible to use passthrough with an ALB.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-14-34-a5a655f273525bef77e40d3f803e94ef.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use a Network Load Balancer (NLB) with a TCP listener, then terminate SSL on EC2 instances" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with an HTTPS listener, then install SSL certificates on the ALB and EC2 instances" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in passthrough mode, then terminate SSL on EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use passthrough mode with an ALB and terminate SSL on the EC2 instances.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a Network Load Balancer (NLB) with an HTTPS listener, then install SSL certificates on the NLB and EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use a HTTPS listener with an NLB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with a TCP listener, then terminate SSL on EC2 instances" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use a TCP listener with an ALB.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/userguide/what-is-load-balancing.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/userguide/what-is-load-balancing.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in passthrough mode, then terminate SSL on EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with a TCP listener, then terminate SSL on EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use a Network Load Balancer (NLB) with a TCP listener, then terminate SSL on EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with an HTTPS listener, then install SSL certificates on the ALB and EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Use a Network Load Balancer (NLB) with an HTTPS listener, then install SSL certificates on the NLB and EC2 instances.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c', 'd'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is designing a web application that runs on and Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones. The network engineer will add an Elastic Load Balancer to distribute incoming connections across the EC2 instances. Security requirements mandate that data in transit must be encrypted.Which solution options meet the encryption requirement? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203924, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying a retail website on the AWS Cloud behind an Amazon CloudFront distribution. The website must be protected against malicious attacks including Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS), SQL injection, and cross-site scripting.</p><p>Which AWS services can be used to safeguard the website? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS WAF is a web application firewall that helps protect your web applications or APIs against common web exploits and bots that may affect availability, compromise security, or consume excessive resources. AWS WAF gives you control over how traffic reaches your applications by enabling you to create security rules that control bot traffic and block common attack patterns, such as SQL injection or cross-site scripting.</p><p>AWS WAF integrates with CloudFront. When you create a web ACL, you can specify one or more CloudFront distributions that you want AWS WAF to inspect. AWS WAF starts to inspect and manage web requests for those distributions based on the conditions that you identify in the web ACL.</p><p>AWS Shield is a managed Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) protection service that safeguards applications running on AWS. AWS Shield provides always-on detection and automatic inline mitigations that minimize application downtime and latency.</p><p>When using Amazon CloudFront, AWS Shield automatically provides comprehensive protection against infrastructure layer attacks like SYN floods, UDP floods, or other Reflection attacks. AWS Shield’s always-on detection and mitigation systems automatically scrubs bad traffic at Layer 3 and 4 to protect your application. Over 99% of infrastructure layer attacks detected by AWS Shield are automatically mitigated in less than 1 second for attacks on Amazon CloudFront.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"AWS Shield for layer 3 and layer 4 protection" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"AWS Web Application Firewall (WAF) for application layer protection" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Amazon Inspector for layer 3 and layer 4 protection" is incorrect.</p><p>This service is used to run automated security assessments for EC2 instances. It will not block attacks.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "AWS Config for layer 3 and layer 4 protection" is incorrect.</p><p>This service is used to manage the configuration of AWS resources and alert or remediate if a configuration deviates from configured baselines.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "AWS Shield for application layer protection" is incorrect.</p><p>AWS Shield operates at layer 3 and layer 4 rather than at the application layer. AWS WAF operates at the application layer.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/waf/latest/developerguide/cloudfront-features.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/waf/latest/developerguide/cloudfront-features.html</a></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/shield/">https://aws.amazon.com/shield/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>AWS Shield for layer 3 and layer 4 protection.</p>', '<p>Amazon Inspector for layer 3 and layer 4 protection.</p>', '<p>AWS Web Application Firewall (WAF) for application layer protection.</p>', '<p>AWS Config for layer 3 and layer 4 protection.</p>', '<p>AWS Shield for application layer protection.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying a retail website on the AWS Cloud behind an Amazon CloudFront distribution. The website must be protected against malicious attacks including Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS), SQL injection, and cross-site scripting.Which AWS services can be used to safeguard the website? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203926, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway to replace an on-premises Network Attached Storage (NAS) device that recently failed. The company must establish connectivity to AWS in the shortest time possible.</p><p>Which option is the most cost-effective way to get up and running quickly?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Storage Gateway connects an on-premises software appliance with cloud-based storage to provide seamless integration with data security features between your on-premises IT environment and the AWS storage infrastructure. You can use the service to store data in the Amazon Web Services Cloud for scalable and cost-effective storage that helps maintain data security.</p><p>An AWS Storage Gateway can be connected to the AWS Cloud using an internet connection. It is not necessary to establish a VPN or Direct Connect connection. This would be the fastest and easiest way to get the solution up and running.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use the company’s existing internet connection" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Provision an AWS Direct Connect dedicated connection" is incorrect.</p><p>Direct Connect connections can take weeks to months to provision so this would take too long.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Order an AWS Direct Connect hosted connection" is incorrect.</p><p>Even hosted connections from APN Partners can take some time to connect so would not be as quick as using the internet connection.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN" is incorrect.</p><p>A VPN is not required and would take additional time to configure.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/storagegateway/latest/userguide/WhatIsStorageGateway.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/storagegateway/latest/userguide/WhatIsStorageGateway.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN.</p>', '<p>Provision an AWS Direct Connect dedicated connection.</p>', '<p>Order an AWS Direct Connect hosted connection.</p>', '<p>Use the company’s existing internet connection.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway to replace an on-premises Network Attached Storage (NAS) device that recently failed. The company must establish connectivity to AWS in the shortest time possible.Which option is the most cost-effective way to get up and running quickly?', 'related_lectures': []}]}
