{'count': 20, 'next': None, 'previous': None, 'results': [{'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203928, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has deployed multiple Amazon VPCs and requires full interconnectivity between the VPCs and several regional offices. The connectivity must be secure and redundant and should allow up to 2.5 Gbps throughput.</p><p>What should a network engineer do to meet these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Transit Gateway is the ideal solution to enable full interconnectivity between the VPCs and the regional offices.</p><p>In this scenario the VPC has an attached transit gateway, and you have multiple Site-to-Site VPN connections to multiple on-premises locations. You set up the routing so that any traffic from the VPC bound for your networks is routed to the transit gateway.</p><p>You can also use this scenario to create Site-to-Site VPN connections to multiple geographic locations and provide secure communication between sites.</p><p>The following diagram illustrates this configuration:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-19-29-01cd13dcc3504700e3cb6a2ca340af53.jpg"><p>AWS Transit Gateway also enables you to scale the IPsec VPN throughput with equal cost multi-path (ECMP) routing support over multiple VPN tunnels. A single VPN tunnel still has a maximum throughput of 1.25 Gbps. If you establish multiple VPN tunnels to an ECMP-enabled transit gateway, it can scale beyond the default maximum limit of 1.25 Gbps.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a transit gateway. Configure ECMP routing support and use multiple VPN tunnels per regional office. Use a VPC attachment to connect the VPCs to the transit gateway and configure the route tables to support the connectivity requirements" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a virtual private gateway. Configure ECMP routing support across both tunnels and update the routing tables in each VPC to support the connectivity requirements" is incorrect.</p><p>The virtual private gateway is created within a single VPC, so this solution does not offer full interconnectivity between all VPCs and regional offices.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a transit gateway. Configure ECMP routing support and use multiple VPN tunnels per regional office. Configure VPC peering to support the connectivity requirements" is incorrect.</p><p>VPC peering is unnecessary in this scenario as it would be better to use the AWS transit gateway to enable the interconnectivity between VPCs and regional offices.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a virtual private gateway. Use an AWS transit gateway peering connection to connect all the VPCs and remote offices together" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use an AWS transit gateway peering connection when the regional offices are connected to a virtual private gateway. An AWS transit gateway peering connection is used between different transit gateways.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/Examples.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/Examples.html</a></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/networking-and-content-delivery/scaling-vpn-throughput-using-aws-transit-gateway/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/networking-and-content-delivery/scaling-vpn-throughput-using-aws-transit-gateway/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a virtual private gateway. Configure ECMP routing support across both tunnels and update the routing tables in each VPC to support the connectivity requirements.</p>', '<p>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a transit gateway. Configure ECMP routing support and use multiple VPN tunnels per regional office. Configure VPC peering to support the connectivity requirements.</p>', '<p>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a virtual private gateway. Use an AWS transit gateway peering connection to connect all the VPCs and remote offices together.</p>', '<p>Configure an AWS Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing from each regional office to a transit gateway. Configure ECMP routing support and use multiple VPN tunnels per regional office. Use a VPC attachment to connect the VPCs to the transit gateway and configure the route tables to support the connectivity requirements.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has deployed multiple Amazon VPCs and requires full interconnectivity between the VPCs and several regional offices. The connectivity must be secure and redundant and should allow up to 2.5 Gbps throughput.What should a network engineer do to meet these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203930, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer is deploying an AWS Direct Connect connection between a client’s on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC. The client’s network is collocated at an existing AWS Direct Connect location. The network engineer must assess if the customer router meets the requirements for terminating the Direct Connect Link.</p><p>Which three conditions must be met? (Select THREE.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The client already has a network within an AWS Direct Connect Location. Therefore, the network engineer needs to assess if the customer router supports the requirements for terminating the DX connection.</p><p>AWS state that your network must meet the following conditions:</p><ul><li><p>Your network must use single-mode fiber with a 1000BASE-LX (1310 nm) transceiver for 1 gigabit Ethernet, a 10GBASE-LR (1310 nm) transceiver for 10 gigabit, or a 100GBASE-LR4 for 100 gigabit Ethernet.</p></li><li><p>Auto-negotiation for a port must be disabled for a connection with a port speed of more than 1 Gbps. However, depending on the AWS Direct Connect endpoint serving your connection, auto-negotiation might need to be enabled or disabled for 1 Gbps connections.</p></li><li><p>802.1Q VLAN encapsulation must be supported across the entire connection, including intermediate devices.</p></li><li><p>Your device must support Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) and BGP MD5 authentication.</p></li><li><p>(Optional) You can configure Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) on your network. Asynchronous BFD is automatically enabled for AWS Direct Connect virtual interfaces but does not take effect until you configure it on your router.</p></li></ul><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"802.1Q VLAN encapsulation" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Single-mode optical fiber connectivity" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Border Gateway Protocol (BGP)" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP)" is incorrect.</p><p>EIGRP is not supported, you must have support in your network for BGP.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Multi-mode optical fiber connectivity" is incorrect.</p><p>Only single-mode fiber is supported.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "1 Gbps copper connectivity" is incorrect.</p><p>Copper connectivity is not supported; all DX connections must use single-mode fiber optics.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/Welcome.html#overview_requirements">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/Welcome.html#overview_requirements</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>802.1Q VLAN encapsulation.</p>', '<p>Single-mode optical fiber connectivity.</p>', '<p>Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).</p>', '<p>Multi-mode optical fiber connectivity.</p>', '<p>1 Gbps copper connectivity.</p>', '<p>Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'b', 'f'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer is deploying an AWS Direct Connect connection between a client’s on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC. The client’s network is collocated at an existing AWS Direct Connect location. The network engineer must assess if the customer router meets the requirements for terminating the Direct Connect Link.Which three conditions must be met? (Select THREE.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203932, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company requires private connectivity between their on-premises data center and AWS. The company has selected an AWS Partner Network (APN) Partner to provide a dedicated circuit for a 10 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection.</p><p>What steps must be taken to order the cross connect at the Direct Connect location?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Direct Connect locations include an AWS cage in which the AWS routers exist and customer or partner cages in which the customer / partner routers exist. To complete the connection of the DX link you must arrange for a cross-connect to be installed between the AWS router and the customer / partner router. This cross-connect is a cable that connects the routers together.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-25-52-0e78ad0718ee3d1c3928eb7e7c128017.jpg"><p>An APN Partner can help with connecting your data center to an AWS Direct Connect location, but they will still need the information on the Letter of Authorization - Connecting Facility Assignment (LOA-CFA) document to be able to arrange for the cross-connect.</p><p>To get access to the LOA-CFA you must create a new AWS Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console. Once AWS has processed the request you will then be able to download the LOA-CFA. The network engineer in this scenario would then be able to forward the LOA-CFA to the APN Partner who can arrange the connection.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a new Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console. Download the LOA-CFA document and provide it to the APN Partner. The APN Partner will arrange for cross-connect installation" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Request the LOA-CFA document from the APN Partner and submit the document when creating a new Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console" is incorrect.</p><p>The LOA-CFA must be obtained from within your AWS account after creating a new DX connection in the AWS Management Console.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Search for the APN Partner in the AWS Management Console and obtain the connection information. Contact the data center to arrange the cross-connect installation" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot obtain the information required for installation of the cross-connect from the APN Partner and you do not contact the DC directly for installation.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Contact the data center hosting the AWS Direct Connect infrastructure and request the details required for installation of the cross-connect. Pass the information gathered to the APN Partner so they can install the cross-connect" is incorrect.</p><p>The DC provider will not have this information, you must get the LOA-CFA document from AWS and provide it to the APN Partner.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/create-connection.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/create-connection.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Request the LOA-CFA document from the APN Partner and submit the document when creating a new Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console.</p>', '<p>Search for the APN Partner in the AWS Management Console and obtain the connection information. Contact the data center to arrange the cross-connect installation.</p>', '<p>Contact the data center hosting the AWS Direct Connect infrastructure and request the details required for installation of the cross-connect. Pass the information gathered to the APN Partner so they can install the cross-connect.</p>', '<p>Create a new Direct Connect connection in the AWS Management Console. Download the LOA-CFA document and provide it to the APN Partner. The APN Partner will arrange for cross-connect installation.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company requires private connectivity between their on-premises data center and AWS. The company has selected an AWS Partner Network (APN) Partner to provide a dedicated circuit for a 10 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection.What steps must be taken to order the cross connect at the Direct Connect location?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203934, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is using an AWS Site-to-Site VPN between their network and AWS. The network engineer noticed that the connection is unstable and is sometimes not available when first attempting a connection to a web service. Subsequent connection attempts succeed. The VPN includes two tunnels.</p><p>Which action should the network engineer take to resolve the instability? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The issues may be due to idle timeouts on the VPN connection or issues with dead peers. To resolve the issues the network engineer should check the DPD settings on the customer gateway device to ensure that DPD is enabled and working correctly.</p><p>The network engineer should also ensure that there’s constant bidirectional traffic across the VPN connection. If necessary, AWS recommends creating a host that sends ICMP requests to an instance in your VPC every 5 seconds. This will prevent the link from becoming inactive.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Ensure that dead peer detection (DPD) is enabled on the customer gateway device" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Ensure that there\'s constant bidirectional traffic between the local network and the VPC" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Send ICMP requests to the customer gateway device every 5 seconds from a host in the on-premises network" is incorrect.</p><p>This does not help as the requests will not traverse the VPN connection. The ICMP requests should be sent across the link to an instance in the VPC.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Advertise a longer AS_PATH on one path to cause all traffic to prefer that tunnel" is incorrect.</p><p>A shorter AS_PATH should be used to cause traffic to prefer a tunnel, not a longer one.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Set a higher multi-exit discriminator (MED) on one path to cause all traffic to prefer that tunnel" is incorrect.</p><p>A lower MED should be used to cause traffic to prefer a path, not a higher one.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/vpn-tunnel-instability-inactivity/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/vpn-tunnel-instability-inactivity/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Send ICMP requests to the customer gateway device every 5 seconds from a host in the on-premises network.</p>', '<p>Ensure that dead peer detection (DPD) is enabled on the customer gateway device.</p>', '<p>Advertise a longer AS_PATH on one path to cause all traffic to prefer that tunnel.</p>', "<p>Ensure that there's constant bidirectional traffic between the local network and the VPC.</p>", '<p>Set a higher multi-exit discriminator (MED) on one path to cause all traffic to prefer that tunnel.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'd'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'A company is using an AWS Site-to-Site VPN between their network and AWS. The network engineer noticed that the connection is unstable and is sometimes not available when first attempting a connection to a web service. Subsequent connection attempts succeed. The VPN includes two tunnels.Which action should the network engineer take to resolve the instability? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203936, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company requires full interconnectivity between three Amazon VPCs using private IP addresses. The infrastructure within this AWS account is not expected to grow past the three VPCs. The solution should use AWS services.</p><p>Which solution meets these requirements at the LOWEST cost?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>VPC peering is free to use and you only pay for data transfer. For small deployments VPC peering allows you to interconnect your VPCs using private IP addresses. For larger deployments VPC peering is not ideal as it is not transitive, and you must create separate VPC peering connections between all VPCs.</p><p>In this case the environment consists of only three VPCs, so VPC peering is suitable and is the lowest cost option that meets the stated requirements.</p><p>The diagram below shows a similar solution with four VPCs. Note that a full mesh of connections is required to achieve full interconnectivity between all VPCs.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-27-44-03fc5de982db9bba57f7dc5c1c004d8d.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Implement VPC peering between the three VPCs" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy an AWS Transit Gateway and attach each VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>Transit gateway will be more expensive and therefore VPC peering is more suitable for this solution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use VPN CloudHub to interconnect the VPCs" is incorrect.</p><p>VPN CloudHub is an architecture pattern that is used to interconnect VPCs with remote branch offices over VPN connections using a virtual private gateway. It is not suitable for connecting VPCs together.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a software IPSec VPN connection between each VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>Software VPNs are not an AWS service, you must use third-party software. Usually this will also come at an additional cost, and you would pay the data transfer charges.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/peering/what-is-vpc-peering.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/peering/what-is-vpc-peering.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Deploy an AWS Transit Gateway and attach each VPC.</p>', '<p>Create a software IPSec VPN connection between each VPC.</p>', '<p>Use VPN CloudHub to interconnect the VPCs.</p>', '<p>Implement VPC peering between the three VPCs.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company requires full interconnectivity between three Amazon VPCs using private IP addresses. The infrastructure within this AWS account is not expected to grow past the three VPCs. The solution should use AWS services.Which solution meets these requirements at the LOWEST cost?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203938, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets. The instances must save statistical data to an Amazon S3 bucket within the same AWS Region. The connectivity should be private, and the bucket should only be accessible to instances in the VPC.</p><p>How should a network administrator configure the connectivity?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A VPC endpoint for Amazon S3 is a logical entity within a VPC that allows connectivity only to Amazon S3. The VPC endpoint routes requests to Amazon S3 and routes responses back to the VPC. VPC endpoints change only how requests are routed.</p><p>The correct type of VPC endpoint to use with Amazon S3 is a gateway VPC endpoint which is also used for Amazon DynamoDB. For other services an interface VPC endpoint is created which deploys an ENI in a subnet and you must update the route table.</p><p>You can use a bucket policy with the aws:SourceVpce condition to restrict connections to the bucket to instances within the VPC only by specifying the VPC ID.</p><p>The example policy below restricts access to a single bucket to connections coming from a single VPC:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-29-16-d44911b14c48927bc29e2266d5c4807a.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use a gateway VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceVpce condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a gateway VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceIp condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC CIDR" is incorrect.</p><p>The aws:SourceIp condition will limit access to a specific IP or range of addresses. This only works for public IP addresses, and you must instead use aws:VpcSourceIp for private addresses.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an interface VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceVpce condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>A gateway VPC endpoint should be used for Amazon S3 as explained above.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an interface VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceIp condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC CIDR" is incorrect.</p><p>A gateway VPC endpoint should be used for Amazon S3 as explained above and the aws:VpcSourceIp condition should be used for private IP addresses.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/example-bucket-policies-vpc-endpoint.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/example-bucket-policies-vpc-endpoint.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use a gateway VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceVpce condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC.</p>', '<p>Use a gateway VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceIp condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC CIDR.</p>', '<p>Use an interface VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceVpce condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC.</p>', '<p>Use an interface VPC endpoint to connect privately to the bucket. Use the aws:SourceIp condition in the bucket’s policy to restrict access to the VPC CIDR.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets. The instances must save statistical data to an Amazon S3 bucket within the same AWS Region. The connectivity should be private, and the bucket should only be accessible to instances in the VPC.How should a network administrator configure the connectivity?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203940, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network administrator wants to create an alarm that sends an alert if there have been 10 or more rejected attempts to connect to a specific Amazon EC2 instance over TCP port 22 (SSH) within a 1-hour time period.</p><p>Which of the following solutions will meet this requirement?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>VPC Flow Logs is a feature that enables you to capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in your VPC. Flow log data can be published to Amazon CloudWatch Logs or Amazon S3.</p><p>You can search and filter the log data coming into CloudWatch Logs by creating one or more <em>metric filters</em>. Metric filters define the terms and patterns to look for in log data as it is sent to CloudWatch Logs. CloudWatch Logs uses these metric filters to turn log data into numerical CloudWatch metrics that you can graph or set an alarm on.</p><p>For this solution the network administrator can create a metric filter that matches the pattern of the traffic that must be monitored. An alarm can be created that triggers and Amazon SNS notification to notify the administrator of the failed connection attempts.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a VPC Flow Log that writes to CloudWatch Logs. Create a metric filter that matches the pattern of the traffic and configure an alarm that sends a notification" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an AWS Lambda function that monitors the CloudWatch metrics for EC2 instances and triggers an Amazon SNS notification" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a VPC Flow Log that triggers an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches the pattern of the traffic. Setup a CloudWatch alarm that sends a notification" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an AWS Config rule that monitors EC2 instance connection state changes and send a notification using Amazon SNS" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/MonitoringLogData.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/MonitoringLogData.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create an AWS Lambda function that monitors the CloudWatch metrics for EC2 instances and triggers an Amazon SNS notification.</p>', '<p>Create a VPC Flow Log that writes to CloudWatch Logs. Create a metric filter that matches the pattern of the traffic and configure an alarm that sends a notification.</p>', '<p>Create a VPC Flow Log that triggers an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches the pattern of the traffic. Setup a CloudWatch alarm that sends a notification.</p>', '<p>Create an AWS Config rule that monitors EC2 instance connection state changes and send a notification using Amazon SNS.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A network administrator wants to create an alarm that sends an alert if there have been 10 or more rejected attempts to connect to a specific Amazon EC2 instance over TCP port 22 (SSH) within a 1-hour time period.Which of the following solutions will meet this requirement?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203942, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A legacy application runs behind an Amazon CloudFront distribution using a custom origin. Customers have reported connection errors and a network administrator has investigated and noticed that CloudFront is dropping the TCP connection and returning the HTTP status code 502 (Bad Gateway).</p><p>Which of the following could be potential causes of this issue?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>For origins other than Elastic Load Balancing load balancers, you must use a certificate that is signed by a trusted third-party certificate authority (CA), for example, Comodo, DigiCert, or Symantec. Therefore, we know that the custom origin must be using a self-signed certificate as there is no load balancer in this solution.</p><p>AWS state the following:</p><p><em>“If the origin server returns an expired certificate, an invalid certificate, or a self-signed certificate, or if the origin server returns the certificate chain in the wrong order, CloudFront drops the TCP connection, returns HTTP status code 502 (Bad Gateway), and sets the X-Cache header to Error from cloudfront.”</em></p><p>This sounds very much like the issue that is occurring here, so it is most likely due to the expiry of a self-signed certificate.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"A self-signed SSL/TLS certificate has expired" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The SSL/TLS certificate on the distribution has expired" is incorrect.</p><p>This is less likely as the SSL/TLS certificate on the distribution is managed by AWS/ACM and the error that is showing indicates an issue with the custom origin.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The origin access identity (OAI) is misconfigured" is incorrect.</p><p>An OAI is used to protect access to an S3 origin, not a custom origin on a web service.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The security group rules are incorrect for the distribution" is incorrect.</p><p>Security group rules are not associated with distributions, they are configured for EC2 instances and Elastic Load Balancers.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/using-https-cloudfront-to-custom-origin.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/using-https-cloudfront-to-custom-origin.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>The security group rules are incorrect for the distribution.</p>', '<p>The SSL/TLS certificate on the distribution has expired.</p>', '<p>A self-signed SSL/TLS certificate has expired.</p>', '<p>The origin access identity (OAI) is misconfigured.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'A legacy application runs behind an Amazon CloudFront distribution using a custom origin. Customers have reported connection errors and a network administrator has investigated and noticed that CloudFront is dropping the TCP connection and returning the HTTP status code 502 (Bad Gateway).Which of the following could be potential causes of this issue?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203944, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The ALB uses an HTTPS listener with a public SSL/TLS certificate. Recently, there have been some connection issues a network engineer suspects that the issues relate to client TLS negotiation. The network engineer must inspect the traffic to determine the resolution.</p><p>How can the network engineer capture the network traffic?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>This question requires you to know what information is recorded in VPC Flow Logs compared to packet capturing. VPC Flow Logs is a feature that enables you to capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in your VPC.</p><p>An example of the information recorded by VPC flow logs is as follows:</p><p>2 123456789010 eni-1235b8ca123456789 172.31.16.139 172.31.16.21 20641 22 6 20 4249 1418530010 1418530070 ACCEPT OK</p><p>As you can see the data includes the source ENI, IP addresses, port numbers, protocols etc. It does not include details such as the TLS client negotiation errors, TCP window size etc.</p><p>Therefore, in this scenario we must capture the traffic using packet capture software. AWS provides Traffic Mirroring which allows you to copy network traffic from an elastic network interface of Amazon EC2 instances or Elastic Load Balancers to a target.</p><p>The target of the Traffic Mirroring session can be an EC2 instance or a Network Load Balancer. If we use an EC2 instance as the target we can then run packet capture software on that instance to capture all traffic for inspection. Packet capture software such as tcpdump or Wireshark can be used for this purpose.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-39-37-0a573d851e68e89a4fb2ac79a3bb2023.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure VPC Traffic Mirroring. Set the traffic mirror source to the ALB elastic network interface. Set the traffic mirror target to an EC2 instance with packet capture software" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure VPC Traffic Mirroring. Set the traffic mirror source to the ALB elastic network interface. Set the traffic mirror target to Amazon S3 for analysis with Amazon Athena" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot configure Amazon S3 as a target for traffic mirroring. You must select an EC2 instance or a Network Load Balancer.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure VPC Flow Logs on the ALB elastic network interface. Use custom flow logs to add the TLS alert messages to the captured metadata" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot configure VPC Flow Logs to capture TLS alert messages. Please see the example of captured information in the explanation section.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure VPC Flow Logs on the ALB elastic network interface. Send the flow logs to Amazon S3 in the same AWS Region for analysis with Amazon Athena" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot configure VPC Flow Logs to capture TLS alert messages. Please see the example of captured information in the explanation section.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/mirroring/what-is-traffic-mirroring.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/mirroring/what-is-traffic-mirroring.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure VPC Flow Logs on the ALB elastic network interface. Use custom flow logs to add the TLS alert messages to the captured metadata.</p>', '<p>Configure VPC Traffic Mirroring. Set the traffic mirror source to the ALB elastic network interface. Set the traffic mirror target to Amazon S3 for analysis with Amazon Athena.</p>', '<p>Configure VPC Traffic Mirroring. Set the traffic mirror source to the ALB elastic network interface. Set the traffic mirror target to an EC2 instance with packet capture software.</p>', '<p>Configure VPC Flow Logs on the ALB elastic network interface. Send the flow logs to Amazon S3 in the same AWS Region for analysis with Amazon Athena.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The ALB uses an HTTPS listener with a public SSL/TLS certificate. Recently, there have been some connection issues a network engineer suspects that the issues relate to client TLS negotiation. The network engineer must inspect the traffic to determine the resolution.How can the network engineer capture the network traffic?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203946, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A group of Amazon EC2 instances in a private subnet require access to services running on the internet. The instances must only be able to connect to a whitelist of IP addresses.</p><p>Which combination of actions represents the least management overhead? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Instances running in a private subnet do not have public IP addresses or an internet gateway specified in route tables. To connect to the internet a NAT gateway or NAT instance is required to be deployed into a public subnet. The route tables of the private subnet must then be configured with a route to the NAT device for any internet-bound traffic.</p><p>To restrict access to a specific whitelist of IP addresses a security group can be created and attached to the instances. The allowed addresses can be added to rules in the security group which will essentially create a whitelist of addresses that can be reached.</p><p>The diagram below shows how a NAT gateway is deployed and how the route tables must be configured:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-41-57-6d90e64427d448031fb12b04e7508650.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy a NAT gateway into the VPC" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure a security group to restrict access" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a VPC endpoint for the internet IP addresses" is incorrect.</p><p>VPC endpoints cannot be created for non-AWS services such as internet IP addresses.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a virtual private gateway into the VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>A virtual private gateway is used for connecting VPNs, not for connecting EC2 instances in private subnets to the internet.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach an internet gateway to the private subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot attach internet gateways to private subnets as the instances will not have public IP addresses which will be needed to use an IGW.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-nat-gateway.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-nat-gateway.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a VPC endpoint for the internet IP addresses.</p>', '<p>Deploy a NAT gateway into the VPC.</p>', '<p>Configure a security group to restrict access.</p>', '<p>Deploy a virtual private gateway into the VPC.</p>', '<p>Attach an internet gateway to the private subnet.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A group of Amazon EC2 instances in a private subnet require access to services running on the internet. The instances must only be able to connect to a whitelist of IP addresses.Which combination of actions represents the least management overhead? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203948, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company deployed an AWS Direct Connect connection between an on-premises data center and AWS. The network engineer wants to prevent traffic destined to Amazon S3 endpoints from traversing the internet. All Amazon S3 connectivity should go through the Direct Connect connection.</p><p>How should the network engineer configure the connectivity?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A public virtual interface will be required to connect to public AWS endpoints such as Amazon S3. The alternative is to use a private VIF and a VPC interface endpoint (not offered as a solution). The customer router will then be updated to prefer the DX connection as the next hop. This will ensure that all traffic destined for S3 endpoints will traverse the DX connection and will not go out to the internet.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a public virtual interface. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a public virtual interface. Establish an AWS Site-to-Site VPN over the connection. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>A VPN does not offer any advantages here and would require a private VIF.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a private virtual interface. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>A public VIF must be used for S3 unless you have an interface VPC endpoint.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure a private virtual interface on the Direct Connect connection. Create an S3 gateway endpoint in the VPC. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use an S3 gateway endpoint when connecting via a DX connection through a private VIF. The VPC endpoint must be an interface VPC endpoint which establishes an ENI in the VPC which is used for routing connections.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/public-private-interface-dx/">https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/public-private-interface-dx/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a private virtual interface. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic.</p>', '<p>Configure a private virtual interface on the Direct Connect connection. Create an S3 gateway endpoint in the VPC. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic.</p>', '<p>Create a public virtual interface. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic.</p>', '<p>Create a public virtual interface. Establish an AWS Site-to-Site VPN over the connection. Update the route table on the customer router to prefer the Direct Connect as the next hop for S3 traffic.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company deployed an AWS Direct Connect connection between an on-premises data center and AWS. The network engineer wants to prevent traffic destined to Amazon S3 endpoints from traversing the internet. All Amazon S3 connectivity should go through the Direct Connect connection.How should the network engineer configure the connectivity?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203950, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has a Direct Connect (DX) connection from an on-premises data center to the us-east-1 Region. The company also runs applications in the us-west-1 Region. The company has multiple VPCs in each Region. The DX connection is connected to a Direct Connect gateway that is associated with a transit gateway. The transit gateway is attached to all the VPCs in us-east-1.</p><p>An application that is deployed in us-west-1 requires access to a file service in the on-premises data center. The application also requires access to a database in the us-east-1 VPC.</p><p>Which solution will meet these requirements with the LOWEST latency?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A <em>transit gateway</em> is a network transit hub that you can use to interconnect your virtual private clouds (VPCs) and on-premises networks.</p><p>You can attach multiple VPCs to a transit gateway and you can also peer transit gateways. For this scenario, peering will mean the instances in us-west-1 VPCs can communicate via the peering connection to the us-east-1 VPCs.</p><p>Further to this, the connection can also be made to the on-premises data center via the transit gateway peering connection and the attached direct connect gateway.</p><p>The diagram below depicts how a DX gateway can be attached to a transit gateway which has attachments to multiple VPCs. The remote transit gateway can peer with this transit gateway to allow fully transitive routing.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-45-53-fee973bdfcf86bb06cd6fb4a888cffcc.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a transit gateway in us-west-1 and attach the VPCs. Create a transit gateway peering connection between the transit gateways" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a transit gateway in us-west-1 and attach the VPCs. Associate the transit gateway in us-west-1 with the Direct Connect gateway in us-east-1" is incorrect.</p><p>A Direct Connect gateway does not allow gateway associations that are on the same Direct Connect gateway to send traffic to each other. Therefore, the us-west-1 instances would not be able to communicate with the us-west-1 instances.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Direct Connect connection in us-west-1 and attach the VPCs with a Direct Connect gateway and a transit gateway. Create an AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection over the internet between the Direct Connect connections" is incorrect.</p><p>There is no need to establish an additional DX connection in us-west-1.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create inter-Region VPC peering connections between the VPCs in each Region. Route through the Direct Connect gateway to the on-premises file service" is incorrect.</p><p>VPC peering does not allow transitive routing so this solution would not allow instances in us-west-1 to communicate with the on-premises file service.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/tgw-peering.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/tgw-peering.html</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/peering/invalid-peering-configurations.html#transitive-peering">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/peering/invalid-peering-configurations.html#transitive-peering</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a transit gateway in us-west-1 and attach the VPCs. Associate the transit gateway in us-west-1 with the Direct Connect gateway in us-east-1.</p>', '<p>Create a Direct Connect connection in us-west-1 and attach the VPCs with a Direct Connect gateway and a transit gateway. Create an AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection over the internet between the Direct Connect connections.</p>', '<p>Create a transit gateway in us-west-1 and attach the VPCs. Create a transit gateway peering connection between the transit gateways.</p>', '<p>Create inter-Region VPC peering connections between the VPCs in each Region. Route through the Direct Connect gateway to the on-premises file service.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has a Direct Connect (DX) connection from an on-premises data center to the us-east-1 Region. The company also runs applications in the us-west-1 Region. The company has multiple VPCs in each Region. The DX connection is connected to a Direct Connect gateway that is associated with a transit gateway. The transit gateway is attached to all the VPCs in us-east-1.An application that is deployed in us-west-1 requires access to a file service in the on-premises data center. The application also requires access to a database in the us-east-1 VPC.Which solution will meet these requirements with the LOWEST latency?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203952, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying an application on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group. The instances are deployed across multiple Availability Zones. A network engineer must ensure the application is highly available and scalable. The load on the EC2 instances must be automatically distributed. Application clients must also be able to create an allow list of IP addresses for connecting to the application.</p><p>Which solution meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>When you create an internet-facing network load balancer, you can optionally specify one Elastic IP address per subnet. If you do not choose one of your own Elastic IP addresses, Elastic Load Balancing provides one Elastic IP address per subnet for you. These Elastic IP addresses provide your load balancer with static IP addresses that will not change during the life of the load balancer.</p><p>Elastic IP addresses are static, public addresses and the clients will be able to add them to their allow lists in firewall rules. This solution is highly available and scalable across multiple AZs and traffic is distributed automatically.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch a Network Load Balancer (NLB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the NLB Elastic IP addresses to the clients" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the ALB Elastic IP addresses to the clients" is incorrect.</p><p>The ALB does not support Elastic IP addresses. The IP addresses of the load balancer nodes are dynamic addresses so they will change over time. This means the clients cannot add them to their allow lists as the addresses would change and connectivity issues would occur.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the ALB alias record to the clients" is incorrect.</p><p>The ALB alias is of little use here as the clients need static IP addresses to whitelist. The alias will simply resolve to the dynamic IP addresses of the load balancer nodes.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch a Network Load Balancer (NLB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the NLB CNAME record to the clients" is incorrect.</p><p>The NLB should be configured with Elastic IP addresses, and these should be provided to the clients. A CNAME simply resolves to another DNS name.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/network/network-load-balancers.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/network/network-load-balancers.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the ALB Elastic IP addresses to the clients.</p>', '<p>Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch a Network Load Balancer (NLB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the NLB Elastic IP addresses to the clients.</p>', '<p>Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the ALB alias record to the clients.</p>', '<p>Create a target group for the EC2 instances. Launch a Network Load Balancer (NLB) and attach the target group to the Auto Scaling Group. Provide the NLB CNAME record to the clients.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying an application on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group. The instances are deployed across multiple Availability Zones. A network engineer must ensure the application is highly available and scalable. The load on the EC2 instances must be automatically distributed. Application clients must also be able to create an allow list of IP addresses for connecting to the application.Which solution meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203954, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An AWS Lambda function requires access to an application running a private subnet of an Amazon VPC. An engineer has connected the Lambda function to the VPC using the private subnet ID and security group ID. The Lambda function also connects to an API on the internet and is no longer able to connect to the API.</p><p>What changes should the engineer make so that the Lambda function can access BOTH the application in the private subnet and the internet-based API?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>To enable connectivity to an application in a private subnet and the Internet you must first allow the function to connect to the private subnet (which has already been done).</p><p>Lambda needs the following VPC configuration information so that it can connect to the VPC:</p><p>· Private subnet ID.</p><p>· Security Group ID (with required access).</p><p>Lambda uses this information to setup an Elastic Network Interface (ENI) using an available IP address from your private subnet. Next you need to add a NAT Gateway for Internet access (no public IP).</p><p>The NAT Gateway should be connected to a public subnet and a route needs to be added to the private subnet.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Add a NAT Gateway to a public subnet and specify a route in the route table of the private subnet" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach an Internet Gateway to the VPC and specify a route in the route table of the private subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>The Lambda function is connected to a private subnet so the IGW cannot be used to directly access the internet, a NAT gateway is required.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Connect an AWS Site-to-Site VPN to the private subnet so Lambda can connect to the Internet" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use a VPN to connect a subnet to the internet so this would not work. VPNs are used to connect VPCs to on-premises networks.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add an elastic network interface to the Lambda function that is connected to a public subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>The Lambda function already has an ENI in the private subnet and needs a way to use that ENI to access the internet. The NAT gateway allows the function to do that.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/configuration-vpc.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/configuration-vpc.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Attach an Internet Gateway to the VPC and specify a route in the route table of the private subnet.</p>', '<p>Add a NAT Gateway to a public subnet and specify a route in the route table of the private subnet.</p>', '<p>Connect an AWS Site-to-Site VPN to the private subnet so Lambda can connect to the Internet.</p>', '<p>Add an elastic network interface to the Lambda function that is connected to a public subnet.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'An AWS Lambda function requires access to an application running a private subnet of an Amazon VPC. An engineer has connected the Lambda function to the VPC using the private subnet ID and security group ID. The Lambda function also connects to an API on the internet and is no longer able to connect to the API.What changes should the engineer make so that the Lambda function can access BOTH the application in the private subnet and the internet-based API?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203956, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company runs a web application in the AWS Cloud. The web application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The development team release updates on a scaled down version of the application running on-premises. The development team requires that when new updates are ready 10% of the website traffic is directed to the on-premises application.</p><p>Which configuration changes should a network engineer make?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>When you create a record, you choose a routing policy, which determines how Amazon Route 53 responds to queries. Weighted routing lets you associate multiple resources with a single domain name (example.com) or subdomain name (acme.example.com) and choose how much traffic is routed to each resource. This can be useful for a variety of purposes, including load balancing and testing new versions of software.</p><p>To configure weighted routing, you create records that have the same name and type for each of your resources. You assign each record a relative weight that corresponds with how much traffic you want to send to each resource. Amazon Route 53 sends traffic to a resource based on the weight that you assign to the record as a proportion of the total weight for all records in the group.</p><p>The diagram below shows how weighted routing works and is configured:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-49-01-36ad12850a17d4577ecc434bf3738f8e.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Configure an Amazon Route 53 weighted routing policy that directs 90% of the traffic to the ALB and 10% to the on-premises application" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure an Amazon Route 53 multivalue routing policy and configure 90% of the endpoint addresses to point to the ALB and 10% to the on-premises application" is incorrect.</p><p>Multivalue answer routing lets you configure Amazon Route 53 to return multiple values, such as IP addresses for your web servers, in response to DNS queries. You cannot weight the records that are returned.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add the on-premises application servers to a target group, add the target group to the ALB and use path-based routing to direct 10% of the traffic to the on-premises application" is incorrect.</p><p>Neither host-based routing nor path-based routing are applicable here. These are techniques for routing based on information in the host header or URL path respectively. In this example the requests will not have a different host header or path.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Add the on-premises application servers to a target group, add the target group to the ALB and use host-based routing to direct 10% of the traffic to the on-premises application" is incorrect.</p><p>Please see the explanation for the previous incorrect answer.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html#routing-policy-weighted">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html#routing-policy-weighted</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure an Amazon Route 53 multivalue routing policy and configure 90% of the endpoint addresses to point to the ALB and 10% to the on-premises application.</p>', '<p>Add the on-premises application servers to a target group, add the target group to the ALB and use path-based routing to direct 10% of the traffic to the on-premises application.</p>', '<p>Configure an Amazon Route 53 weighted routing policy that directs 90% of the traffic to the ALB and 10% to the on-premises application.</p>', '<p>Add the on-premises application servers to a target group, add the target group to the ALB and use host-based routing to direct 10% of the traffic to the on-premises application.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company runs a web application in the AWS Cloud. The web application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The development team release updates on a scaled down version of the application running on-premises. The development team requires that when new updates are ready 10% of the website traffic is directed to the on-premises application.Which configuration changes should a network engineer make?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203958, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company runs EC2 instances in private subnets across multiple Availability Zones. The instances require outbound internet access which must be redundant. An internet gateway has been attached to the VPC.</p><p>Which actions should a network engineer take to provision redundant and scalable internet access?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>This question is simply checking that you understand how to implement NAT gateways for high availability. The solution is to deploy the NAT gateway across multiple Availability Zones. This will ensure that the NAT gateway nodes are deployed across AZs which provides high availability. NAT gateway scales seamlessly up to 45 Gbps.</p><p>Remember that when deploying a NAT gateway, the actual gateway is deployed into public subnets, but the route tables of private subnets must be updated.</p><p>NAT instances do not offer high availability or elasticity. The following table outlines the most important differences between the NAT instance and NAT gateway:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-50-33-dcbda0d9c299646172d1e251c2fcabaf.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy NAT gateways in public subnets of each Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT gateway for all non-VPC traffic" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy NAT gateways in private subnets of each Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT gateway for all non-VPC traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>NAT gateways must be deployed in public subnets and referenced in route tables of private subnets.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a NAT instance in a public subnet of an Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT instances for all non-VPC traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>The NAT instances are not elastically scalable and deploying an instance in a single AZ will not provide HA.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a NAT instance in a private subnet of an Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT instances for all non-VPC traffic" is incorrect.</p><p>NAT instances must also be deployed in public subnets.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-nat-gateway.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-nat-gateway.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Deploy NAT gateways in public subnets of each Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT gateway for all non-VPC traffic.</p>', '<p>Deploy NAT gateways in private subnets of each Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT gateway for all non-VPC traffic.</p>', '<p>Deploy a NAT instance in a public subnet of an Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT instances for all non-VPC traffic.</p>', '<p>Deploy a NAT instance in a private subnet of an Availability Zone. Update the route tables of private subnets to point to the NAT instances for all non-VPC traffic.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company runs EC2 instances in private subnets across multiple Availability Zones. The instances require outbound internet access which must be redundant. An internet gateway has been attached to the VPC.Which actions should a network engineer take to provision redundant and scalable internet access?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203960, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company regularly creates individual AWS accounts for different projects based on software development lifecycle (SDLC) phases such as Development (Dev), Quality Assurance (QA), and Production (Prod). All accounts are added to an AWS Organizations organization.</p><p>The company is looking for a way to enforce infrastructure compliance and consistency across these different accounts. Specifically, the company require a method to enable developers to deploy Amazon VPCs quickly, securely, and easily in any environment.</p><p>Which solution meets these requirements with the LEAST administrative effort?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Service Catalog is in scope for the Advanced Networking exam with regards to deploying infrastructure components such as Amazon VPCs. Service Catalog allows administrators to create predefined and approved products based on CloudFormation templates.</p><p>Service Catalog integrates with AWS Organizations to make sharing of products easy. In this case the administrator can create products for common VPC deployments based on an approved CloudFormation template. The product should be shared with the organization or specific OUs to make deployment easier.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Provision an AWS Service Catalog portfolio that hosts an approved VPC template in a shared services account. Share the VPC product with the organization " is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Provision an AWS Service Catalog portfolio that hosts an approved VPC template in a shared services account. Create IAM roles in each project account for deploying the product" is incorrect.</p><p>Using IAM roles would make the solution more complex to deploy and considering the company already adds all accounts to AWS Organizations it would be easier to share the product with the organization.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a centralized Amazon VPC in a shared service account. Share the VPC using AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM)" is incorrect.</p><p>This would create a shared VPC that could be accessed across accounts. This does not meet the requirements as what the developers want to do is to automate the creation of standardized VPCs within each new account.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an AWS CloudFormation template and store it in an Amazon S3 bucket. Instruct developers to download the template and use it to create a CloudFormation Stack that deploys the VPC" is incorrect.</p><p>This is another example of a solution that would require more effort on the part of the developers. The network administrator wants to make the deployment simple so using Service Catalog is a better solution.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/mt/standardizing-infrastructure-delivery-in-distributed-environments-using-aws-service-catalog/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/mt/standardizing-infrastructure-delivery-in-distributed-environments-using-aws-service-catalog/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Provision an AWS Service Catalog portfolio that hosts an approved VPC template in a shared services account. Create IAM roles in each project account for deploying the product.</p>', '<p>Create a centralized Amazon VPC in a shared service account. Share the VPC using AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM).</p>', '<p>Provision an AWS Service Catalog portfolio that hosts an approved VPC template in a shared services account. Share the VPC product with the organization.</p>', '<p>Create an AWS CloudFormation template and store it in an Amazon S3 bucket. Instruct developers to download the template and use it to create a CloudFormation Stack that deploys the VPC.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company regularly creates individual AWS accounts for different projects based on software development lifecycle (SDLC) phases such as Development (Dev), Quality Assurance (QA), and Production (Prod). All accounts are added to an AWS Organizations organization.The company is looking for a way to enforce infrastructure compliance and consistency across these different accounts. Specifically, the company require a method to enable developers to deploy Amazon VPCs quickly, securely, and easily in any environment.Which solution meets these requirements with the LEAST administrative effort?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203962, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network administrator is asked to troubleshoot an issue with an Amazon VPC. Users have reported that internet access has stopped working. The administrator checked the route table and found the following entry</p><p><strong>Destination Target Status</strong></p><p>0.0.0.0/0 igw-XXXXX Black Hole</p><p>What is the most likely explanation for the failure of internet access?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>A black hole indicates that the internet gateway specified in the route is not accessible. This could be due to the internet gateway being detached from the VPC or it may have been deleted. If the internet gateway is detached from the VPC it can be easily re-attached. If the internet gateway has been deleted a new internet gateway must be created and attached to the VPC and the route table would need to be updated.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"The internet gateway has been detached from the VPC" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The internet gateway is not attached to the VPC subnets" is incorrect.</p><p>Internet gateways are attached to VPCs and referenced in subnet route tables. They are not attached to subnets.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Route propagation has failed for the internet gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>Route propagation is not the issue when a black hole status is reported. This is more likely due to the internet gateway being unattached or deleted.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "The NAT gateway has been deleted" is incorrect.</p><p>A NAT gateway is not referenced in the route table, only an internet gateway.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/API_Route.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/API_Route.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>The NAT gateway has been deleted.</p>', '<p>The internet gateway is not attached to the VPC subnets.</p>', '<p>Route propagation has failed for the internet gateway.</p>', '<p>The internet gateway has been detached from the VPC.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 3: Network Management and Operation', 'question_plain': 'A network administrator is asked to troubleshoot an issue with an Amazon VPC. Users have reported that internet access has stopped working. The administrator checked the route table and found the following entryDestination Target Status0.0.0.0/0 igw-XXXXX Black HoleWhat is the most likely explanation for the failure of internet access?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203964, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying a solution for sharing media files around the world using Amazon CloudFront with an Amazon S3 origin configured as a static website. The company requires that all traffic for the website must be inspected by AWS WAF.</p><p>Which solution meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The AWS Web Application Firewall (WAF) can be attached to an Amazon CloudFront distribution to enable protection from web exploits. In this case the distribution uses an S3 origin, and the question is stating that all traffic must be inspected by AWS WAF. This means we need to ensure that requests cannot circumvent AWS WAF and hit the S3 bucket directly.</p><p>This can be achieved by configuring an origin access identity (OAI) which is a special type of CloudFront user that is created within the distribution and configured in an S3 bucket policy. The policy will only allow requests that come from the OAI which means all requests must come via the distribution and cannot hit S3 directly.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-06_21-53-38-82608edc650036c74a5dfda8108d914d.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy CloudFront with an S3 origin and configure an origin access identity (OAI) to restrict access to the S3 bucket. Enable AWS WAF on the CloudFront distribution" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Network ACL that limits access to the S3 bucket to the CloudFront IP addresses. Attach a WebACL to the CloudFront distribution" is incorrect.</p><p>Network ACLs restrict traffic in/out of subnets but S3 is a public service.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an Amazon Route 53 Alias record to forward traffic for the website to AWS WAF. Configure AWS WAF to inspect traffic and attach the CloudFront distribution" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot direct traffic to AWS WAF using an Alias record.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an S3 bucket policy with a condition that only allows requests that originate from AWS WAF" is incorrect.</p><p>This cannot be done. Instead use an OAI in the bucket policy.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/private-content-restricting-access-to-s3.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/private-content-restricting-access-to-s3.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create a Network ACL that limits access to the S3 bucket to the CloudFront IP addresses. Attach a WebACL to the CloudFront distribution.</p>', '<p>Use an Amazon Route 53 Alias record to forward traffic for the website to AWS WAF. Configure AWS WAF to inspect traffic and attach the CloudFront distribution.</p>', '<p>Create an S3 bucket policy with a condition that only allows requests that originate from AWS WAF.</p>', '<p>Deploy CloudFront with an S3 origin and configure an origin access identity (OAI) to restrict access to the S3 bucket. Enable AWS WAF on the CloudFront distribution.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying a solution for sharing media files around the world using Amazon CloudFront with an Amazon S3 origin configured as a static website. The company requires that all traffic for the website must be inspected by AWS WAF.Which solution meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 57203966, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A fleet of Amazon EC2 instances run in a single Amazon VPC. Inter-instance communications use private IP addresses. A new requirement specifies that the domain name retrieved through the DHCP protocol should be different for a specific set of instances located in a separate subnet.</p><p>How can the specific instances be allocated a different domain name by DHCP without affecting instances in other subnets?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) provides a standard for passing configuration information to hosts on a TCP/IP network. The options field of a DHCP message contains configuration parameters, including the domain name, domain name server, and the netbios-node-type.</p><p>When you create a VPC, AWS automatically creates a set of DHCP options and associates them with the VPC. You can configure your own DHCP options set for your VPC. You cannot modify an existing DHCP options set.</p><p>In this case a new VPC must be created as a specific set of instances require a different domain name than others. As the DHCP options set is associated at the VPC (not subnet) level, a separate VPC is required. VPC peering will then allow the instances to continue to communicate using private IP addresses.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a new VPC, configure the DHCP option set with the different domain name, and re-launch the specific instances there. Establish a VPC peering connection" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a new DHCP option set with the different domain name and associate it with the specified subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>As explained above, a DHCP option set is associated with a VPC, not a subnet.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Modify the existing DHCP option set and specify a different domain name for instances in the specified subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot modify an existing DHCP option set. You must create a new one and associate it at the VPC level.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Modify the instances to use the Amazon provided DNS server using the IP address 169.254.269.25" is incorrect.</p><p>The DNS server does not allocate the domain name to the client. The DHCP protocol is used for configuring the DNS domain name on the client.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_DHCP_Options.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_DHCP_Options.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Modify the existing DHCP option set and specify a different domain name for instances in the specified subnet.</p>', '<p>Create a new DHCP option set with the different domain name and associate it with the specified subnet.</p>', '<p>Create a new VPC, configure the DHCP option set with the different domain name, and re-launch the specific instances there. Establish a VPC peering connection.</p>', '<p>Modify the instances to use the Amazon provided DNS server using the IP address 169.254.269.253.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A fleet of Amazon EC2 instances run in a single Amazon VPC. Inter-instance communications use private IP addresses. A new requirement specifies that the domain name retrieved through the DHCP protocol should be different for a specific set of instances located in a separate subnet.How can the specific instances be allocated a different domain name by DHCP without affecting instances in other subnets?', 'related_lectures': []}]}
