{'count': 20, 'next': None, 'previous': None, 'results': [{'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265722, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A manager is trying to determine the overall cost of an application that will be deployed across a hybrid environment. The application includes EC2 instances in an Amazon VPC that process large volumes of data. The data will then be sent across a private virtual interface of an AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection to an analytics application in an on-premises data center.</p><p>What costs will be incurred to the data being sent over the DX connection? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>There are three factors that determine pricing for AWS Direct Connect: capacity, port-hours, and data transfer out (DTO). Data transfer in is charged at a rate of 0.00 USD per GB so there is not cost for moving data into AWS.</p><p><strong>Capacity</strong> is the maximum rate that data can be transferred through a network connection. The capacity of AWS Direct Connect connections are measured in megabit per second (Mbps) or gigabit per second (Gbps). One gigabit per second, or 1 Gbps, is equal to 1,000 megabits per second (1,000 Mbps).</p><p><strong>Port-hours</strong> measure the time that a port is provisioned for your use with AWS, or an AWS Direct Connect Delivery Partner’s, networking equipment inside an AWS Direct Connect location. Even when no data is passing through the port, you are charged for port-hours. Port-hour pricing is determined by the connection type: dedicated or hosted.</p><p><strong>Data transfer out (DTO)</strong> refers to the cumulative network traffic that is sent through AWS Direct Connect to destinations outside of AWS. This is charged per gigabyte (GB), and unlike capacity measurements, DTO refers to the amount of data transferred, not the speed.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Per gigabyte charges for data transfer out" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Capacity charges for provisioned throughput" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Per virtual interface charges for private VIFs" is incorrect.</p><p>You pay for hosted or dedicated connections, but you do not pay per virtual interface.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Per gigabyte charges for data transfer in" is incorrect.</p><p>Data transfer in is charged at a rate of 0.00 USD per GB so there is not cost for moving data into AWS</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Per cross connect between racks in the data center" is incorrect.</p><p>You do not pay for the cross connects that are provisioned between racks in the data center. You pay for port hours based on the amount of time a port is provisioned for your use.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/directconnect/pricing/">https://aws.amazon.com/directconnect/pricing/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Per gigabyte charges for data transfer out.</p>', '<p>Per virtual interface charges for private VIFs.</p>', '<p>Per gigabyte charges for data transfer in.</p>', '<p>Per cross connect between racks in the data center.</p>', '<p>Capacity charges for provisioned throughput.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'e'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A manager is trying to determine the overall cost of an application that will be deployed across a hybrid environment. The application includes EC2 instances in an Amazon VPC that process large volumes of data. The data will then be sent across a private virtual interface of an AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection to an analytics application in an on-premises data center.What costs will be incurred to the data being sent over the DX connection? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265724, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has several Amazon VPCs and an on-premises data center. The company plans to connect all VPCs and the on-premises data center for full, transitive, interconnectivity. Latency must be low, and throughput should be consistent. All VPCs use non-overlapping CIDR ranges.</p><p>Which design options should the company select? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The company requires low latency connectivity with consistent throughput. For connecting the on-premises data center this will necessitate the use of AWS Direct Connect as a VPN connection will not offer consistent performance.</p><p>For interconnectivity between the DX connection and the VPCs and AWS Transit Gateway can be deployed with VPC and DX attachments. Transit Gateway offers full transitive routing and hybrid connectivity.</p><p>The diagram below depicts a solution with Transit Gateway, multiple VPCs, and a corporate office/on-premises location:</p><p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_00-41-09-38d82de48c6816de0340fa4b324004bd.jpg"></p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"AWS Transit Gateway with VPC and Direct Connect attachments" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"AWS Direct Connect for connecting the on-premises data center" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Amazon VPC Peering Connections with a NAT Gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot use VPC peering when you have overlapping CIDR ranges, and it does not offer transitive routing. Using a NAT Gateway does not assist with getting around the overlapping CIDR issue.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "AWS Site-to-Site VPN for connecting the on-premises data center" is incorrect.</p><p>This would not offer consistent performance so an AWS Direct Connect connection should be used instead.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "AWS Transit Gateway with VPC and VPN attachments" is incorrect.</p><p>The Transit Gateway should be used with a VPC and DX attachment rather than a VPN attachment.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/building-scalable-secure-multi-vpc-network-infrastructure/transit-gateway-vs-vpc-peering.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/building-scalable-secure-multi-vpc-network-infrastructure/transit-gateway-vs-vpc-peering.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>AWS Transit Gateway with VPC and Direct Connect attachments.</p>', '<p>Amazon VPC Peering Connections with a NAT Gateway.</p>', '<p>AWS Direct Connect for connecting the on-premises data center.</p>', '<p>AWS Site-to-Site VPN for connecting the on-premises data center.</p>', '<p>AWS Transit Gateway with VPC and VPN attachments.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company has several Amazon VPCs and an on-premises data center. The company plans to connect all VPCs and the on-premises data center for full, transitive, interconnectivity. Latency must be low, and throughput should be consistent. All VPCs use non-overlapping CIDR ranges.Which design options should the company select? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265726, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A network engineer has recently deployed an AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection. The company already has an AWS Site-to-Site VPN which should be used as a backup, but the engineer has noticed that all traffic is passing through the VPN and not using the Direct Connect connection. The VPN uses the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).</p><p>What should the network engineer do to route the traffic through the Direct Connect connection?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>There are a few requirements to ensure that the VPN is used as a backup to the DX connection. The following requirements must be met:</p><ul><li><p>Be sure that you use the same virtual private gateway for both Direct Connect and the VPN connection to the VPC.</p></li><li><p>If you are configuring a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) VPN, advertise the same prefix for Direct Connect and the VPN.</p></li><li><p>If you are configuring a static VPN, add the same static prefixes to the VPN connection that you are announcing with the Direct Connect virtual interface.</p></li></ul><p>In this case the VPN uses BGP so the answer that specifies to advertise the same prefixes for DX and VPN is the best answer. Note that AWS prefers BGP paths through DX connections to VPN connections so the traffic will always use DX if it is available.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Advertise the same prefix for Direct Connect and the VPN" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Configure the DX connection AS_PATH to be longer than the VPN AS_PATH" is incorrect.</p><p>If you are advertising the same routes toward the AWS VPC, the Direct Connect path is always be preferred, regardless of AS path prepending.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Remove the VPN connection from the VPC route table" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not necessary and would result in the VPN connection not being used at all which is not desired.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Reconfigure the DX and VPN connections to use static routing" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not necessary; you can still use dynamic routing with BGP as per the explanation above.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/hybrid-connectivity/vpn-connection-as-a-backup-to-aws-dx-connection-example.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/hybrid-connectivity/vpn-connection-as-a-backup-to-aws-dx-connection-example.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Configure the DX connection AS_PATH to be longer than the VPN AS_PATH.</p>', '<p>Remove the VPN connection from the VPC route table.</p>', '<p>Advertise the same prefix for Direct Connect and the VPN.</p>', '<p>Reconfigure the DX and VPN connections to use static routing.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A network engineer has recently deployed an AWS Direct Connect (DX) connection. The company already has an AWS Site-to-Site VPN which should be used as a backup, but the engineer has noticed that all traffic is passing through the VPN and not using the Direct Connect connection. The VPN uses the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).What should the network engineer do to route the traffic through the Direct Connect connection?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265728, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application that receives connections from the internet requires security inspection of the incoming traffic. The security inspection will be performed by a fleet of network virtual appliances deployed in a separate VPC. All communication should use private addresses and only the endpoints for connecting to the virtual appliances should be exposed and routable from the application VPC.</p><p>How can a network engineer configure the solution according to the requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>With this solution, a fleet of security appliances is configured behind a Gateway Load Balancer in a separate VPC. An endpoint service is configured for the Gateway Load Balancer. The owner of the application VPC creates a Gateway Load Balancer endpoint in subnet 2 in their VPC (represented by an endpoint network interface).</p><p>All traffic entering the VPC through the internet gateway is first routed to the Gateway Load Balancer endpoint for inspection in the security VPC before it\'s routed to the destination subnet. Similarly, all traffic leaving the EC2 instance in subnet 1 is first routed to Gateway Load Balancer endpoint for inspection in the security VPC before it\'s routed to the internet.</p><p>This solution is depicted in the diagram below:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_00-44-10-6424b8c936ab00972b171d52ce8e04c8.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy a Gateway Load Balancer (GLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC endpoint service for the GLB endpoints in the application VPC. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the GLB before routing it to the application instances" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC endpoint service for the NLB endpoints in the application VPC. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the NLB before routing it to the application instances" is incorrect.</p><p>A Gateway Load Balancer (GLB) should be used for routing traffic to virtual appliances for security inspection.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a Gateway Load Balancer (GLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC peering connection between the VPCs. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the GLB before routing it to the application instances" is incorrect.</p><p>A VPC endpoint should be used for this solution. Note the requirements indicated that only the GLB endpoints should be routable and VPC peering would enable full routing between subnets.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC peering connection between the VPCs. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the NLB before routing it to the application instances" is incorrect.</p><p>This answer specifies the wrong type of ELB (an NLB rather than a GLB) and uses VPC peering instead of a VPC endpoint which is incorrect as explained previously.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/privatelink/vpc-endpoint-services-gwlbe.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/privatelink/vpc-endpoint-services-gwlbe.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Deploy a Gateway Load Balancer (GLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC endpoint service for the GLB endpoints in the application VPC. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the GLB before routing it to the application instances.</p>', '<p>Deploy a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC endpoint service for the NLB endpoints in the application VPC. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the NLB before routing it to the application instances.</p>', '<p>Deploy a Gateway Load Balancer (GLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC peering connection between the VPCs. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the GLB before routing it to the application instances.</p>', '<p>Deploy a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in front of the network virtual appliances. Create a VPC peering connection between the VPCs. Update the VPC route tables to route all incoming application traffic to the NLB before routing it to the application instances.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'An application that receives connections from the internet requires security inspection of the incoming traffic. The security inspection will be performed by a fleet of network virtual appliances deployed in a separate VPC. All communication should use private addresses and only the endpoints for connecting to the virtual appliances should be exposed and routable from the application VPC.How can a network engineer configure the solution according to the requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265730, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company plans to run multiple SaaS applications behind a single load balancer. The solution must support Server Name Indication (SNI) to allow multiple SSL/TLS certificates to be added and connections should be routed to targets based on the host header included in the request.</p><p>Which type of load balancer should be used?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Both the ALB and NLB support SNI. This means that you can add multiple SSL/TLS certificates to the load balancer and the most appropriate certificate will be selected when a client connects. However, NLB does not support host-based routing so it will be unable to route connection requests to targets based on the host header.</p><p>The ALB supports host-based routing, path-based routing, query string parameter-based routing, and source IP address-based routing</p><p>The diagram below shows how you can use both host-based and path-based routing with an Application Load Balancer:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_00-46-10-af43cca3cd8f8b70241643888a56477a.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Application Load Balancer" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Network Load Balancer" is incorrect.</p><p>The NLB supports SNI but does not support host-based routing.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Gateway Load Balancer" is incorrect.</p><p>The GLB is used for distributing connections to security devices such as IDS/IPS systems.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Classic Load Balancer" is incorrect.</p><p>The CLB does not support SNI, nor does it support host-based routing.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/features/">https://aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/features/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Application Load Balancer.</p>', '<p>Network Load Balancer.</p>', '<p>Gateway Load Balancer.</p>', '<p>Classic Load Balancer.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company plans to run multiple SaaS applications behind a single load balancer. The solution must support Server Name Indication (SNI) to allow multiple SSL/TLS certificates to be added and connections should be routed to targets based on the host header included in the request.Which type of load balancer should be used?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265732, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company uses an Amazon Route 53 public hosted zone for their company domain records. A network administrator must configure logging for the public DNS queries that Route 53 receives.</p><p>Which solution meets these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>You can configure Amazon Route 53 to log information about the public DNS queries that Route 53 receives, such as the following:</p><ul><li><p>domain or subdomain that was requested</p></li><li><p>Date and time of the request</p></li><li><p>DNS record type (such as A or AAAA)</p></li><li><p>Route 53 edge location that responded to the DNS query</p></li><li><p>DNS response code, such as NoError or ServFail</p></li></ul><p>Once you configure query logging, Route 53 will send logs to CloudWatch Logs. You use CloudWatch Logs tools to access the query logs.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use Route 53 query logging to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use VPC Flow Logs to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs" is incorrect.</p><p>VPC Flow Logs captures data about the IP traffic within your VPC. It does not capture DNS queries for public hosted zones.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use AWS GuardDuty to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs" is incorrect.</p><p>GuardDuty is a threat detection service and does not log information about DNS queries to CloudWatch Logs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use AWS CloudTrail to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs" is incorrect.</p><p>CloudTrail is used to capture API activity. It does not capture DNS queries as these do not generate API actions within your AWS account.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/query-logs.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/query-logs.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use AWS GuardDuty to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs.</p>', '<p>Use VPC Flow Logs to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs.</p>', '<p>Use Route 53 query logging to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs.</p>', '<p>Use AWS CloudTrail to log information to Amazon CloudWatch Logs.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company uses an Amazon Route 53 public hosted zone for their company domain records. A network administrator must configure logging for the public DNS queries that Route 53 receives.Which solution meets these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265734, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>The security team of a company has recently updated their security policy for firewall rules. The team requires that only ports TCP 80, and TCP 443 should be open to any source address. Existing security groups should be modified to adhere to the new guidance.</p><p>How can a network administrator most easily identify security groups that do not adhere to the new policy?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>AWS Config is a service that enables you to assess, audit, and evaluate the configurations of your AWS resources. Config continuously monitors and records your AWS resource configurations and allows you to automate the evaluation of recorded configurations against desired configurations.</p><p>The AWS Config managed rule “vpc-sg-open-only-to-authorized-ports” checks whether any security groups with inbound 0.0.0.0/0 have TCP or UDP ports accessible. The rule is NON_COMPLIANT when a security group with inbound 0.0.0.0/0 (any source address) has a port accessible which is not specified in the rule parameters.</p><p>To configure the rule, you must supply a comma-separated list of TCP ports authorized to be open to 0.0.0.0/0. If any other ports are open to any source address the rule will be NON_COMPLIANT and the network administrator can then remediate the issue.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use the AWS Config managed rule “vpc-sg-open-only-to-authorized-ports” and specify a comma-separated list of authorized TCP ports" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Write an AWS Lambda function that uses the AWS API to query security groups looking for rules that allow ports TCP 80, and TCP 443 from 0.0.0.0/" is incorrect.</p><p>Though this is certainly possible it is not the easiest way to achieve this outcome. It would be much easier to use the AWS Config managed rule.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use the AWS Config managed rule “ec2-instance-no-public-ip” and specify a comma-separated list of authorized TCP ports" is incorrect.</p><p>This rule checks whether Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) instances have a public IP association.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a VPC Flow Log that writes to Amazon S3. Use Amazon Athena to query the log files and identify accepted connections on ports TCP 80, and TCP 44" is incorrect.</p><p>Identifying successful connections to these ports does not help to identify the configuration of the security group, especially as these are the ports that should be allowed to have connections from any source address.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/vpc-sg-open-only-to-authorized-ports.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/vpc-sg-open-only-to-authorized-ports.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Write an AWS Lambda function that uses the AWS API to query security groups looking for rules that allow ports TCP 80, and TCP 443 from 0.0.0.0/0.</p>', '<p>Use the AWS Config managed rule “ec2-instance-no-public-ip” and specify a comma-separated list of authorized TCP ports.</p>', '<p>Create a VPC Flow Log that writes to Amazon S3. Use Amazon Athena to query the log files and identify accepted connections on ports TCP 80, and TCP 443.</p>', '<p>Use the AWS Config managed rule “vpc-sg-open-only-to-authorized-ports” and specify a comma-separated list of authorized TCP ports.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'The security team of a company has recently updated their security policy for firewall rules. The team requires that only ports TCP 80, and TCP 443 should be open to any source address. Existing security groups should be modified to adhere to the new guidance.How can a network administrator most easily identify security groups that do not adhere to the new policy?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265736, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying a web application that uses an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The ALB will be connected to public subnets in the same Availability Zones (AZs) as the private subnets in which the applications instances will be deployed.</p><p>The Auto Scaling group is expected to grow up to 100 instances and the application must be highly available across three AZs.</p><p>Which of the following subnets designs is suitable for the EC2 application instances?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The solution must be highly available across three AZs, therefore we need three subnets as each subnet maps to one AZ and cannot span across AZs.</p><p>Next, we must determine which subnet mask to use. The following subnet masks were included in answers:</p><p>· /25 – this provides 128 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>· /26 – this provides 64 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>· /27 – this provides 32 IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>AWS also reserve the first four and last address in each subnet so you must subtract 5 from the above number of IP addresses to determine the usable IP addresses per subnet.</p><p>This solution requires up to 100 EC2 instances across the three subnets. The best subnet mask to use from the options available is a /26 as this will provide room for up to 177 EC2 instances.</p><p>The calculation to reach this number if 64 (total IPs) – 5 (reserved IPs) x 3 (subnets) = 177.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Three subnets with a /26 subnet mask across three AZs" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Three subnets with a /27 subnet mask across three AZs" is incorrect.</p><p>Using a /27 subnet mask will only allow for a maximum of 81 EC2 instances. The calculation to reach this number if 32 (total IPs) – 5 (reserved IPs) x 3 (subnets) = 81.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Two subnets with a /26 subnet mask across three AZs" is incorrect.</p><p>Three subnets must be used to enable high availability across three AZs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Two subnets with a /25 subnet mask across three AZs" is incorrect.</p><p>Three subnets must be used to enable high availability across three AZs.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Two subnets with a /26 subnet mask across three AZs.</p>', '<p>Three subnets with a /27 subnet mask across three AZs.</p>', '<p>Two subnets with a /25 subnet mask across three AZs.</p>', '<p>Three subnets with a /26 subnet mask across three AZs.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['d'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying a web application that uses an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The ALB will be connected to public subnets in the same Availability Zones (AZs) as the private subnets in which the applications instances will be deployed.The Auto Scaling group is expected to grow up to 100 instances and the application must be highly available across three AZs.Which of the following subnets designs is suitable for the EC2 application instances?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265738, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is planning to deploy an application into an Amazon VPC. The application will run on Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group in a single subnet. The application requires a local network interface in the subnet for communicating with a database instance. The application also requires a network interface in a separate subnet for communication with a web service. The company has already created an AMI for deployment.</p><p>Which steps should be taken to meet these requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Launch templates can be used to create custom networking configurations. Within a launch template you can add multiple Elastic Network Interfaces (ENIs) and specify settings such as the availability zones they should be connected to.</p><p>Note that you cannot attach multiple ENIs to an Amazon EC2 instance connected to subnets in different availability zones. Each ENI must be connected to a subnet in the same availability zone.</p><p>The diagram below provides more information on using multiple ENIs:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_00-57-45-afb9cb732e66f831c9ee953cff7d7f67.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create multiple subnets in the same availability zone. Create a launch template for the AMI that includes a custom network configuration with ENIs in each subnet. Create an Auto Scaling group based on the new template" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create multiple subnets in different availability zones. Create a launch configuration for the AMI that includes a custom network configuration with ENIs in each subnet. Create an Auto Scaling group based on the new template" is incorrect.</p><p>The subnets must be in the same availability zone. This solution will not work as the subnets are in different AZs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create multiple subnets in the same availability zone. Create a launch template for with a standard network configuration. Create an AWS Lambda function which adds an additional ENI. Create an Auto Scaling group based on the new launch template. Create a lifecycle hook to invoke the Lambda function" is incorrect.</p><p>Using Lambda is totally unnecessary as the solution requirements can be easily met using the launch template.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create multiple subnets in different availability zones. Create a new launch template with default network settings. Create an Auto Scaling group and select two subnets to be used for the instances" is incorrect.</p><p>Subnets must be the same AZ and custom network settings should be used as explained above.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-eni.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-eni.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create multiple subnets in the same availability zone. Create a launch template for the AMI that includes a custom network configuration with ENIs in each subnet. Create an Auto Scaling group based on the new template.</p>', '<p>Create multiple subnets in different availability zones. Create a launch configuration for the AMI that includes a custom network configuration with ENIs in each subnet. Create an Auto Scaling group based on the new template.</p>', '<p>Create multiple subnets in the same availability zone. Create a launch template for with a standard network configuration. Create an AWS Lambda function which adds an additional ENI. Create an Auto Scaling group based on the new launch template. Create a lifecycle hook to invoke the Lambda function.</p>', '<p>Create multiple subnets in different availability zones. Create a new launch template with default network settings. Create an Auto Scaling group and select two subnets to be used for the instances.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is planning to deploy an application into an Amazon VPC. The application will run on Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group in a single subnet. The application requires a local network interface in the subnet for communicating with a database instance. The application also requires a network interface in a separate subnet for communication with a web service. The company has already created an AMI for deployment.Which steps should be taken to meet these requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265740, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company manages a hybrid network across its on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC. The company is planning to deploy an Amazon EFS file system that will be used by on-premises servers. The on-premises servers must resolve DNS queries using local DNS servers. The company plans to use a custom domain name for Amazon EFS and local servers should connect to EFS using the domain name.</p><p>What should a network engineer do to meet these requirements? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>On-premises servers will be provided with the addresses of local DNS servers to use for DNS queries. The requirements of this solution are that the on-premises server must be able to resolve DNS queries for AWS service within the VPC using the local DNS server.</p><p>An inbound Route 53 Resolver can provide this capability. With an inbound resolver, queries received by on-premises DNS servers are forwarded to the Route 53 Resolver inbound endpoint which can resolve queries using a Route 53 hosted zone.</p><p>The hosted zone in Route 53 can be configured with a record for the Amazon EFS custom domain name. The type of record should be a CNAME record which will be resolved to the domain name of the EFS file system.</p><p>Therefore, the network engineer should create an inbound endpoint for Route 53 Resolver and a CNAME record in a hosted zone for the EFS mount targets.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_00-59-40-f421cbe3eab97579f8cc6ed688a81b07.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create an Amazon Route 53 Resolver inbound endpoint and configure it for the VPC where Amazon EFS resides" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a Route 53 private hosted zone and add a new CNAME record with the value of the Amazon EFS DNS name. Configure forwarding rules on the on-premises DNS servers to forward queries for the custom domain host to the Route 53 Resolver" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an Amazon Route 53 Resolver outbound endpoint and configure it for the VPC where Amazon EFS resides" is incorrect.</p><p>An outbound endpoint is used to forward DNS resolution queries to DNS servers in the on-premises data center which is the opposite of the requirements for this solution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution with a custom origin pointing to the Amazon EFS file system" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot add an EFS file system as a custom origin for a CloudFront distribution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Route 53 private hosted zone and add a new SRV record with the value of the Amazon EFS DNS name. Configure forwarding rules on the on-premises DNS servers to forward queries for the custom domain host to the Route 53 Resolver" is incorrect.</p><p>The SRV record is a server locator record and is the wrong type of record to use here. A CNAME record is a canonical name record which maps one host name to another. For this solution a CNAME record should be used to map the custom domain name to the mount target domain name for the EFS file system.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resolver.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resolver.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create an Amazon Route 53 Resolver inbound endpoint and configure it for the VPC where Amazon EFS resides.</p>', '<p>Create an Amazon Route 53 Resolver outbound endpoint and configure it for the VPC where Amazon EFS resides.</p>', '<p>Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution with a custom origin pointing to the Amazon EFS file system.</p>', '<p>Create a Route 53 private hosted zone and add a new CNAME record with the value of the Amazon EFS DNS name. Configure forwarding rules on the on-premises DNS servers to forward queries for the custom domain host to the Route 53 Resolver.</p>', '<p>Create a Route 53 private hosted zone and add a new SRV record with the value of the Amazon EFS DNS name. Configure forwarding rules on the on-premises DNS servers to forward queries for the custom domain host to the Route 53 Resolver.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'd'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company manages a hybrid network across its on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC. The company is planning to deploy an Amazon EFS file system that will be used by on-premises servers. The on-premises servers must resolve DNS queries using local DNS servers. The company plans to use a custom domain name for Amazon EFS and local servers should connect to EFS using the domain name.What should a network engineer do to meet these requirements? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265742, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying a network security inspection service running on an Amazon EC2 instance. All traffic passing between the VPC and an on-premises data center must pass through the security instance.</p><p>How can a network engineer deploy the security instance to maximize network performance? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Enhanced networking uses single root I/O virtualization (SR-IOV) to provide high-performance networking capabilities on supported instance types. SR-IOV is a method of device virtualization that provides higher I/O performance and lower CPU utilization when compared to traditional virtualized network interfaces.</p><p>Enhanced networking provides higher bandwidth, higher packet per second (PPS) performance, and consistently lower inter-instance latencies. There is no additional charge for using enhanced networking.</p><p>Another technique for improving network performance is to add multiple ENIs to an EC2 instance. Instances with multiple network cards provide higher network performance, including bandwidth capabilities above 100 Gbps and improved packet rate performance. Each network interface is attached to a network card.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use an EC2 instance that supports enhanced networking" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Attach multiple elastic network interfaces to the EC2 instance" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Send outbound traffic through a NAT gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>A NAT gateway will not assist with accelerating performance and is only used for connecting instances in private subnets to the internet via an internet gateway.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach an Elastic IP Address to the EC2 instance" is incorrect.</p><p>Adding an EIP does not improve performance, it means you get a static public IP address. This would not even be used for private communications between an EC2 instance and on-premises systems when using a VPN or Direct Connect.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach an Elastic Fabric Adapter to the EC2 instance" is incorrect.</p><p>An EFA is used for accelerating performance for High Performance Computing (HPC) and machine learning applications. It is used where inter-instance communications must have very low latency. This is not a good use case for an EFA.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/enhanced-networking.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/enhanced-networking.html</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-eni.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-eni.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use an EC2 instance that supports enhanced networking.</p>', '<p>Send outbound traffic through a NAT gateway.</p>', '<p>Attach an Elastic IP Address to the EC2 instance.</p>', '<p>Attach an Elastic Fabric Adapter to the EC2 instance.</p>', '<p>Attach multiple elastic network interfaces to the EC2 instance.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'e'], 'section': 'Domain 4: Network Security, Compliance, and Governance', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying a network security inspection service running on an Amazon EC2 instance. All traffic passing between the VPC and an on-premises data center must pass through the security instance.How can a network engineer deploy the security instance to maximize network performance? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265744, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company is deploying a service that runs on TCP port 80 in VPC A within AWS Account A. The company wants to provide access to the service to client EC2 instances in VPC B within AWS Account B. The service will be exposed using AWS PrivateLink.</p><p>Which tasks should the network engineer complete to meet these requirements? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>There are three knowledge tests in this question:</p><p>1. Which type of load balancer should be used for AWS PrivateLink? The correct choice is a Network Load Balancer as ALBs cannot be used for this purpose.</p><p>2. Which type of listener should be used for the NLB? The correct choice is a TCP listener as HTTP listeners are not supported on the NLB</p><p>3. Which type of endpoint should be created for clients connecting to the AWS PrivateLink service? The correct choice is an interface endpoint as gateway endpoints are used for S3 and DynamoDB.</p><p>The architecture pattern described in this question is a service provider model using AWS PrivateLink. In this architecture a service provider VPC (VPC A in Account A) offers a service that is deployed behind an NLB. The consumer VPC (VPC B in Account B) consumes the service by creating an interface endpoint to the service exposed through PrivateLink.</p><p>An example of a similar deployment is provided in the image below:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_01-02-11-931976a4bf37ea7a5b73ebe21ec09eb8.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in VPC A that has a TCP listener. Add the principal ARN of account B to the service endpoints allow list" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create an interface endpoint in VPC B that points to the service identifier of the endpoint service in AWS account A" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in VPC A that has a HTTP listener. Add the principal ARN of account B to the service endpoints allow list" is incorrect.</p><p>A NLB should be created with a TCP listener as it is a Layer 4 load balancer. HTTP listeners can be created on ALBs.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in VPC A that has a HTTP listener. Add the principal ARN of account B to the service endpoints allow list" is incorrect.</p><p>An ALB cannot be used for PrivateLink, you must use an NLB instead.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a gateway endpoint in VPC B that points to the service identifier of the endpoint service in AWS account A" is incorrect.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/privatelink/features/">https://aws.amazon.com/privatelink/features/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in VPC A that has a HTTP listener. Add the principal ARN of account B to the service endpoints allow list.</p>', '<p>Create a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in VPC A that has a TCP listener. Add the principal ARN of account B to the service endpoints allow list.</p>', '<p>Create a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in VPC A that has a HTTP listener. Add the principal ARN of account B to the service endpoints allow list.</p>', '<p>Create a gateway endpoint in VPC B that points to the service identifier of the endpoint service in AWS account A.</p>', '<p>Create an interface endpoint in VPC B that points to the service identifier of the endpoint service in AWS account A.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'e'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company is deploying a service that runs on TCP port 80 in VPC A within AWS Account A. The company wants to provide access to the service to client EC2 instances in VPC B within AWS Account B. The service will be exposed using AWS PrivateLink.Which tasks should the network engineer complete to meet these requirements? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265746, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A manufacturing company is creating a RESTful API that uses AWS Lambda. Wholesale suppliers can use the API to access the latest pricing information for products. The information is confidential and should only be accessed using private IP addresses. All customers who use the API use Amazon VPCs.</p><p>How can the manufacturing company provision secure access to the API for customers?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Using Amazon API Gateway, you can create private REST APIs that can only be accessed from your virtual private cloud in Amazon VPC by using an interface VPC endpoint. This is an endpoint network interface that you create in your VPC. This will enable the customers to connect to the API from their VPCs using private IP addresses.</p><p>Lambda can be used as the backend for the API by configuring a Lambda proxy integration or a Lambda non-proxy integration.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Use an Amazon API Gateway API with a private API. Create interface VPC endpoints in customer VPCs to connect to the API" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use an Amazon API Gateway API with a regional API. Create interface VPC endpoints in customer VPCs to connect to the API" is incorrect.</p><p>A regional API is not a private API and does not use private IP addresses. Therefore, this answer is incorrect as it does not meet the security requirements of the solution.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Use a Network Load Balancer (NLB) as the front end to the API. Configure the Lambda function as a target for the NLB. Use PrivateLink to connect customer VPCs" is incorrect.</p><p>AWS Lambda is not a supported target for a Network Load Balancer, you must use an Application Load Balancer instead. Also, an ALB would not be a suitable front-end for an API.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy the Lambda function in a VPC within the manufacturer’s account. Use a VPC endpoint to connect from customer VPCs" is incorrect.</p><p>You can connect to an AWS Lambda function using a VPC endpoint. However, when using Lambda to process API requests you still need a front-end for the API such as API Gateway.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/apigateway-private-apis.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/apigateway-private-apis.html</a></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/getting-started-with-lambda-integration.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/getting-started-with-lambda-integration.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Use an Amazon API Gateway API with a private API. Create interface VPC endpoints in customer VPCs to connect to the API.</p>', '<p>Use an Amazon API Gateway API with a regional API. Create interface VPC endpoints in customer VPCs to connect to the API.</p>', '<p>Use a Network Load Balancer (NLB) as the front end to the API. Configure the Lambda function as a target for the NLB. Use PrivateLink to connect customer VPCs.</p>', '<p>Deploy the Lambda function in a VPC within the manufacturer’s account. Use a VPC endpoint to connect from customer VPCs.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A manufacturing company is creating a RESTful API that uses AWS Lambda. Wholesale suppliers can use the API to access the latest pricing information for products. The information is confidential and should only be accessed using private IP addresses. All customers who use the API use Amazon VPCs.How can the manufacturing company provision secure access to the API for customers?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265748, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application running in a private subnet needs outbound connectivity to an internet service using the IPv6 protocol. A network engineer has configured IPv6 for the Amazon VPC and the EC2 instances can communicate with each other over IPv6.</p><p>The network engineer needs to enable connectivity to the internet service. The network engineer must control which IP addresses the application can communicate with and ensure inbound connections from the internet cannot be initiated.</p><p>Which actions should the network engineer take to meet this requirement? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>IPv6 addresses are globally unique and are therefore public by default. If you want your instance to be able to access the internet, but you want to prevent resources on the internet from initiating communication with your instance, you can use an egress-only internet gateway.</p><p>To do this, create an egress-only internet gateway in your VPC, and then add a route to your route table that points all IPv6 traffic (::/0) or a specific range of IPv6 address to the egress-only internet gateway. IPv6 traffic in the subnet that\'s associated with the route table is routed to the egress-only internet gateway.</p><p>An egress-only internet gateway is stateful: it forwards traffic from the instances in the subnet to the internet or other AWS services, and then sends the response back to the instances.</p><p>An egress-only internet gateway has the following characteristics:</p><ul><li><p>You cannot associate a security group with an egress-only internet gateway. You can use security groups for your instances in the private subnet to control the traffic to and from those instances.</p></li><li><p>You can use a network ACL to control the traffic to and from the subnet for which the egress-only internet gateway routes traffic.</p></li></ul><p>Therefore, an egress-only internet gateway is the solution for enabling outbound-only IPv6 communications to the service on the internet. The network engineer can control which IP addresses the instances can communicate with using security groups attached to the instances.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Create an egress-only internet gateway" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Attach a security group to the EC2 instances" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a NAT gateway in a public subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>A NAT gateway is used for IPv4 traffic and cannot be used for IPv6 traffic.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Attach a security group to the egress-only internet gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot attach security groups to the egress-only internet gateway, they must be attached to the EC2 instances.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create an internet gateway in a private subnet" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot attach internet gateways to subnets, they are attached to VPCs. The routes to an internet gateway are then added to the route tables of public subnets. Instances require public IP addresses to use them.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/egress-only-internet-gateway.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/egress-only-internet-gateway.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Create an egress-only internet gateway.</p>', '<p>Attach a security group to the EC2 instances.</p>', '<p>Create a NAT gateway in a public subnet.</p>', '<p>Attach a security group to the egress-only internet gateway.</p>', '<p>Create an internet gateway in a private subnet.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'b'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'An application running in a private subnet needs outbound connectivity to an internet service using the IPv6 protocol. A network engineer has configured IPv6 for the Amazon VPC and the EC2 instances can communicate with each other over IPv6.The network engineer needs to enable connectivity to the internet service. The network engineer must control which IP addresses the application can communicate with and ensure inbound connections from the internet cannot be initiated.Which actions should the network engineer take to meet this requirement? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265750, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': "<p>A large company has migrated production workloads from several data centers into an Amazon VPC configured with the CIDR block 10.11.0.0/20. The company has nearly depleted the IP address space.</p><p>The company is planning to migrate more data center workloads and must extend the VPC by allocating an additional block of addresses.</p><p>Which CIDR blocks meet the company's requirements? (Select TWO.)</p>", 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The company has used up their address space and must add a secondary CIDR block to an existing VPC. This is allowed but with some restrictions. The following restrictions discount three of the available answers:</p><p>· If the primary CIDR block is a private address space (RFC 1918) you cannot associate a secondary CIDR from the other RFC 1918 ranges.</p><p>· The CIDR block must not overlap with any existing CIDR block that\'s associated with the VPC.</p><p>The following table provides an overview of permitted and restricted CIDR block associations, which depend on the IPv4 address range in which your VPC\'s primary CIDR block resides.</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_01-05-54-06c94800bfbe1b7e6e0d42701b1e254a.jpg"><p>From the table above we know that we cannot add any other RFC 1918 address ranges as the secondary CIDR block because the primary CIDR block is RFC 1918. Therefore, the 192.168.0.0/16 and 172.16.0.0/20 CIDR blocks would be restricted.</p><p>The 10.11.0.0/16 address ranges overlaps with the existing 10.11.0.0/20 address range.</p><p>The 10.1.0.0/20 and 10.12.0.0/20 CIDR blocks are both within the same RFC 1918 private address space and do not overlap with the existing primary CIDR block and are therefore permitted associations.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"10.1.0.0/20" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"10.12.0.0/20" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "172.16.0.0/20" is incorrect (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "10.11.0.0/16" is incorrect (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "192.168.0.0/16" is incorrect (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>10.1.0.0/20</p>', '<p>172.16.0.0/20</p>', '<p>10.12.0.0/20</p>', '<p>10.11.0.0/16</p>', '<p>192.168.0.0/16</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'c'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': "A large company has migrated production workloads from several data centers into an Amazon VPC configured with the CIDR block 10.11.0.0/20. The company has nearly depleted the IP address space.The company is planning to migrate more data center workloads and must extend the VPC by allocating an additional block of addresses.Which CIDR blocks meet the company's requirements? (Select TWO.)", 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265752, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs on Docker containers managed with Amazon ECS. Users must connect using TLS connections and security policy mandates that a single TLS connection must be made from the client through to the container. A network engineer must design a solution that supports load balancing to multiple containers and TCP pass through.</p><p>Which solution supports the security requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The Network Load Balancer is the best option for managing secure traffic as it provides support for TCP traffic pass through, without decrypting and then re-encrypting the traffic. Additionally, the Network Load Balancer supports target groups, which means port mapping can be used, as well as configuring the load balancer as part of the task definition for the containers.</p><p>The diagram below depicts an end-to-end encrypted session (left) where the TLS certificate is installed on the backend instance (or container):</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_01-08-33-fb01997efeae33f5d5e98fb62bc7f91e.jpg"><p>The Network Load Balancer integrates seamlessly with ECS providing end-to-end TLS communication across services without offloading or terminating the certificates. This gives you the ability to use dynamic ports in ECS containers. It can also handle tens of millions of requests per second while maintaining high throughput at ultra-low latency for applications that require the TCP protocol.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Deploy a Network Load Balancer with a TCP listener" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy a Network Load Balancer with a TLS listener" is incorrect.</p><p>With a TLS listener you must install a TLS certificate on the load balancer. This would be the architecture in the right-hand side of the above diagram and results in two encrypted connections.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy an Application Load Balancer with a HTTPS listener" is incorrect.</p><p>An ALB does not support TCP passthrough so you cannot have a single encrypted connection from client to instance/container.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Deploy an Application Load Balancer with a TLS listener" is incorrect.</p><p>ALBs do not support TLS listeners.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/compute/maintaining-transport-layer-security-all-the-way-to-your-container-using-the-network-load-balancer-with-amazon-ecs/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/compute/maintaining-transport-layer-security-all-the-way-to-your-container-using-the-network-load-balancer-with-amazon-ecs/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Deploy an Application Load Balancer with a HTTPS listener.</p>', '<p>Deploy a Network Load Balancer with a TCP listener.</p>', '<p>Deploy an Application Load Balancer with a TLS listener.</p>', '<p>Deploy a Network Load Balancer with a TLS listener.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'An application runs on Docker containers managed with Amazon ECS. Users must connect using TLS connections and security policy mandates that a single TLS connection must be made from the client through to the container. A network engineer must design a solution that supports load balancing to multiple containers and TCP pass through.Which solution supports the security requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265754, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An application runs in public and private subnets of an Amazon VPC. The application reads and writes to Amazon S3 buckets. A manager must determine the data transfer costs associated with traffic between the EC2 instances and the S3 buckets.</p><p>Which statements about data transfer costs are correct? (Select TWO.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>If an internet gateway is used to access the public endpoint of the AWS services in the same Region, there are no data transfer charges. If a NAT gateway is used to access the same services, there is a data processing charge (per gigabyte (GB)) for data that passes through the gateway.</p><p>Please refer to the reference link below for more information on data transfer charges.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"There are data processing charges for data transfer to S3 public endpoints in the same Region if the traffic passes through a NAT gateway" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"There are no charges for data transfer through an internet gateway to S3 public endpoints in the same Region" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "There are no charges for data transfer through an internet gateway to S3 public endpoints in any Region" is incorrect.</p><p>This is incorrect as you will be charged for transfer to S3 endpoints in other Regions.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "There are no charges for data transfer to S3 public endpoints in the same Region if the traffic passes through a NAT gateway" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not true, there are always data processing charges associated with NAT gateways.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "There are data transfer charges for all data sent to S3 public endpoints in all cases" is incorrect.</p><p>This is not true as you can send data through an internet gateway to S3 endpoints in the same Region without incurring costs.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/architecture/overview-of-data-transfer-costs-for-common-architectures/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/architecture/overview-of-data-transfer-costs-for-common-architectures/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>There are data processing charges for data transfer to S3 public endpoints in the same Region if the traffic passes through a NAT gateway.</p>', '<p>There are no charges for data transfer through an internet gateway to S3 public endpoints in any Region.</p>', '<p>There are no charges for data transfer to S3 public endpoints in the same Region if the traffic passes through a NAT gateway.</p>', '<p>There are data transfer charges for all data sent to S3 public endpoints in all cases.</p>', '<p>There are no charges for data transfer through an internet gateway to S3 public endpoints in the same Region.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a', 'e'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'An application runs in public and private subnets of an Amazon VPC. The application reads and writes to Amazon S3 buckets. A manager must determine the data transfer costs associated with traffic between the EC2 instances and the S3 buckets.Which statements about data transfer costs are correct? (Select TWO.)', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265756, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company has registered the domain names example.com and mydomain.com in Amazon Route 53. Websites for each domain name have been launched on Amazon EC2 instances across two Availability Zones. The EC2 instances for each website have been added to separate target groups. A network administrator has registered TLS certificates for each domain name in AWS Certificate Manager (ACM).</p><p>The network administrator must deploy a load balancing solution for the websites. Which solution will reduce administrative overhead and cost?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>The requirements are that the solution should be low cost and reduce administrative overhead. Therefore, if possible, a single load balancer should be used. This is indeed possible as you can import multiple ACM certificates to an ALB/NLB, and Server Name Indication (SNI) will be used to select the most appropriate certificate.</p><p>For this solution the two websites are running on different sets of instances within separate target groups. The requests will specify the domain names example.com and mydomain.com. To forward connections to the correct target group we can use host-based routing with an ALB. This configuration will cause all requests for a specific domain name to be forwarded to the appropriate target group.</p><p>The diagram below shows examples of host-based routing and path-based routing with an ALB:</p><img src="https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/practice_test_question_explanation/2023-02-07_01-10-50-ce28cf3a12fefc2bac3f1b56d6b38b8c.jpg"><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Launch an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Create a single HTTPS listener and import both certificates from ACM. Use host-based routing rules to forward connections to the appropriate target group" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Launch a Network Load Balancer (NLB). Create a single TLS listener and import both certificates from ACM. Use host-based routing rules to forward connections to the appropriate target group" is incorrect.</p><p>Host-based routing is not supported with an ALB.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Launch two Application Load Balancers (ALBs). Create a single HTTPS listener per ALB and import the relevant certificate from ACM. Attach the appropriate target group to each ALB" is incorrect.</p><p>This would be a more expensive solution in cost and administrative overhead.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Launch two Network Load Balancers (NLBs). Create a single TLS listener per NLB and import the relevant certificate from ACM. Attach the appropriate target group to each NLB" is incorrect.</p><p>As with the previous incorrect answer, this would be more costly than the correct solution.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/new-application-load-balancer-sni/">https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/new-application-load-balancer-sni/</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Launch an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Create a single HTTPS listener and import both certificates from ACM. Use host-based routing rules to forward connections to the appropriate target group.</p>', '<p>Launch a Network Load Balancer (NLB). Create a single TLS listener and import both certificates from ACM. Use host-based routing rules to forward connections to the appropriate target group.</p>', '<p>Launch two Application Load Balancers (ALBs). Create a single HTTPS listener per ALB and import the relevant certificate from ACM. Attach the appropriate target group to each ALB.</p>', '<p>Launch two Network Load Balancers (NLBs). Create a single TLS listener per NLB and import the relevant certificate from ACM. Attach the appropriate target group to each NLB.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'A company has registered the domain names example.com and mydomain.com in Amazon Route 53. Websites for each domain name have been launched on Amazon EC2 instances across two Availability Zones. The EC2 instances for each website have been added to separate target groups. A network administrator has registered TLS certificates for each domain name in AWS Certificate Manager (ACM).The network administrator must deploy a load balancing solution for the websites. Which solution will reduce administrative overhead and cost?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265758, 'assessment_type': 'multiple-choice', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>A company requires an AWS Direct Connect connection from an on-premises data center. The port speed of the connection should be 500 Mbps.</p><p>Which procedure will provide the BEST solution to the requirements?</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>1Gbps and 10Gbps ports are available for creating through the AWS Management Console, API or CLI. Speeds of 50Mbps, 100Mbps, 200Mbps, 300Mbps, 400Mbps, and 500Mbps can be ordered from any APN partners supporting AWS Direct Connect.</p><p>There are two types of connections:</p><ul><li><p>Dedicated Connection: A physical Ethernet connection associated with a single customer. Customers can request a dedicated connection through the AWS Direct Connect console, the CLI, or the API.</p></li><li><p>Hosted Connection: A physical Ethernet connection that an AWS Direct Connect Partner provisions on behalf of a customer. Customers request a hosted connection by contacting a partner in the AWS Direct Connect Partner Program, who provisions the connection.</p></li></ul><p>Therefore, a hosted connection is required when working with an APN Partner to deliver a sub-1 Gbps connection.</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"Contact an APN Partner to order a hosted connection" is the correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a dedicated connection through the CLI or API" is incorrect.</p><p>A dedicated connection cannot be created for sub-1 Gbps. A hosted connection is required.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Submit the request to an AWS Technical Account Manager" is incorrect.</p><p>You cannot submit a request for an AWS Direct Connect connection to an AWS TAM.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "Create a 1 Gbps connection using the AWS Management Console" is incorrect.</p><p>The company requires a 500 Mbps connection which is entirely possible by contacting an APN Partner. Therefore, there is no need to compromise and pay more for a 1 Gbps connection.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithConnections.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithConnections.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>Contact an APN Partner to order a hosted connection.</p>', '<p>Create a dedicated connection through the CLI or API.</p>', '<p>Submit the request to an AWS Technical Account Manager.</p>', '<p>Create a 1 Gbps connection using the AWS Management Console.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['a'], 'section': 'Domain 1: Network Design', 'question_plain': 'A company requires an AWS Direct Connect connection from an on-premises data center. The port speed of the connection should be 500 Mbps.Which procedure will provide the BEST solution to the requirements?', 'related_lectures': []}, {'_class': 'assessment', 'id': 70265760, 'assessment_type': 'multi-select', 'prompt': {'question': '<p>An Amazon Route 53 public hosted zone has been created for example.com. A network engineer must create DNS records that point to AWS resources. IP address changes should not affect DNS resolution. The network engineer plans to use Alias records.</p><p>Which AWS services can Alias records point to? (Select THREE.)</p>', 'relatedLectureIds': '', 'feedbacks': ['', '', '', '', '', ''], 'explanation': '<p>Amazon Route 53 <em>alias records</em> provide a Route 53–specific extension to DNS functionality. Alias records let you route traffic to selected AWS resources, such as CloudFront distributions and Amazon S3 buckets. They also let you route traffic from one record in a hosted zone to another record. An alias maps to the AWS DNS name of a service so if the IP address changes, this will not affect DNS resolution.</p><p>When Route 53 receives a DNS query for an alias record, Route 53 responds with the applicable value for that resource:</p><ul><li><p><strong>An Amazon API Gateway custom regional API or edge-optimized API</strong> – Route 53 responds with one or more IP addresses for your API.</p></li><li><p><strong>An Amazon VPC interface endpoint</strong> – Route 53 responds with one or more IP addresses for your interface endpoint.</p></li><li><p><strong>A CloudFront distribution</strong> – Route 53 responds with one or more IP addresses for CloudFront edge servers that can serve your content.</p></li><li><p><strong>An Elastic Beanstalk environment</strong> – Route 53 responds with one or more IP addresses for the environment.</p></li><li><p><strong>An ELB load balancer</strong> – Route 53 responds with one or more IP addresses for the load balancer.</p></li><li><p><strong>An AWS Global Accelerator accelerator</strong> – Route 53 responds with one of the two IP addresses for the accelerator.</p></li><li><p><strong>An Amazon S3 bucket that is configured as a static website</strong> – Route 53 responds with one IP address for the Amazon S3 bucket.</p></li><li><p><strong>Another Route 53 record in the same hosted zone</strong> – Route 53 responds as if the query is for the record that is referenced by the alias record.</p></li></ul><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"An Amazon VPC interface endpoint" is a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"An Amazon CloudFront distribution" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>CORRECT: </strong>"An Application Load Balancer" is also a correct answer (as explained above.)</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "An Amazon EC2 instance" is incorrect. You cannot point an alias record to an EC2 instance.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "An AWS Fargate container" is incorrect. You cannot point an alias record to an AWS Fargate container.</p><p><strong>INCORRECT:</strong> "An Amazon DynamoDB table" is incorrect. You cannot point an alias record to an Amazon DynamoDB table.</p><p><strong>References:</strong></p><p><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resource-record-sets-choosing-alias-non-alias.html">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resource-record-sets-choosing-alias-non-alias.html</a></p>', 'answers': ['<p>An Amazon EC2 instance.</p>', '<p>An Amazon VPC interface endpoint.</p>', '<p>An Amazon CloudFront distribution.</p>', '<p>An AWS Fargate container.</p>', '<p>An Amazon DynamoDB table.</p>', '<p>An Application Load Balancer.</p>']}, 'correct_response': ['b', 'c', 'f'], 'section': 'Domain 2: Network Implementation', 'question_plain': 'An Amazon Route 53 public hosted zone has been created for example.com. A network engineer must create DNS records that point to AWS resources. IP address changes should not affect DNS resolution. The network engineer plans to use Alias records.Which AWS services can Alias records point to? (Select THREE.)', 'related_lectures': []}]}
